old_content: The earliest archaeological evidence of lost wax casting in China was found in the sixth century BC. The Cemetery of Chu State in Xichuan, Henan Province.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lawton |first1=Thomas |title=New Perspectives on Chu Culture During the Eastern Zhou Period}}</ref> Bronze Jin, cast using traditional piece-mold techniques, is further embellished by adding prefabricated ornate open worked handles, which are produced through a [[Lost-wax casting|lost wax process]] and then attached. Lost wax was eventually introduced to China from the ancient Near East as far west as possible, and the process has an early and long history in the region, but exactly when and how it was introduced is unclear. The dewaxing process is more suitable for casting decorations with deep undercuts and openwork designs than the molding process, which complicates the removal of molded parts from the model. Although lost-wax casting was never used to make large vessels, it became more and more popular in the late Eastern Zhou Dynasty and the Qin and Han Dynasties. The lost-wax casting process for casting small parts was more economical than the mold-making process because the amount of metal used was easier to control.

old_content: The '''[[2020–21 in Scottish football|2020–21 season]]''' was [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]'s 132nd season of competitive football. They competed in the [[2020–21 Scottish Premiership|Scottish Premiership]], [[2020–21 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]], [[2020–21 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]], [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] and [[2020–21 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]]. The club failed to win a trophy for first time since 2010.

name=":22" /><ref name=":27" /> The Healthy Body Image Program is an online platform intended to screen and deliver tailored interventions to students on campuses.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wilfley DE, Agras WS, Taylor CB | title = Reducing the burden of eating disorders: a model for population-based prevention and treatment for university and college campuses | journal = The International Journal of Eating Disorders | volume = 46 | issue = 5 | pages = 529–32 | date = July 2013 | pmid = 23658106 | pmc = 3703768 | doi = 10.1002/eat.22117 }}</ref> The program labels students as low- or high-risk, or identifies those with a possible clinical/subclinical eating disorder.<ref name="A screening tool for detecting eati">{{cite journal | vauthors = Graham AK, Trockel M, Weisman H, Fitzsimmons-Craft EE, Balantekin KN, Wilfley DE, Taylor CB | title = A screening tool for detecting eating disorder risk and diagnostic symptoms among college-age women | journal = Journal of American College Health | volume = 67 | issue = 4 | pages = 357–366 | date = 2019-05-19 | pmid = 29979922 | pmc = 6320726 | doi = 10.1080/07448481.2018.1483936 }}</ref> It subsequently offers suitable evidence-based online interventions or a referral to a specialized physician in order to address risks and clinical status.<ref name="A screening tool for detecting eati" /> Educational campaigns intended to deliver factual knowledge regarding eating disorders and helpful resources have proven to be most successful when targeting students.<ref name=":22" /> Although many colleges in the United States offer annual or bi-annual education programs, very few do so on a monthly or weekly basis, which can impact students’ ability to access proper services.<ref name=":22" /> Efficacy of treatments are also reported when there is an emphasis on holistic health and interactive components.<ref name=":27" /> Increasing media literacy, specifically concerning distorted media representation of body image, and promoting body satisfaction can improve management skills and encourage positive relationship building.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Stice E, Shaw H, Marti CN | title = A meta-analytic review of eating disorder prevention programs: encouraging findings | journal = Annual Review of Clinical Psychology | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | pages = 207–31 | date = April 2007 | pmid = 17716054 | doi = 10.1146/annurev.clinpsy.3.022806.091447 }}</ref> Interventions that aid students in recognizing risk factors, such as sociocultural pressure for certain body types, body dissatisfaction, poor = 17165018 | title = Eating disorder diagnostic scale: additional evidence of reliability and validity | journal = Psychological Assessment | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | pages = 60–71 | date = March 2004 | pmid = 15023093 | doi = 10.1037/1040-3590.16.1.60 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Yager Z, O'Dea JA | title = Prevention programs for body image and eating disorders on University 10.1093/heapro/dan004 | doi-access = free }}</ref> Additionally, interventions that promote weight control through healthy dietary techniques, utilize persuasion principles (e.g. foot-in-the-door method), and include motivational enhancement exercises have been reported to improve weight gain and functional impairment.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Yager Z, O'Dea J | title = A controlled intervention to promote a healthy body image, reduce eating disorder risk and prevent excessive exercise among trainee health education and physical education teachers | journal = Health Education old_content: Shortly before reaching the islands of [[Guadeloupe]] and [[Dominica]] on November 8, the fleet came upon two English ships that fled when they spied the Spanish. While Admiral Guzman was chasing one of them, Admiral Alonso pursued the other ship, ''Francis''. After several exchanges of cannonfire, de Canço attacked the enemy ship and captured all 26 sailors aboard.<ref>Maynarde 1849, p. 48</ref><ref name="Casariego1953">{{cite book|author=Jesús Evaristo Casariego|author-link=Jesús Evaristo Casariego Fernández-Noriega|title=Mares y veleros de España|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kJMKAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Cancio%22|year=1953|publisher=Navío y Corcel|page=60}}</ref> Sailing orders found aboard it revealed that the fleet of 27 ships with 2,500 men aboard, and commanded by [[John Hawkins (naval commander)|John Hawkins]] and [[Francis Drake]], was sitting in Guadeloupe, preparing its landing boats for an assault on the island of Puerto Rico and its treasure.<ref name="Wernham1994">{{cite book|author=R. B. Wernham|title=The Return of the Armadas : The Last Years of the Elizabethan War against Spain 1595–1603: The Last Years of the Elizabethan War against Spain 1595–1603|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mapur4SwDiAC&pg=PA49|date= 1994|publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn=978-0191591747|page=49}}</ref> Alarmed by this revelation, de Canço fired four cannon shots to alert one of his boats, which was in pursuit of another English ship, to go as soon as possible to warn Puerto Rico of the danger.

Wernham|title=The Return of the Armadas : The Last Years of the Elizabethan War against Spain 1595–1603: The Last Years of the Elizabethan War against Spain 1595–1603|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mapur4SwDiAC&pg=PA49|date= 1994|publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn=978-0191591747|page=49}}</ref> Alarmed by this revelation, de Canço fired four cannon shots to alert one of his boats, which was in pursuit of another English ship, to go as soon as possible to warn Puerto Rico of the danger.

old_content: The details of the internal affairs of his reign are sparse. Beyond the length of his reign, all [[Michael Panaretos]] relates explicitly about George is the cryptic statement that he "was treacherously betrayed by his officials on the mountain of Taurezion and taken captive in June [of 1280]".<ref>Panretos, ''Chronicle'', 4; translated in A. Bryer, "The Fate of George Komnenos, Ruler of Trebizond (1266–1280)," ''[[Byzantinische Zeitschrift]]'' '''66''' (1973), p. 333</ref> Although three different Armenian chronicles state he was killed by [[Abaqa Khan]] of the [[Ilkhan]], along with the [[atabeg]] of [[Lori Province|Lori]],<ref>Bryer, "The Fate of George Komnenos", pp. 343-345</ref> he was very much alive in 1284 when he returned to Trebizond and attempted to recover his throne during the reign of his brother [[John II of Trebizond|John II]], when Panaretos states he was known as "the Wanderer".<ref>Panretos, ''Chronicle'', 5; translated in Bryer, "The Fate of George Komnenos", p. 333</ref>
new_content: The details of the internal affairs of his reign are sparse. Beyond the length of his reign, all [[Michael Panaretos]] relates explicitly about George is the cryptic statement that he "was treacherously betrayed by his officials on the mountain of Taurezion and taken captive in June [of 1280]".<ref>Panretos, ''Chronicle'', 5; translated in Scott Kennedy, ''Two works on Trebizond'' (Cambridge: Dumbarton Oaks Medieval Library, 2019), p. 5</ref> Although three different Armenian chronicles state he was killed by [[Abaqa Khan]] of the [[Ilkhan]], along with the [[atabeg]] of [[Lori Province|Lori]],<ref>A. Bryer, "The Fate of George Komnenos, Ruler of Trebizond (1266–1280)," ''[[Byzantinische Zeitschrift]]'' '''66''' (1973), pp. 343-345</ref> he was very much alive in 1284 when he returned to Trebizond and attempted to recover his throne during the reign of his brother [[John II of Trebizond|John II]], when Panaretos states he was known as "the Vagabond".<ref>Panretos, ''Chronicle'', 8; translated in Kennedy, ''Two Works'', p. 7</ref>

old_content: Ricardo Jorge Mollo was born in the [[Pergamino]] neighbourhood of [[Buenos Aires, Argentina]] on 17 August, 1957, but moved to [[El Palomar]] early in his life. He is the younger brother of [[:es:Omar Mollo|Omar Mollo]], who would be later on a co-founder of the Argentine hard rock band [[:es:MAM (banda)|MAM]], and taught Mollo his first chords when they lived in El Palomar.
new_content: Ricardo Jorge Mollo was born in the [[Pergamino]] neighbourhood of [[Buenos Aires, Argentina]] on 17 August, 1957, but moved to [[El Palomar, Buenos Aires|El Palomar]] early in his life. He is the younger brother of [[:es:Omar Mollo|Omar Mollo]], who would be later on a co-founder of the Argentine hard rock band [[:es:MAM (banda)|MAM]], and taught Mollo his first chords when they lived in El Palomar.

old_content: '''Myth''' is a [[genre]] of [[folklore]] or [[theology]] consisting primarily of [[narrative]]s that play a fundamental role in a society, such as foundational tales or [[origin myth]]s. For folklorists, historians, philosophers or theologians this is very different from the vernacular usage of the term "myth" that simply refers to something that is not true. Instead, the truth value of a myth is not a defining criterion.<ref>Deretic, Irina. “Why are myths true: Plato on the veracity of myths.” Vestnik of Saint Petersburg University. Philosophy and Conflict Studies (2020): vol. 36, issue 3, pp. 441–451.</ref>
new_content: '''Myth''' is a [[genre]] of [[folklore]] or [[theology]] consisting primarily of [[narrative]]s that play a fundamental role in a society, such as foundational tales or [[origin myth]]s. For scholars, this is very different from the vernacular usage of the term "myth" that simply refers to something that is not true. Instead, the truth value of a myth is not a defining criterion.<ref>Deretic, Irina. “Why are myths true: Plato on the veracity of myths.” Vestnik of Saint Petersburg University. Philosophy and Conflict Studies (2020): vol. 36, issue 3, pp. 441–451.</ref>

old_content: The '''2025 FIFA Futsal Women's World Cup''' is the planned inaugural edition of the [[FIFA Futsal Women's World Cup]], an international [[futsal]] competition organized by [[FIFA]]. The inaugural edition is to be hosted in the [[Philippines]] in 2025.<ref name="FIFA-2024-05-15a">{{cite press release |date=May 15, 2024 |title=FIFA Council approves Women's International Match Calendar 2026-2029 |url=https://inside.fifa.com/about-fifa/organisation/fifa-council/media-releases/fifa-council-approves-womens-international-match-calendar-2026-2029 |publisher=[[FIFA]] |accessdate=May 15, 2024}}</ref><ref name="FIFA-2024-05-15b">{{cite news |date=May 15, 2024 |title=Everything you need to know about the FIFA Futsal Women's World Cup |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/news/articles/futsal-womens-world-cup-info-details |accessdate=May 15, 2024 |publisher=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Terrado |first1=Reuben |date=15 May 2024 |title=Philippines to host first FIFA Futsal Women's World Cup in 2025 |url=https://www.spin.ph/football/philippines-to-host-first-fifa-futsal-women-s-world-cup-in-2025-a795-20240515 |access-date=15 May 2024 |work=Sports Interactive Network Philippines |language=en}}</ref>  This will be the first time the Philippines hosts a FIFA event, the second FIFA women's tournament in Southeast Asia since the [[2004 FIFA U-19 Women's World Championship]] in Thailand, and the second futsal World Cup in the region after the [[2012 FIFA Futsal World Cup|2012 FIFA Futsal World Cup.]]
new_content: The '''2025 FIFA Futsal Women's World Cup''' is the planned inaugural edition of the [[FIFA Futsal Women's World Cup]], an international [[futsal]] competition organized by [[FIFA]]. old_content: Jaan'nisar features Junaid Khan, a young and bright police officer who is gifted with exemplary skills in the line of duty.  Played by the talented [[Sohail Sameer]], Inspector Junaid is a very honest and capable police officer but the police station he is posted in has witnessed huge rise in the number of kidnapping, robberies, thefts, murders, domestic violence, drugs and other heinous crimes. Many crimes are not reported to police. Junaid equips the police station on modern lines and introduces such reforms in police culture that rapidly decrease crime rate in the area. He strengthens forensic investigation to nab the perpetrators of heinous crimes on scientific lines. From laying hands on circumstantial evidence to weighing the related factors and scientifically examining the proofs, Junaid discharges his responsibilities with utmost devotion, zeal, courage and commitment.

old_content: The film's story revolves around two individuals: an orphaned Hawaiian girl named [[Stich]], who is raised by her older sister, [[List of Lilo & Stitch characters#Nani Pelekai|Nani]], after their parents' deaths, and the [[Extraterrestrials in fiction|extraterrestrial creature]] [[Lilo (Lilo & Stitch)|Experiment 626]], who is adopted by stich as her "dog" and renamed "Lilo". Lilo, who was genetically engineered to cause chaos and destruction, initially uses Stitch to avoid recapture by the intergalactic federation. They develop a close bond through the Hawaiian concept of [[Ohana|''{{okina}}ohana'']], or [[extended family]], causing Stitch to reconsider his intended destructive purpose in order to keep his newfound family together.
new_content: The film's story revolves around two individuals: an orphaned Hawaiian girl named [[Lilo Pelekai]], who is raised by her older sister, [[List of Lilo & Stitch characters#Nani Pelekai|Nani]], after their parents' deaths, and the [[Extraterrestrials in fiction|extraterrestrial creature]] [[Stitch (Lilo & Stitch)|Experiment 626]], who is adopted by Lilo as her "dog" and renamed "Stitch". Stitch, who was genetically engineered to cause chaos and destruction, initially uses Lilo to avoid recapture by the intergalactic federation. They develop a close bond through the Hawaiian concept of [[Ohana|''{{okina}}ohana'']], or [[extended family]], causing Stitch to reconsider his intended destructive purpose in order to keep his newfound family together.

old_content: As the first President of the Republic, Ståhlberg had to form various presidential precedents and interpretations of how the office of President should be conducted. His term in office was also marked by a succession of short-lived governments. During his time as president, Ståhlberg nominated and appointed eight governments. These were mostly coalitions of the Agrarians and the National Progressive, National Coalition and Swedish People's parties, although Ståhlberg also appointed two caretaker governments.  Importantly, Ståhlberg generally supported all the governments that he nominated, although he also sometimes disagreed with them.
new_content: As the first President of the Republic, Ståhlberg had to form various presidential precedents and interpretations of how the office of President should be conducted. His term in office was also marked by a succession of short-lived governments. During his time as president, Ståhlberg nominated and appointed eight governments. These were mostly coalitions of the Agrarians and the National Progressive, National Coalition and Swedish People's parties, although Ståhlberg also appointed two caretaker governments. Importantly, Ståhlberg generally supported all the governments that he nominated, although he also sometimes disagreed with them.

old_content: In 1854, his mother married Oliver Barnes and in 1855 his family moved to [[Berea, Ohio]], where while traveling for Fletcher Hulet,<ref name=Atwater /> he was able to study [[mathematics]] intermittently and Newton's ''[[Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica|Principia]]''<ref name=Atwater>{{cite book|pages=562–565|title=History of the city of Minneapolis, Minnesota|publisher=Munsell|author=Atwater, Isaac|year=1893|volume=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rj4VAAAAYAAJ}}</ref><ref name=Abbe>{{cite news|author=Abbe, Mary|title=Art lover T.B. Walker: Where it all began|date=9 April 2005|url=http://www.startribune.com/1375/story/33833.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20070726111749/http://www.startribune.com/1375/story/33833.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 July 2007|work=Star Tribune|publisher=Avista Capital Partners|accessdate=2007-11-02}}</ref> at [[Baldwin-Wallace College|Baldwin University]]. When he finished college at age 19, he filled a contract in [[Paris, Illinois]] for railroad ties. He then taught school and then became a traveling salesman of grindstones.<ref name=Cyclopaedia /> He is remembered as a man of "strong opinions" who would not eat [[grapefruit]] and who slept with a pistol under his pillow.<ref name=Madison /> His brother Platt Bayless Walker II founded ''Mississippi Valley Lumberman'', a magazine.<ref name=MNHS /> He had another brother and two sisters: Oliver W. Barnes, Adelaide B. Walker, and Helen M. Walker.<ref name=MNHS />

old_content: The [[Cynicism (philosophy)|Cynics]] were influenced by Heraclitus, such as by his condemnation of the mystery cults.<ref name=kyon/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JL-cyJ6zdJwC|title=The Cynics: The Cynic Movement in Antiquity and Its Legacy |first1=Robert Bracht|last1=Branham|first2=Marie-Odile|last2=Goulet-Cazé|date=June 7, 1996|publisher=University of California Press |isbn=9780520204492 |via=Google Books}}</ref>{{efn|name=myste}} Heraclitus is sometimes even depicted as a cynic. According to one source, "the Cynic affinity with Heraclitus lies not so much in his philosophy as in his cultural criticism and (idealised) lifestyle."<ref>Bosman, P. R. “TRACES OF CYNIC MONOTHEISM IN THE EARLY ROMAN EMPIRE.” ''Acta Classica'', vol. 51, 2008, pp. 1–20. ''JSTOR'', {{JSTOR|24592647}}. Accessed 2 Jan. 2024.</ref> The Cynics attributed several of the later [[Cynic epistles]] to his authorship.<ref>J. F. Kindstrand, “The Cynics and Heraclitus”, Eranos 82 (1984), 149–78</ref> Heraclitus wrote: "Dogs bark at every one they do not know."{{efn|{{harvnb|B97}}}} Similarly, [[Diogenes|Diogenes the Cynic]], when asked by [[Alexander the Great|Alexander]] why he considered himself a dog, responded that he "barks at those who give me nothing".<ref>Diogenes Laertius Book 6</ref><ref>The Philosophy of Cynicism, Luis Navia, p. 27</ref>

old_content: On June 6, 2021, the Tigers selected Foley's contract and promoted him to the major leagues for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/tigers/2021/06/tigers-cut-jacoby-jones-call-up-rookie-pitcher-amid-flurry-of-moves.html|title=Tigers cut JaCoby Jones, call up rookie pitcher amid flurry of moves|author=Evan Woodbery|date=June 6, 2021|website=[[MLive]]|access-date=June 6, 2021}}</ref> At the time of his promotion, Foley had a 3.60 ERA, 1.40 WHIP, and ten strikeouts in nine appearances (ten innings pitched) with the [[Toledo Mud Hens]]. old_content: The climate is of the temperate Mediterranean type, with the amount of rainfall increasing considerably and progressively from north to south. In the Santiago area, the average monthly temperatures are about {{Convert|30|C||abbr=}} in the summer months of January and February and {{Convert|15|C||abbr=}} in the winter months of June and July. The average monthly precipitation is no more than a trace in January and February and {{Convert|69.7|mm}} in June and July. By contrast, in Concepción the average monthly temperatures are somewhat lower in the summer at {{Convert|17.6|C}} but higher in the winter at {{Convert|9.3|C}}, and the amount of rain is much greater. In the summer, [[Concepción, Chile|Concepción]] receives an average of twenty millimeters of rain per month; in June and July, the city is pounded by an average of {{Convert|253|mm}} per month. The numerous rivers greatly increase their flow as a result of the winter rains and the spring melting of the Andean snows, and they contract considerably in the summer. The combination of abundant snow in the Andes and relatively moderate winter temperatures creates excellent conditions for Alpine skiing.

By contrast, in Concepción the average monthly temperatures are somewhat lower in the summer at {{Convert|17.6|C}} but higher in the winter at {{Convert|9.3|C}}, and the amount of rain is much greater. In the summer, [[Concepción, Chile|Concepción]] receives an average of twenty millimeters of rain per month; in June and July, the city is pounded by an average of {{Convert|253|mm}} per month. The numerous rivers greatly increase their flow as a result of the winter rains and the spring melting of the Andean snows, and they contract considerably in the summer. The combination of abundant snow in the Andes and relatively moderate winter temperatures creates excellent conditions for Alpine skiing.

old_content: The re-formed band released ''[[Power (Kansas album)|Power]]'' in November 1986.<ref name="Larkin"/> The first single, "[[All I Wanted (Kansas song)|All I Wanted]]", became the last Kansas single to hit the ''Billboard'' Top 40 chart, peaking at No. 19.<ref name="The Great Rock Discography" /> It also received considerable airplay on MTV. Two more singles, the title track and "Can't Cry Anymore", were less successful, "Power" hitting the lower end of the Hot 100 and getting substantial play and charting on the Rock Charts, but "Can't Cry Anymore" receiving little airplay despite a clever music video.
new_content: The re-formed band released ''[[Power (Kansas album)|Power]]'' on October 28, 1986.<ref name="Larkin"/> The first single, "[[All I Wanted (Kansas song)|All I Wanted]]", became the last Kansas single to hit the ''Billboard'' Top 40 chart, reaching #19.  It made the Top 10 on Billboard's Album Rock Tracks and received considerable airplay on MTV. Two more singles, the title track and "Can't Cry Anymore", were less successful, "Power" hitting the lower end of the Hot 100 and getting substantial play and charting on the Rock Charts, but "Can't Cry Anymore" receiving little airplay despite a clever music video.  The album sold approximately 400,000 copies.

old_content: The pirates obtain most of their weapons from [[Yemen]], but a significant number are sourced from [[Mogadishu]], Somalia's capital. Weapons dealers in the capital receive a deposit from a ''[[hawala]]'' dealer on behalf of the pirates and the weapons are then driven to [[Puntland]], where the pirates pay the balance.<ref name="Pirates high life"/> Various photographs of pirates in situ indicate that their weapons are predominantly [[AK-47]], [[AKM]], [[Type 56 assault rifle|Type 56]], [[RPK]], [[PK machine gun#PKM|PKM]], [[RPG-7]], and [[Tokarev pistol]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/devon/7791236.stm|title=Somali pirates killed 'legally'|work=BBC News |date=19 December 2008|access-date=27 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pflanz|first=Mike|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/piracy/4238924/Cargo-ship-escapes-Somali-pirates.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220112/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/piracy/4238924/Cargo-ship-escapes-Somali-pirates.html |archive-date=12 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Cargo ship escapes Somali pirates|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=14 January 2009|access-date=27 March 2009|location=London}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Additionally, given the particular origin of their weaponry, they are likely to have [[hand grenade]]s such as the [[RGD-5]] or [[F1 grenade (Russia)|F1]].

old_content: The observatory project was related to the precise calculation of the calendar; two different [[astronomical tables]] ({{transl|ar|[[zij]]}}) were in use in Egypt at the time, one calculated in the 9th century by [[al-Khwarizmi]] and the other in the early 11th century by [[Ibn Yunus]], on behalf of the Fatimid caliph [[Al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah|al-Hakim]] ({{reign|996|1021}}). The two were not in agreement, and furthermore both had drifted from actual observations. The construction of an observatory south of Cairo had already begun in 1012, but abandoned thereafter.{{sfn|Halm|2014|p=136}} Work began in 1119 on a hill south of the cemetary of [[al-Qarafa]], where the small 'Mosque of the Elephant' was located. The affair turned into a fiasco: costs skyrocketed, especially for the large, and difficult to cast, bronze rings used for observations. Even when the latter were successfully cast and installed, it turned out that the [[Muqattam Hills]] actually blocked the view of the sun during sunrise; the whole apparatus had to be transported to a new site on the Muqattam itself.{{sfn|Halm|2014|pp=135–138}} Several scholars were involved with the project, including the [[al-Andalus|Andalusi]] [[Abu Ja'far ibn Hasday]], the {{transl|ar|[[qadi]]}} and geometer Ibn Abi'l-Ish of [[Tarabulus|Tripoli]],<!-- this is deliberate, it is not clear which Tripoli he came from --> the instrument-maker Abu'l-Naja ibn Sind of [[Alexandria]], and the geometer Abu Muhammad Abd al-Karim of [[Sicily]].{{sfn|Dunlop|1960|p=1091}} Construction was interrupted by al-Afdal's death in 1121, and when al-Bata'ihi, upon being appointed to the vizierate, ordered it resumed, the apparatus was laboriously moved to the [[Bab al-Nasr (Cairo)|Bab al-Nasr]] gate.{{sfn|Halm|2014|p=138}} This too would remain unfinished: after al-Bata'ihi's downfall in 1125, Caliph al-Amir ordered the materials dismantled and the workers and scholars dispersed.{{sfn|Dunlop|1960|p=1091}}{{sfn|Halm|2014|p=138}}

The two were not in agreement, and furthermore both had drifted from actual observations. old_content: The [[Dinka]] and [[Nuer people|Nuer]] are the two largest ethnic groups in South Sudan. Conflict over pastures and cattle raids has been happening between these two ethnic groups as they battle for grazing their animals. In 1983, there was a civil war between Southern and Northern Sudan, and Southern Sudan was forced into the lower Region, where there was less resources. These Effects created conflict between the Dinka and Nuer people in South Sudan.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Conflict between Dinka and Nuer in South Sudan {{!}} Climate-Diplomacy |url=https://climate-diplomacy.org/case-studies/conflict-between-dinka-and-nuer-south-sudan |access-date=2022-05-26 |website=climate-diplomacy.org |language=en}}</ref>

old_content: Principal photography on the production was completed in February 2022. It was confirmed that [[Owen Teague]] and [[Marin Ireland]] had been added to the cast and that Endeavor Content and WME Independent were selling distribution rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2022/02/anne-hathaway-thomasin-mckenzie-thriller-eileen-launches-sales-at-efm-via-endeavor-content-wme-independent-1234927173/|title=Anne Hathaway & Thomasin McKenzie Thriller 'Eileen' Launches Sales At EFM Via Endeavor Content & WME Independent|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=February 4, 2022|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=January 22, 2023|archive-date=January 22, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230122163803/https://deadline.com/2022/02/anne-hathaway-thomasin-mckenzie-thriller-eileen-launches-sales-at-efm-via-endeavor-content-wme-independent-1234927173/|url-status=live}}</ref> Author of the novel and the screenplay Moshfegh was quoted as saying it was "a very faithful adaptation of the tone" of her original work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en/article/7k8ppg/ottessa-moshfegh-interview|title=The macabre mind of Ottessa Moshfegh|last=Pierce|first=Barry|date=June 17, 2022|website=[[i-D]]|publisher=[[Vice Media]]|access-date=January 22, 2023|archive-date=January 22, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230122073103/https://i-d.vice.com/en/article/7k8ppg/ottessa-moshfegh-interview|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2022, she confirmed the edit was locked-in and said that McKenzie as Eileen was "amazing. It's like she was born to play that role, she's just so exciting to watch. And Anne Hathaway plays Rebecca, the sort of femme fatale character. I mean, we're watching it again today and the first cut of it, I was like, 'This is so much better than my book.' So the movie is really satisfying, I'm excited about that."<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/books/ottessa-moshfegh-interview-lapvona-trailer/|title=The evolution of Ottessa Moshfegh|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|date=June 13, 2022|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=January 22, 2023|archive-date=November 4, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221104211452/https://ew.com/books/ottessa-moshfegh-interview-lapvona-trailer/|url-status=live}}</ref> Moshfegh said bringing her writer husband Luke Goebel into the script writing process made the script better because he was able to add another perspective to the story. They began writing drafts during the height of the [[COVID-19]] lockdown in 2020 and avoiding seasonal wildfires from Oregon to Pasadena to Palm Springs with Moshfegh saying to ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', "There was a sense of looming danger haunting us, which actually really helped the writing process." Hathaway described the project as "''[[Carol (film)|Carol]]'' meets ''[[Reservoir Dogs]]''".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2023/01/eileen-ottessa-moshfegh-anne-hathaway-sundance-first-look/|title=Inside ''Eileen'', a Gorgeously Strange Ottessa Moshfegh Adaptation|last=Canfield|first=David|date=January 19, 2023|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|access-date=January 22, 2023|archive-date=January 22, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230122224042/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2023/01/eileen-ottessa-moshfegh-anne-hathaway-sundance-first-look|url-status=live}}</ref>

old_content: He was the son of Robert Radford, and Thomasina Wyke of [[Oakford, Devon|Oakford]], Devon.<ref>Woodger</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=The Murder of Nicholas Radford |url=https://www.dartmoorresource.org.uk/the-murder-of-nicholas-radford/ |access-date=2023-03-17 |website=Dartmoor Resource |language=en-GB}}</ref> According to [[Tristram Risdon|Risdon]] (d.1640), he was a descendant of the ''de Radford'' family of the estate of Radford, in the parish of [[Winkleigh]], Devon, who had changed their name from ''de Bickly'', after Robert de Bickly, son of Ralph Borne, had during the reign of King Richard I (1199-1299) been granted the estate of Radford by Oliver de Tracy, [[Feudal barony of Barnstaple|feudal baron of Barnstaple]].<ref>[[Tristram Risdon|Risdon, Tristram]] (d.1640), Survey of Devon, 1811 edition, London, 1811, with 1810 Additions, p.263</ref> According to Pole the arms of Radford of Radford were: ''Sable, three [[lampago]]es (man tigers with lion's bodies and man's faces) passant in pale [[Lions in heraldry|coward]] argent''.<ref>Pole, p.499</ref>
new_content: He was the son of Robert Radford, and Thomasina Wyke of [[Oakford, Devon|Oakford]], Devon.<ref>Woodger</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=The Murder of Nicholas Radford |url=https://www.dartmoorresource.org.uk/the-murder-of-nicholas-radford/ |access-date=2023-03-17 |website=Dartmoor Resource |language=en-GB}}</ref> According to [[Tristram Risdon|Risdon]] (d.1640), he was a descendant of the ''de Radford'' family of the estate of Radford, in the parish of [[Winkleigh]], Devon, who had changed their name from ''de Bickly'', after Robert de Bickly, son of Ralph Borne, had during the reign of King Richard I (1199-1299) been granted the estate of Radford by Oliver de Tracy, [[Feudal barony of Barnstaple|feudal baron of Barnstaple]].<ref>[[Tristram Risdon|Risdon, Tristram]] (d.1640), Survey of Devon, 1811 edition, London, 1811, with 1810 Additions, p.263</ref> According to Pole the arms of Radford of Radford were: ''Sable, three [[lampago]]es (man tigers with lion's bodies and man's faces) passant in pale [[Lions in heraldry|coward]] argent''.<ref>Pole, p.499</ref>

old_content: '''Kiin Kiin''' (Thai: "come and eat") is a Danish restaurant serving Thai cuisine, located in [[Guldbergsgade]] at [[Nørrebro]] in [[Copenhagen]]. old_content: Originating in [[England]] during the [[Middle Ages]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Zapf |first1=Patricia A. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hOslS-NSCVEC&pg=PA182 |title=Forensic Psychology and Law |last2=Roesch |first2=Ronald |last3=Hart |first3=Stephen D. |publisher=Wiley |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-470-57039-5 |location=Hoboken, New Jersey |page=182 |access-date=2 December 2014}}</ref> prominent modern examples include [[grand juries in the United States]] and in [[Japan]].<ref name=":0" /> Other [[common law]] jurisdictions formerly employed them, and most others now employ a different procedure, referred to as a [[preliminary hearing]], that does not involve a jury.{{Citation needed|date=May 2024}} Grand juries perform both accusatory and investigatory functions. The investigatory functions of grand juries include obtaining and reviewing documents and other evidence, and hearing sworn testimonies of witnesses who appear before it; the accusatory function determines whether there is [[probable cause]] to believe that one or more persons committed a particular offense within the venue of a district court.
new_content: Originating in [[England]] during the [[Middle Ages]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Zapf |first1=Patricia A. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hOslS-NSCVEC&pg=PA182 |title=Forensic Psychology and Law |last2=Roesch |first2=Ronald |last3=Hart |first3=Stephen D. |publisher=Wiley |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-470-57039-5 |location=Hoboken, New Jersey |page=182 |access-date=2 December 2014}}</ref> prominent modern examples include [[grand juries in the United States]], and to a lesser extent, [[Liberia]] and [[Japan]].<ref name=":0" /> Other [[common law]] jurisdictions formerly employed them, and most others now employ a different procedure, referred to as a [[preliminary hearing]], that does not involve a jury.{{Citation needed|date=May 2024}} Grand juries perform both accusatory and investigatory functions. The investigatory functions of grand juries include obtaining and reviewing documents and other evidence, and hearing sworn testimonies of witnesses who appear before it; the accusatory function determines whether there is [[probable cause]] to believe that one or more persons committed a particular offense within the venue of a district court. While most grand juries focus on criminal matters, some civil grand juries serve an independent [[Watchdog journalism|watchdog]] function. Around the 19th-century in Ireland and the U.S., it was not uncommon for Grand juries to be formed to pass or approve public policy.

old_content: '''Bhanupriya''' (born '''Manga Ananda Bhanu'''; 15 January 1967) is an Indian actress, dancer, and voice artiste. In a 4 decade old career, she has appeared in 155 feature films- predominantly in [[Tamil]]-[[Telugu]], and few Malayalam, Kannada and Hindi films. old_content: There are several myths and legends around Harun and his family. One notorious legend/myth<ref>{{Cite web |last=Foundation |first=Encyclopaedia Iranica |title=Welcome to Encyclopaedia Iranica |url=https://iranicaonline.org/ |access-date=2024-05-18 |website=iranicaonline.org |language=en-US}}</ref> was that Harun al-Rashid was known for being unhappy with the fact that he was a relative of Abassa's, as he was attracted to her. To keep Abassa in his life, he had her marry [[Ja'far ibn Yahya]]. The marriage was supposed to be one of convenience, but Abassa fell in love with her arranged husband.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Abassa (fl. 8th c.) {{!}} Encyclopedia.com |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/women/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/abassa-fl-8th-c |access-date=2024-05-18 |website=www.encyclopedia.com}}</ref> At night, a [[slave]] woman would be sent to Ja'far's bedroom, and Abassa took the slave woman's place one evening. Her husband was surprised. Abassa would get pregnant and give birth to [[twin]] boys in secret. The twins would be raised in [[Mecca]]. Harun eventually found out about the relationship, and had Ja'far killed. Abassa was either killed, or, sent into [[exile]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Foundation |first=Encyclopaedia Iranica |title=Welcome to Encyclopaedia Iranica |url=https://iranicaonline.org/ |access-date=2024-05-18 |website=iranicaonline.org |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=Betham>{{cite book|last=Betham|first=Matilda|title=Dictionary of the Celebrated Women, Every Age and Country|year=1804|publisher=B. Crosby and Co.|location=Warick Lake|url=https://archive.org/stream/biographicaldict00bethuoft/biographicaldict00bethuoft_djvu.txt}}</ref><ref name="Knapp1846">{{cite book|author=Samuel Lorenzo Knapp|title=Female biography: containing notices of distinguished women, in different nations and ages|url=https://archive.org/details/femalebiography00knapgoog|access-date=29 December 2012|year=1846|publisher=T. Wardle|pages=[https://archive.org/details/femalebiography00knapgoog/page/n77 69]–70}}</ref>

old_content: Chaumette was born in [[Nevers]], France, on 24 May 1763 into a family of shoemakers who wanted him to enter the Church. However, he did not have a vocation and instead sought his fortune as a cabin boy. After only reaching the rank of helmsman, he returned to Nevers to study his main interests, [[botany]] and science.<ref>Chronicle of the French Revolution, Longman, 1989 p. 31</ref> He also studied surgery and made a long voyage in the company of an English doctor, serving as his secretary. He then became surgeon to the Brothers of Charity at Moulins.<ref>Chronicle of the French Revolution, Longman, 1989 p. 31</ref> Chaumette studied [[medicine]] at the University of Paris in 1790, but gave up his career in medicine at the start of the Revolution. Chaumette began his political career as member of the [[Jacobin|Jacobin Club]] editing the progressive ''Revolutions de Paris'' journal from 1790.<ref>Jervis, p. 230,</ref> His oratory skills proved him a valuable spokesperson of the [[Cordeliers|Cordelier Club]], and more importantly, the [[sans-culotte]] movement in the [[Revolutionary sections of Paris|Paris sections]]. In August 1792, Chaumette became the Chief Procurator of the [[Paris Commune (French Revolution)|Commune of Paris]]; as member of the Paris Commune during the [[insurrection of 10 August 1792]], he was delegated to visit the prisons, with full power to arrest suspects. On 31 October 1792, he was elected President of the Commune and was re-elected in the Municipal on 2 December of that same year.
new_content: Chaumette was born in [[Nevers]], France, on 24 May 1763 into a family of shoemakers who wanted him to enter the Church. However, he did not have a [[Vocational discernment in the Catholic Church|vocation]] and instead sought his fortune as a [[cabin boy]]. After only reaching the rank of [[helmsman]], he returned to Nevers to study his main interests, [[botany]] and science.<ref>Chronicle of the French Revolution, Longman, 1989 p. 31</ref> He also studied surgery and made a long voyage in the company of an English doctor, serving as his secretary. He then became surgeon at the [[Brothers Hospitallers of Saint John of God|Frères de la charité]] in [[Moulins]].<ref>Chronicle of the French Revolution, Longman, 1989 p. 31</ref> Chaumette studied [[medicine]] at the [[University of Paris]] in 1790, but gave up his career in medicine at the start of the Revolution. Chaumette began his political career as member of the [[Jacobin|Jacobin Club]] editing the progressive ''Revolutions de Paris'' journal from 1790.<ref>Jervis, p. 230,</ref> His oratory skills proved him a valuable spokesperson of the [[Cordeliers|Cordelier Club]], and more importantly, the [[sans-culotte]] movement in the [[Revolutionary sections of Paris|Paris sections]]. In August 1792, Chaumette became the Chief Procurator of the [[Paris Commune (French Revolution)|Commune of Paris]]; as member of the Paris Commune during the [[insurrection of 10 August 1792]], he was delegated to visit the prisons, with full power to arrest suspects. On 31 October 1792, he was elected President of the Commune and was re-elected in the Municipal on 2 December of that same year.

old_content: Born in [[Bareilly]], [[British India]], Khan studied under his father [[Naqi Ali Khan]] and Meccan scholar [[Ahmad Zayni Dahlan]]. Khan was authorized in [[Sufism]] by [[Shah Al-i Rasul]] and founded the [[Manzar-i Islam]] in 1904. He was a staunch critic of the [[Deobandi movement]], denouncing them in his book ''al-Mu'tamad al-Mustanad''.
new_content: Born in [[Bareilly]], [[British India]], Khan studied under his father [[Naqi Ali Khan]] and Meccan scholar [[Ahmad Zayni Dahlan]]. Khan was authorized in [[Sufism]] by [[Shah Al-i Rasul]] and founded the [[Manzar-i Islam]] in 1904. He was a staunch critic of [[Ahmadiyya]], [[Deobandism]] and the [[Wahhabism]], denouncing their beliefs in his book {{Transliteration|ar|[[Husamul Haramain|Husam ul-Haramayn]]}}, which was published in 1906. The following year, he wrote {{Transliteration|ar|[[Hada'iq-i Bakhshish]]}}, a renowned poetic work in praise of [[Muhammad]].

old_content: Upon assuming her role as countess at the Villa Pisani in 1852, Evelina focused on creating extensive formal gardens on the grounds of the villa in [[Vescovana]].<ref>Lorne Blyth, [https://www.flavoursholidays.co.uk/blog/villa-padova-history/ "A Brief History of Villa Padova"] ''Flavour Holidays'' (6 June 2015).</ref> Her gardens reflected her English and her Turkish influences.<ref>[http://www.italianways.com/villa-pisani-and-its-green-treasure/ "Villa Pisani and its Green Treasure"] ''Italian Ways'' (10 March 2016).</ref> She also commissioned the family chapel on the grounds, built in 1860 and designed by sculptor [[Antonio Gradenigo]]. She hosted international travelers at the villa,<ref>Margaret Symonds, [https://books.google.com/books?id=m2M9AAAAYAAJ&dq=Evelina%20van%20Millingen&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q=Evelina%20van%20Millingen&f=false ''Days Spent on a Doge's Farm''] (Century Company 1908).</ref> including [[Henry James]]<ref>Henry James, [https://books.google.com/books?id=cLMS967ykasC&lpg=PA170&dq=Pisani%20Henry%20James&pg=PA170#v=onepage&q=Pisani%20Henry%20James&f=false ''Letters, Volume 3''] (Harvard University Press 1980): 170-171.</ref> and [[Augusta, Lady Gregory]].<ref>Greg Winston, [http://digitalcommons.colby.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3340&context=cq "Redefining Coole: Lady Gregory, Class Politics, and the Land War"] ''Colby Quarterly'' 37(3)(September 2001): 221.</ref>

old_content: The Beatles' producer [[George Martin]] once claimed that, during the Beatles’ visit to [[Denver|Denver, Colorado]], "a number of people pretending to be Beatles" were employed by the promoters of the band's concerts in order to distract the crowds of fans from the real Beatles, while they were exiting a hotel.<ref>{{Cite web |title=All You Need Is Ears {{!}} PDF {{!}} Sound Recording And Reproduction {{!}} Johann Sebastian Bach |url=https://www.scribd.com/document/469601510/All-You-Need-Is-Ears |access-date=24 March 2024 |website=Scribd}}</ref> According to journalist [https://www.rocksbackpages.com/Library/Writer/maureen-ogrady Maureen O'Grady,] who wrote about it in the May 1966 issue of ''RAVE Magazine'',<ref>{{Cite web |title=RAVE Magazine, June 1966 |url=https://worldradiohistory.com/UK/Rave-Magazine/1966/RAVE-1966-05.pdf}}</ref> such a tactic was used when the Beatles first played in [[Baltimore]], in 1964. As a result, stories began to circulate that the Beatles had sent four lookalikes to perform on stage on one of their American tours.<ref>{{Citation |title=Beatles Los Angeles Press Conference 1966 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O8MgItRRaTo |access-date=24 March 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=George Harrison & Ravi Shankar - The Dick Cavett Show (1971) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Z4E8soT1Gw |access-date=24 March 2024}}</ref> Both Paul McCartney and [[George Harrison]] later refuted these claims.

As a result, stories began to circulate that the Beatles had sent four lookalikes to perform on stage on one of their American tours.<ref>{{Citation |title=Beatles Los Angeles Press Conference 1966 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O8MgItRRaTo |access-date=24 March 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=George Harrison & Ravi Shankar - The Dick Cavett Show (1971) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Z4E8soT1Gw |access-date=24 March 2024}}</ref> Both Paul McCartney and [[George Harrison]] later refuted these claims.

old_content: '''Bhanupriya''' (born '''Manga Ananda Bhanu'''; 15 January 1967) is an Indian actress, Bharatnatyam and [[Kuchipudi]] dancer, and voice artiste. In a career spanning over 4 decades, Bhanupriya has appeared in 155 feature films- predominantly in Tamil & Telugu, in addition to occasional performances in Malayalam, Kannada and Hindi films. She has starred in a variety of roles, ranging from slapstick comedy to epic dramas. She has won three state [[Nandi Awards]], two [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]], two [[Filmfare Awards South]] and two [[Cinema Express Awards]].
new_content: '''Bhanupriya''' (born '''Manga Ananda Bhanu'''; 15 January 1967) is an Indian actress, dancer, and voice artiste. In a 4 decade old career, she has appeared in 155 feature films- predominantly in [[Tamil]]-[[Telugu]], and few Malayalam, Kannada and Hindi films. She has starred in a variety of roles, which garnered her three state [[Nandi Awards]], two [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]], two [[Filmfare Awards South]] and two [[Cinema Express Awards]].

old_content: In the year 1882, in Calcutta, India, he founded the great business house '''"Whiteaway, Laidlaw, and Co."'''. Soon, Whiteaway opened branches in about 20 cities, in India and the Straits Settlements, including Shanghai, Singapore, Penang, Kuala Lumpur, Ipoh, Taiping, Seremban, Klang, Malacca and Telok Anson. Whiteaway was as much into tailoring and as they were into importing and selling household goods.  Robert Laidlaw was also a proprietor of tea estates in Darjeeling and of rubber estates in the Federated Malay States. He served as Chairman of Whiteaway, Laidlaw and Co. and '''Duncan Durian Rubber Estate, Ltd.''', till his death in 1917.<ref name="WhoWas" /> He was also a director of the '''Pilot Insurance Corporation.'''

old_content: James Gardner, architecture critic for the ''[[New York Sun]]'' wrote that the original building "was indubitably a landmark; the best that can be said for its replacement is that, if we're lucky, no one will ever notice it."<ref>{{cite news|last=Gardner|first=James|title=Missing the Marble at 2 Columbus Circle|work=New York Sun|date=April 15, 2008|url=http://www.nysun.com/arts/missing-the-marble-at-2-columbus-circle/74723/|access-date=September 5, 2009|archive-date=January 15, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090115003920/http://www.nysun.com/arts/missing-the-marble-at-2-columbus-circle/74723/|url-status=live}}</ref> Five years after the renovation was complete, Gardner maintained that the redesigned structure was "far inferior" to Stone's original design.<ref>{{Cite web|date=February 22, 2013|title=Architecture review: The Stone curse|url=https://therealdeal.com/2013/02/22/architecture-review-the-stone-curse/|access-date=June 29, 2022|website=The Real Deal New York|language=en-US|archive-date=November 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211115231936/https://therealdeal.com/2013/02/22/architecture-review-the-stone-curse/|url-status=live}}</ref> Francis Morrone, also of the ''Sun'', wrote: "Where Stone's original building read as neatly scaled to its setting, Mr. Cloepfil's redesign reads as a piece of abstract sculpture that, at building scale, seems all wrong."<ref>{{cite news|last=Morrone|first=Francis|title=Taking a Fresh Look at Columbus Circle|work=New York Sun|date=August 7, 2008|url=http://www.nysun.com/calendar/taking-a-fresh-look-at-columbus-circle/83318/|access-date=September 5, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005080059/http://www.nysun.com/calendar/taking-a-fresh-look-at-columbus-circle/83318/|archive-date=October 5, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Witold Rybczynski]] wrote in [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] that the new design "feels like an alien presence",<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rybczynski|first=Witold|date=January 14, 2009|title=Goodbye, 2 Columbus Circle|journal=Slate Magazine|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2208529|access-date=September 5, 2009|archive-date=June 25, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625192149/http://www.slate.com/id/2208529|url-status=live}}</ref> and architecture critic [[Justin Davidson]] said, "This version won't satisfy those old_content: In January 1977, Hubbard shot Montgomery three times and robbed her of her gold and diamond wristwatch, along with about $500 in cash and checks. Hubbard later called police and reported that he had been drinking whiskey with Montgomery, who committed suicide. Montgomery died as a result of three gunshot wounds – one each to the face, head, and shoulder.
new_content: In January 1977, Hubbard shot Montgomery three times and robbed her of her gold and diamond wristwatch, along with about $500 in cash and checks. Montgomery died as a result of three gunshot wounds—one each to the face, head, and shoulder.

old_content: Climate change is a global challenge which will affect all countries in the long-term as the impact of climate change is spread unevenly across different regions. However, there may be a disproportionately harsher effect in fragile contexts and/or socially vulnerable and marginalized groups due to [[climate change vulnerability]]. For example, the [[Bay of Bengal]], which includes Bangladesh, Myanmar, India, Indonesia, and Sri Lanka, is one of the world’s most climate-vulnerable regions and. Marginalized groups and minority communities, both in the [[Global North and Global South#Definition|Global North and Global South]], are most affected by the effects of climate change, for which they are least responsible, which many call environmental injustice (see also [[climate justice]]).<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Gonzalez |first=Carmen |title=Global Justice in the Anthropocene. ENVIRONMENTAL LAW AND GOVERNANCE FOR THE ANTHROPOCENE. Louis Kotze, ed. Hart Publishing, 2017 |url=https://www.academia.edu/31758184}}</ref>

old_content: A '''''Grand Theft Auto'' clone''' (often shortened to '''''GTA'' clone''') belongs to a [[Video game genres|subgenre]] of [[open world]] [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[video game]]s, characterized by their likeness to the [[Grand Theft Auto|''Grand Theft Auto'' series]] in either gameplay, or overall design. In these types of open world games, players may find and use a variety of vehicles and weapons while roaming freely in an open world setting. The objective of ''Grand Theft Auto'' clones is to complete a sequence of core missions involving driving and shooting, but often side-missions and [[minigame]]s are added to improve [[replay value]]. The storylines of games in this subgenre typically have strong themes of crime, violence and other controversial elements such as [[Substance abuse|drugs]] and [[pornography|sexually explicit]] content.
new_content: A '''''Grand Theft Auto'' clone''' (often shortened to '''''GTA'' clone''') belongs to a [[Video game genres|subgenre]] of [[open world]] [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[video game]]s, characterized by their likeness to the [[Grand Theft Auto|''Grand Theft Auto'' series]] in either gameplay, or overall design. In these types of open world games, players may find and use a variety of vehicles and weapons while roaming freely in an open world setting. The objective of ''Grand Theft Auto'' clones is to complete a sequence of core missions involving driving and shooting, but often side-missions and [[minigame]]s are added to improve [[replay value]]. The storylines of games in this subgenre typically have strong themes of crime, violence and other controversial elements such as drugs and sexually explicit content.

old_content: The battlefield is located on both sides of the river, on either side of [[Arkansas Highway 161]], whose bridge is the location of the 1863 Reed's Bridge. The entire battlefield is the best-preserved of the three major battle sites of the Union advance on Little Rock.<ref name=NRHP>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkansaspreservation.com/National-Register-Listings/PDF/PU3068.nr.pdf|title=NRHP nomination for Bayou Meto (Reed's Bridge) Battlefield|publisher=Arkansas Preservation|accessdate=2015-06-13}}</ref>  A {{convert|412|acre|ha|adj=on}} area covering the core of the battlefield was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2002.<ref name="nris"/>

old_content: "'''The Medicine Will'''" is a song recorded by American [[country music]] artist [[Brad Paisley]] that features on his thirteenth studio album ''[[Son of the Mountains]]''. The song was released on September 29, 2023, alongside the title track, with both being included on Paisley's [[extended play]] ''The First Four Tracks''. Paisley co-wrote the song with [[Lee Thomas Miller]], and co-produced it with Luke Wooten, describing it as his favorite song he's ever written, with the lyrics highlighting the [[Opioid epidemic in the United States]] and how people in his home state of [[Virginia]] have been impacted by it.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Crabtree |first=Mary Claire |date=2023-10-02 |title=Brad Paisley Addresses The Opioid Crisis in Appalachia With New Single "The Medicine Will"|url=https://www.whiskeyriff.com/2023/10/02/brad-paisley-addresses-the-opioid-crisis-in-appalachia-with-new-single-the-medicine-will/|access-date=February 7, 2024|website=Whisky Riff |language=en-US}}</ref>

old_content: By the 2000s, much of it still looked blighted but a growing number of bright spots were popping up due to a wave of investment in intown Atlanta beginning to rejuvenate the area. As West End was once described as one of Atlanta's most socially diverse and culturally rich communities, it is again returning to the tradition of its past, as it relates to the regenerating of community value and revitalization. An example of revitalization in West End is Sky Lofts, which converted a long vacant Sears parking lot. Sky Lofts brought a lot of new residents, especially young professionals, looking for urban lifestyle. Historic houses are being rehabbed and renovated by new and old residents. West End, as its name suggests (named after London's theater district), is also a mecca for artists. West End was chosen by Creative Loafing in 2010 as '''Best Neighborhood For Artists'''.

old_content: '''Tony Joe White''' (July 23, 1943 – October 24, 2018), nicknamed the '''Swamp Fox''',<ref name= newyorktimes /> was an American singer-songwriter and guitarist, best known for his 1969 [[hit record|hit]] "[[Polk Salad Annie]]" and for "[[Rainy Night in Georgia]]", which he wrote but which was first made popular by [[Brook Benton]] in 1970. He also wrote "[[Steamy Windows]]" and "Undercover Agent for the Blues", both hits for [[Tina Turner]] in 1989; those two songs came by way of Turner's producer at the time, [[Mark Knopfler]], who was a friend of White. "Polk Salad Annie" was also recorded by [[Joe Dassin]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Joe Bonamassa]] and [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]].
new_content: '''Tony Joe White''' (July 23, 1943 – October 24, 2018), nicknamed the '''Swamp Fox''',<ref name= newyorktimes /> was an American singer-songwriter and guitarist, best known for his 1969 [[hit record|hit]] "[[Polk Salad Annie]]" and for "[[Rainy Night in Georgia]]", which he wrote but which was first made popular by [[Brook Benton]] in 1970. He also wrote "[[Steamy Windows]]" and "Undercover Agent for the Blues", both hits for [[Tina Turner]] in 1989; those two songs came by way of Turner's producer at the time, [[Mark Knopfler]], who was a friend of White's. "Polk Salad Annie" was also recorded by [[Joe Dassin]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Joe Bonamassa]] and [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]].

old_content: During his career, Avise was the Major Advisor for 26 PhD or M.S. students and 11 postdocs. Nearly all of these trainees went on to assume faculty positions or other leadership roles around the world, thereby seeding many institutions with research in the fields of molecular ecology, natural history, and evolution. The following are some of the numerous universities where Avise's students or postdoctoral trainees have held or currently hold faculty positions: Colorado State University; University of Arkansas; Purdue University; University of Southwestern Louisiana; East Carolina University; University of South Florida; University of Hawaii; Cornell University; Texas A&M University; University of Idaho; Georgia Tech University; State University of New York at Binghamton; HudsonAlpha Institute for Biotechnology; Oregon State University; South Carolina Department of Natural Resources; Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute; University of Florida; Hawaii Institute of Marine Biology; Michigan State University; National Institutes of Health; University of California at Santa Cruz; University of California at Irvine; Duquesne University; Oxford University; University College of London; University of British Columbia; Hopkins Marine Station of Stanford University; Queens University Belfast; Ocean University of China; U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service; University of Nebraska; and James Cook University Australia.

old_content: * [[List of Titans (2018 TV series) characters#Slade Wilson / Deathstroke|Slade Wilson / Deathstroke]] appears in the [[Titans (season 2)|second season]] of ''[[Titans (2018 TV series)|Titans]]'', portrayed by [[Esai Morales]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Staley|first=Brandon|title=A New Deathstroke Is Coming to Titans, Along with Jericho|url=https://www.cbr.com/titans-dc-universe-deathstroke-jericho/|website=Comic Book Resource|access-date=October 4, 2018|date=October 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/titans-esai-morales-joins-dc-universe-as-deathstroke-1202575173/|title='Titans': Esai Morales Joins DC Universe As Deathstroke|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|date=March 13, 2019|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=March 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Trigon |url=https://www.dcuniverse.com/videos/watch/trigon/e20bfeb3-e426-4b7b-9cab-aa3ee5ccda73 |access-date=September 7, 2019 |series=Titans |series-link=Titans (2018 TV series) |first1=Carol |last1=Banker |first2=Akiva |last2=Goldsman |author-link2=Akiva Goldsman |first3=Geoff |last3=Johns |author-link3=Geoff Johns |first4=Greg |last4=Walker |network=[[DC Universe]] |date=September 6, 2019 |season=2 |number=1 }}</ref> This version is a [[Delta Force]] veteran who underwent experimental bio-enhancements at [[H.I.V.E.]] Slade's feud with the Titans began when he killed [[Garth (comics)|Garth]], causing their leader [[Dick Grayson (Titans character)|Dick Grayson]] to expose Slade's true nature to his son [[Jericho (DC Comics)|Jericho]]. Blaming the Titans for tearing his family apart, Slade attempts to seek revenge by planting his illegitimate daughter [[Rose Wilson|Rose]] into their ranks, though Rose ultimately betrays and stabs him after joining the Titans. A zombified version of Deathstroke briefly appears in the [[Titans season 4|fourth season]].

old_content: As of 2011, Ramgarh has a total number of 47 houses and population of 200 of which 92 include are males while 108 are females according to the report [[published]] by [[Census India]] in 2011. old_content: ''[[The Times]]'''s review of the first UK performance described it as being "in the spirit of the Brandenburg Concertos of Bach.  Indeed, Mr Holst has here come nearer to formal perfection than in any of his previous works, without abandoning his individual point of view."<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--not stated--> |date=12 October 1923 |title=The Promenade Concerts. Mr Holst's Fugal Concerto |work=The Times |location=London |page=7 }}</ref>   However, one composer called it "desiccated",{{sfn|Holst|1958|p=88}} and many other early critical judgements were sparing of praise or outright hostile.  A second critique in ''The Times'' in 1924 conceded that it "is fun, of course, but rather heavy fun; the penalty of jokes is that they ill bear repetition";<ref>https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&retrievalId=ee7febb2-3d16-4ea4-840f-7a888f3ad6f1&hitCount=70&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=4&docId=GALE%7CCS202315388&docType=Review&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&pageNum=1&contentSet=GALE%7CCS202315388&searchId=R3&userGroupName=bright&inPS=true</ref> and a third in 1935 wrote of its "ingenious triviality".<ref>https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&retrievalId=d84485d0-024b-4d06-9e35-0342030962b2&hitCount=70&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=12&docId=GALE%7CCS235351223&docType=Review&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&pageNum=1&contentSet=GALE%7CCS235351223&searchId=R3&userGroupName=bright&inPS=true</ref>  The critic [[Dyneley Hussey]] thought the ''Fugal Concerto'' and the ''Fugal Overture'' "perverse exercises in the contrapuntal style, devoid of any warmth and with none of the real vitality which appears in the earlier '[[St Paul's Suite|St Paul's' Suite]] for strings."<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JzgrAQAAMAAJ&q=%22perverse+exercises+in+the+contrapuntal+style%22&dq=%22perverse+exercises+in+the+contrapuntal+style%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjtw9GXtJCGAxUfVEEAHUqjBXoQ6AF6BAgHEAI (see Man p. XLV for ref)</ref>  American reviews could be as bad.  [[Olin Downes]] wrote that it was "smoothly written, and if a certain middle-of-the-road and eminently respectable manner is really typical of English music, then it is evident that this music is English."  ''[[Musical America]]'' believed that it "scarcely explain[s] the great renown [Holst] enjoys".<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SnHpuUKDQ5MC&pg=PA212&dq=holst+%22fugal+concerto%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjPhoXl1YiGAxU2BNsEHZb9AF4Q6AF6BAgEEAI#v=onepage&q=holst%20%22fugal%20concerto%22&f=false</ref>  A 1967 recording of the work was similarly dismissed as "little more than an academic study"; it was "much less taking [than the ''[[Lyric Movement]]''] with none of [its] character or inspiration".<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uoVHAAAAMAAJ&q=%22little+more+than+an+academic+study%22+%22much+less+taking%22&dq=%22little+more+than+an+academic+study%22+%22much+less+taking%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiK7Muq6JKGAxW4WkEAHYPNAnQQ6AF6BAgIEAI</ref>

new_content: * Aegyptus, husband of [[Thebe (Greek myth)|Thebe]], eponym of [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]] in ?[[Ancient Egypt|Egypt]], whom given by her father [[Zeus]] as his bride<ref>[[John Tzetzes|Tzetzes]] ad [[Lycophron]], [https://topostext.org/work/860#1206 1206] with the historian Lycus as the authority</ref>. In another version of the myth, Aegyptus was instead called the son of Zeus and Thebe<ref name="Tzetzes2">Tzetzes on Lycophron, [https://topostext.org/work/860#1206 1206]</ref> and thus, can be considered brother of the earlier [[Heracles]].<ref>[[John Lydus]], ''De mensibus'' 4.67</ref> He was the father of [[Carcho]] whom the island of [[Carthage]] was named after.<ref name="Tzetzes2" /> This Aegyptus may be the same or different with the one below.

old_content: The 'A' team won the inaugural Alliance in 1891 and dominated the early years of the league, winning five out of the first six seasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.northernfootballalliance.org.uk/handbook/|title=Northern Football Alliance {{!}}|website=www.northernfootballalliance.org.uk|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> They competed in the Alliance until 1902.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://donmouth.co.uk/local_history/northern_alliance/northern_alliance.html|title=Northern Alliance|website=donmouth.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> In 1906 they joined the new [[North Eastern League]] along with reserve teams from [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablese/engnortheasthist.html|title=England - North Eastern League|website=[[RSSSF]]|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> Sunderland finished second to Newcastle United 'A' in their first two seasons, and won the league for the first time in 1925. Sunderland went on to win it a further nine times, second only to Middlesbrough.<ref name=":1" /> The North East's league teams withdrew their reserve teams from the North Eastern League in 1958.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nonleaguematters.co.uk/nlmnet/Addons/NE33.html|title=Website created using 350pages at www.350.com|website=www.nonleaguematters.co.uk|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> Sunderland and Middlesbrough both joined the [[North Regional League]]. Sunderland won it once and came second three times before the league disbanded in 1969.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fchd.info/SUNDERL2.HTM|title=Football Club History Database - Sunderland reserves|website=www.fchd.info|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> Sunderland bid to join [[The Central League]] in 1970, but were unsuccessful after only receiving four votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/opinion/lads-italian-lesson-kills-final-dream-1-1116161|title=Lads' Italian lesson kills final dream|access-date=2018-10-27|language=en}}</ref>

old_content: A '''Shepard tone''', named after [[Roger Shepard]], is a [[sound]] consisting of a [[superposition principle|superposition]] of [[sine wave]]s separated by [[octave]]s. When played with the bass [[Pitch (music)|pitch]] of the tone moving upward or downward, it is referred to as the ''Shepard scale''. This creates the [[auditory illusion]] of a tone that seems to continually ascend or descend in pitch, yet which ultimately gets no higher or lower.<ref name=Shepard1964/>
new_content: A '''Shepard tone''', named after [[Roger Shepard]], is a [[sound]] consisting of a [[superposition principle|superposition]] of [[sine wave]]s all separated by [[octave]]s and at roughly the same perceived volume. A finite sequence of Shepard tones, moving either upward or downward in [[Pitch (music)|pitch]] is called a ''Shepard scale''.  For as long as this sequence of tones is repeated, this creates the [[auditory illusion]] of a tone that either ascends or descends in pitch forever, yet which ultimately gets no higher or lower.<ref name=Shepard1964/>

old_content: The Freedom Alliance can be described{{By whom|date=May 2024}} as [[Hard Eurosceptic]], the party advocates for Finland to leave the [[European Union]] and condemns the EU as being [[Authoritarianism|anti-democratic]], [[Globalism|globalist]] and [[Elite|elitist]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-03-23 |title=Pelasta Suomi globalistien kynsistä |url=https://vapaudenliitto.fi/pelasta-suomi-globalistien-kynsista/ |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Vapauden liitto r.p. |language=fi}}</ref> The Freedom Alliance is also against [[NATO]] and the [[United States]], proclaiming that cooperation with the United States has made Finland a [[satellite state]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-12-10 |title=NATOKUUME SAI SUOMI-NEIDON JÄRJILTÄÄN |url=https://vapaudenliitto.fi/natokuume-sai-suomi-neidon-jarjiltaan/ |access-date=2024-04-30 |website=Vapauden liitto r.p. |language=fi}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-12-22 |title=DCA-sopimuksella Suomi-neidosta tehtiin USA:n marionetti |url=https://vapaudenliitto.fi/dca-sopimuksella-suomi-neidosta-tehtiin-usan-marionetti/ |access-date=2024-04-30 |website=Vapauden liitto r.p. |language=fi}}</ref> The party can be described as against [[Transatlanticism (politics)|transatlanticism]], instead wishing for the return to the [[Paasikivi–Kekkonen doctrine]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-11-12 |title=Vapauden liitto ajaa perinteistä puolueettomuuspolitiikkaa |url=https://vapaudenliitto.fi/vapauden-liitto-ajaa-perinteista-puolueettomuuspolitiikkaa/ |access-date=2024-04-30 |website=Vapauden liitto r.p. |language=fi}}</ref> Despite the opposition to the European Union, the Freedom Alliance wishes to promote European and international cooperation.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=Puolueohjelma {{!}} Vapauden liitto |url=https://vapaudenliitto.fi/puolueohjelma/ |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=Vapauden liitto r.p. |language=fi}}</ref>

old_content: In some cases, variations in sex characteristics are caused by unusual levels of sex hormones, which may be the result of an atypical set of sex chromosomes.{{medical citation needed|date=July 2023}} One common cause of variations in sex characteristics traits is the crossing over of the [[testis-determining factor]] (SRY) from the Y chromosome to the X chromosome during [[meiosis]]. The SRY is then activated in only certain areas, causing development of [[testes]] in some areas by beginning a series of events starting with the upregulation of the [[transcription factor]] (SOX9), and in other areas not being active (causing the growth of [[ovarian]] [[Tissue (biology)|tissues]]). Thus, [[testicular]] and ovarian tissues will both be present in the same individual.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Margarit E, Coll MD, Oliva R, Gómez D, Soler A, Ballesta F | title = SRY gene transferred to the long arm of the X chromosome in a Y-positive XX true hermaphrodite | journal = American Journal of Medical Genetics | volume = 90 | issue = 1 | pages = 25–8 | date = January 2000 | pmid = 10602113 | doi = 10.1002/(SICI)1096-8628(20000103)90:1<25::AID-AJMG5>3.0.CO;2-5 }}</ref>
new_content: In some cases, variations in sex characteristics are caused by unusual levels of sex hormones, which may be the result of an atypical set of sex chromosomes.{{medical citation needed|date=July 2023}} One common cause of variations in sex characteristics traits is the crossing over of the [[testis-determining factor]] (SRY) from the Y chromosome to the X chromosome during [[meiosis]]. The SRY is then activated in only certain areas, causing development of [[testes]] in some areas by beginning a series of events starting with the upregulation of the [[transcription factor]] (SOX9), and in other areas not being active (causing the growth of [[ovarian]] [[Tissue (biology)|tissues]]). Thus, [[testicular]] and ovarian tissues will both be present in the same individual.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Margarit E, Coll MD, Oliva R, Gómez D, Soler A, Ballesta F | title = SRY gene transferred to the long arm of the X chromosome in a Y-positive XX true hermaphrodite | journal = American Journal of Medical Genetics | volume = 90 | issue = 1 | pages = 25–8 | date = January 2000 | pmid = 10602113 | doi = 10.1002/(SICI)1096-8628(20000103)90:1<25::AID-AJMG5>3.0.CO;2-5 }}</ref> Though of all total recorded cases of ovotesticular DSD, in only 8% percent of all cases was SRY present, leaving the rest of cases that could be explained to other or less common causes, or simply being currently unexplainable.

old_content: ''Raillardella pringlei'' is a [[rhizome|rhizomatous]] perennial herb growing in a clump of rosetted basal leaves. The leaves are linear to lance-shaped with smooth or faintly toothed edges, up to 15 centimeters long, and mostly hairless. Leaves also appear on the [[inflorescence]] in opposite pairs on a hairy-glandular stalk. The plant produces an [[inflorescence]] generally 25 centimeters to half a meter tall consisting of a solitary [[Head (botany)|flower head]] or an array of up to three heads. The head is bell-shaped, sometimes widely so. It contains many orange to red-orange disc florets each about a centimeter long, and a fringe of several orange or reddish ray florets each up to 2 centimeters in length. The floral bract is densely covered with glandular hairs. The fruit is a long, narrow [[achene]] which may be 2 centimeters in length including its [[pappus (botany)|pappus]] of plumelike bristles.<ref name="Jepson">{{Cite web|url=https://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=4552|title=The Jepson Herbarium}}</ref>

old_content: The revival in Bengali cinema dates from the rise of directors such as  [[Tarun Majumdar]], along with [[Rituparno Ghosh]], [[Prabhat Roy]], [[Buddhadeb Dasgupta]], [[Anjan Das]], [[Aparna Sen]], [[ Goutam Ghosh]], [[ Kaushik Ganguly]], [[Prabhat Roy]], [[Atanu Ghosh]], [[Suman Ghosh (director)|Suman Ghosh]], [[ Sekhar Das]], [[Sudeshna Roy]], [[Anjan Dutt]], [[Sandip Ray]] .<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gooptu |first1=Sharmistha |date=23 February 2014 |title=Mapping Bengal's cinema history |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/sunday-edition/mapping-bengals-cinema-history.html |work=The Pioneer |access-date=17 April 2024}}</ref> Rituparno Ghosh made his first film, ''[[Hirer Angti]]'', in 1992 and dominated Bengali cinema until his death in 2013, winning numerous national awards for films like ''[[Unishe April]]'', ''[[Dahan (1997 film)|Dahan]]'' and ''[[Utsab]]''. Aparna Sen made her directorial debut in 1981 with the internationally lauded ''[[36 Chowringhee Lane]]'', which looked at the lives of Anglo-Indians living in Calcutta. Her later films have also been celebrated: ''[[Paromitar Ek Din]]'',  ''[[The Japanese Wife]]'', ''[[Goynar Baksho]]'', and others. Buddhadeb Dasgupta is best known for award-winning films like ''[[Uttara (film)|Uttara]]'', ''[[Mondo Meyer Upakhyan]]'', ''[[Charachar]]'', and ''[[Janala]]''. [[Goutam Ghose]] is Internationally Acclaimed for Cult Classic films as [[Antarjali Jatra]], [[Padma Nadir Majhi]], [[ Moner Manush]] and many more.

old_content: The [[Dinka]] and [[Nuer people|Nuer]] are the two largest ethnic groups in South Sudan. Conflict over pastures and cattle raids has been happening between these two ethnic groups as they battle for grazing their animals. In 2013, the former Vice president [[Riek Machar]] who is a Nuer, was dismissed by the president of South Sudan, [[Salva Kiir Mayardit|Salva Kiir]], who is a Dinka, which created conflict between the Dinka and Nuer people in South Sudan.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Conflict between Dinka and Nuer in South Sudan {{!}} Climate-Diplomacy |url=https://climate-diplomacy.org/case-studies/conflict-between-dinka-and-nuer-south-sudan |access-date=2022-05-26 |website=climate-diplomacy.org |language=en}}</ref>
new_content: The [[Dinka]] and [[Nuer people|Nuer]] are the two largest ethnic groups in South Sudan. Conflict over pastures and cattle raids has been happening between these two ethnic groups as they battle for grazing their animals. In 1983, there was a civil war between Southern and Northern Sudan, and Southern Sudan was forced into the lower Region, where there was less resources. These Effects created conflict between the Dinka and Nuer people in South Sudan.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Conflict between Dinka and Nuer in South Sudan {{!}} Climate-Diplomacy |url=https://climate-diplomacy.org/case-studies/conflict-between-dinka-and-nuer-south-sudan |access-date=2022-05-26 |website=climate-diplomacy.org |language=en}}</ref>

old_content: In [[graph theory]], an '''orientation''' of an [[undirected graph]] is an assignment of a direction to each edge, turning the initial graph into a [[directed graph]].
new_content: In [[graph theory]], an '''oriented graph''' is a "one-way" [[directed graph]], i.e. one where any pair of points has an arrow pointing from one to the other (but not vice-versa). More formally, it is a [[directed graph]] created by assigning a direction to each edge of an [[Graph (discrete mathematics)|undirected graph]].

old_content: In September 2016, Senator [[Antonio Trillanes IV]], a former [[Armed Forces of the Philippines|military officer]] who led 2 coup attempts ([[Oakwood Mutiny]] and [[Manila Peninsula siege]]) during the administration of President [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]], turned off the microphone of his fellow Senator (former [[Nacionalista Party|Partymate]]) [[Alan Peter Cayetano]] during a televised Senate hearing on the [[Philippine war on drugs]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/819179/cayetano-to-trillanes-anywhere-anytime-i-wont-back-down|title=Cayetano to Trillanes: Anywhere, anytime, I won't back down|first=Maila|last=Ager|date=26 September 2016|website=INQUIRER.net}}</ref> and engaged in January 2017 with Senator [[Migz Zubiri|Juan Miguel Zubiri]] in near fistfighting, after the [[Coalition for Change|Kilusang Pagbabago]] Coalition Members rejected Trillanes' resolution for investigation for the [[Bureau of Immigration (Philippines)|Bureau of Immigration]] Bribery scandal.
new_content: In September 2016, Senator [[Antonio Trillanes IV]], a former [[Armed Forces of the Philippines|military officer]] who led two coup attempts ([[Oakwood Mutiny]] and [[Manila Peninsula siege]]) during the administration of President [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]], turned off the microphone of his fellow Senator (former [[Nacionalista Party|Partymate]]) [[Alan Peter Cayetano]] during a televised Senate hearing on the [[Philippine war on drugs]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/819179/cayetano-to-trillanes-anywhere-anytime-i-wont-back-down|title=Cayetano to Trillanes: Anywhere, anytime, I won't back down|first=Maila|last=Ager|date=26 September 2016|website=INQUIRER.net}}</ref> and engaged in January 2017 with Senator [[Migz Zubiri|Juan Miguel Zubiri]] in near fistfighting, after the [[Coalition for Change|Kilusang Pagbabago]] Coalition Members rejected Trillanes' resolution for investigation for the [[Bureau of Immigration (Philippines)|Bureau of Immigration]] Bribery scandal.
