old_content: On November 1, 2023, the revival of the [[Arena Football League]] announced the return of the Nashville Kats and and new ownership structure. The team is co-owned by Tamara Dadd Alan, Founding Partner and CEO; Nancy Eckert, Founding Partner and COO/General Counsel; and Chuck McDowell, largest individual stakeholder and Chairman of the franchise.  [[Jeff Fisher]], former [[Tennessee Titans]] Head Coach, is a partner and President of Football Operation for the organization. Sports talk host Greg Pogue also serves as Partner and Vice President of Community Relations. The team will play at [[Nashville Municipal Auditorium]] in Nashville, with one game at [[F&M Bank Arena]] in [[Clarksville, Tennessee|Clarksville]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Organ |first=Mike |title=How Jeff Fisher is helping bring back the Nashville Kats and Arena Football League |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/columnist/mike-organ/2023/11/01/jeff-fisher-tennessee-titans-nashville-kats-arena-football-league-eddie-george-bud-adams/71373615007/ |date=November 1, 2023 |access-date=November 1, 2023 |website=The Tennessean |language=en-US}}</ref>

old_content: The class Js were among the N&W's most reliable steam locomotives; they ran evenly on its mountainous and relatively short route at an average speed of {{convert|40|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}, producing {{convert|5100|hp|abbr=on}} at the tender drawbar.<ref name="Miller2000p68"/><ref name="Boyd2000p132">{{Harvp|Boyd|2000|p=132}}.</ref> On flat [[terrain]], the class J locomotives could haul a {{convert|1025|ST|lb}} passenger train of 15 [[passenger railroad car|car]]s at {{convert|110|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Miller2000p69">{{Harvp|Miller|2000|p=69}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|last1=Rhodes|first1=John T.|last2=Stephenson|first2=David R.|date=September 2013|title=Steam Locomotive Rail Wheel Dynamics Part 1: Precedent Speed of Steam Locomotives|url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55e5ef3fe4b0d3b9ddaa5954/t/55e63647e4b06159647b2fb9/1441150535974/WP_SLRWD_1.pdf|magazine=Coalition for Sustainable Rail|access-date=August 1, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210801200850/https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55e5ef3fe4b0d3b9ddaa5954/t/55e63647e4b06159647b2fb9/1441150535974/WP_SLRWD_1.pdf|archive-date=August 1, 2021}}</ref>{{rp|5–6}} Theoretically, they could go up to {{convert|140|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}} without [[locomotive wheelslip|wheel slippage]].<ref name="Miller2000p66"/> They generally operated about {{convert|500|mi|km}} per day and {{convert|15,000|mi|km}} per month.<ref>{{Harvp|Jeffries|1980|p=239}}.</ref><ref name="Morgan">{{Cite magazine |last=Morgan |first=David P. |date=November 1954 |title=Faith in Steam |url=https://www.trains.com/trn/magazine/archive-access/trains-november-1954/ |url-access=limited |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230721013847/https://www.trains.com/trn/magazine/archive-access/trains-november-1954/ |archive-date=July 21, 2023 |access-date=July 21, 2023 |magazine=[[Trains (magazine)|Trains]] |publisher=[[Kalmbach Media]] |page=25 |volume=15 |issue=1}}</ref>
new_content: The class Js were among the N&W's most reliable steam locomotives; they ran evenly on its mountainous and relatively short route at an average speed of {{convert|40|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}, producing {{convert|5100|hp|abbr=on}} at the tender [[drawbar (haulage)|drawbar]].<ref name="Miller2000p68"/><ref name="Boyd2000p132">{{Harvp|Boyd|2000|p=132}}.</ref> On flat [[terrain]], the class J locomotives could haul a {{convert|1025|ST|lb}} passenger train of 15 [[passenger railroad car|car]]s at {{convert|110|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Miller2000p69">{{Harvp|Miller|2000|p=69}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine|last1=Rhodes|first1=John T.|last2=Stephenson|first2=David R.|date=September 2013|title=Steam Locomotive Rail Wheel Dynamics Part 1: Precedent Speed of Steam Locomotives|url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55e5ef3fe4b0d3b9ddaa5954/t/55e63647e4b06159647b2fb9/1441150535974/WP_SLRWD_1.pdf|magazine=Coalition for Sustainable Rail|access-date=August 1, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210801200850/https://static1.squarespace.com/static/55e5ef3fe4b0d3b9ddaa5954/t/55e63647e4b06159647b2fb9/1441150535974/WP_SLRWD_1.pdf|archive-date=August 1, 2021}}</ref>{{rp|5–6}} Theoretically, they could go up to {{convert|140|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}} without [[locomotive wheelslip|wheel slippage]].<ref name="Miller2000p66"/> They generally operated about {{convert|500|mi|km}} per day and {{convert|15,000|mi|km}} per month.<ref>{{Harvp|Jeffries|1980|p=239}}.</ref><ref name="Morgan">{{Cite magazine |last=Morgan |first=David P. |date=November 1954 |title=Faith in Steam |url=https://www.trains.com/trn/magazine/archive-access/trains-november-1954/ |url-access=limited |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230721013847/https://www.trains.com/trn/magazine/archive-access/trains-november-1954/ |archive-date=July 21, 2023 |access-date=July 21, 2023 |magazine=[[Trains (magazine)|Trains]] |publisher=[[Kalmbach Media]] |page=25 |volume=15 |issue=1}}</ref>

old_content: Within academia, climate security emerged from a discourse of [[environmental security]] and was first mentioned in the Brundtland Report in 1987.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Visser|first1=Wayne|title=Our Common Future ('The Brundtland Report'): World Commission on Environment and Development |doi=10.9774/gleaf.978-1-907643-44-6_12 |journal=The Top 50 Sustainability Books |pages=52–55 |publisher=Greenleaf Publishing Limited |date=December 13, 2009 |last2=Brundtland |first2=Gro Harlem|isbn=978-1-907643-44-6}}</ref> During the 70's and 80's the [[JASON (advisory group)|Jason advisory group]], concerned with security, conducted research on climate change.<ref name="Rich">{{cite news |last=Rich |first=Nathaniel |date=5 August 2018 |title=Losing Earth: The Decade We Almost Stopped Climate Change |pages=4– |work=The New York Times Magazine |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/08/01/magazine/climate-change-losing-earth.html |url-status=live |url-access=limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220115105222/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/08/01/magazine/climate-change-losing-earth.html |archive-date=15 January 2022 |issn=0028-7822}}</ref>  Global climate change became an international issue with the broadening of the concept of security which emerged in the 1980s in the post-Cold War era.The broadening of the concept of security sought to look beyond the military domain, and include political, economic, societal, and environmental areas in the security agenda.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Sheehan |first1=Michael J. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TnSBQgAACAAJ |title=International Security: An Analytical Survey |last2=Sheehan |first2=Professor Michael |date=2005 |publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers |isbn=978-1-58826-298-1 |language=en}}</ref> The term ''security'' can refer to a broad range of securities including national, international, ecological and [[human security]].
new_content: Within academia, climate security emerged from a discourse of [[environmental security]] and was first mentioned in the Brundtland Report in 1987.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Visser|first1=Wayne|title=Our Common Future ('The Brundtland Report'): World Commission on Environment and Development |doi=10.9774/gleaf.978-1-907643-44-6_12 |journal=The Top 50 Sustainability Books |pages=52–55 |publisher=Greenleaf Publishing Limited |date=December 13, 2009 |last2=Brundtland |first2=Gro Harlem|isbn=978-1-907643-44-6}}</ref> During the '70s and '80s the [[JASON (advisory group)|Jason advisory group]], concerned with security, conducted research on climate change.<ref name="Rich">{{cite news |last=Rich |first=Nathaniel |date=5 August 2018 |title=Losing Earth: The Decade We Almost Stopped Climate Change |pages=4– |work=The New York Times Magazine |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/08/01/magazine/climate-change-losing-earth.html |url-status=live |url-access=limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220115105222/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/08/01/magazine/climate-change-losing-earth.html |archive-date=15 January 2022 |issn=0028-7822}}</ref>  Global climate change became an international issue with the broadening of the concept of security which emerged in the 1980s in the post-Cold War era.The broadening of the concept of security sought to look beyond the military domain, and include political, economic, societal, and environmental areas in the security agenda.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Sheehan |first1=Michael J. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TnSBQgAACAAJ |title=International Security: An Analytical Survey |last2=Sheehan |first2=Professor Michael |date=2005 |publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers |isbn=978-1-58826-298-1 |language=en}}</ref> The term ''security'' can refer to a broad range of securities including national, international, ecological and [[human security]].

old_content: '''Matthew Seiyefa''' [[National Institute for Policy and Strategic Studies|MNI]] (born 17 October 1960) was the acting Director General of the Nigerian [[State Security Service (Nigeria)|State Security Service]] from 7 August 2018 till September 2018; he was appointed by Acting President, Prof. [[Yemi Osinbajo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-osinbajo-meets-dss-most-senior-director-seiyefa-magu/|title=Matthew Seiyefa appointed as Acting DG of DSS|date=2018-08-07|work=Punch Newspaper|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en-US}}</ref>
new_content: '''Matthew Seiyefa''' [[National Institute for Policy and Strategic Studies|MNI]] (born 17 October 1960) was the Director General of the Nigerian [[State Security Service (Nigeria)|State Security Service]] from 7 August 2018 till 14th September 2018; he was appointed by Acting President, Prof. [[Yemi Osinbajo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-osinbajo-meets-dss-most-senior-director-seiyefa-magu/|title=Matthew Seiyefa appointed as Acting DG of DSS|date=2018-08-07|work=Punch Newspaper|access-date=2018-08-22|language=en-US}}</ref>

(music)|medley]] of "Human Nature" and "[[Hung Up]]" (2005), wearing a t-shirt that read "BIG AS MADONNA".<ref name="DrakeeKiss">{{cite web |last1=Horowitz |first1=Steven J. |title=Drake sucks face revealed that he actually enjoyed the kiss, even posting a picture of the moment on his [[Instagram]] account.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duboff |first1=Josh |title=Drake says we shouldn't 'misinterpret 2015}}{{subscription}}</ref> Madonna did a "jazzy, percussive" rendition of "Human Nature" on the Madame X Tour.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Katz |first1=Leslie |title=Madonna’s Madame X comes alive, rises |url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/culture/madonna-s-madame-x-comes-alive-rises/article_9f5f2e3a-fdf2-5013-ac8f-b75e89617e6e.html |work=[[San Francisco Examiner]] |access-date=May 18, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230118222555/https://www.sfexaminer.com/culture/madonna-s-madame-x-comes-alive-rises/article_9f5f2e3a-fdf2-5013-ac8f-b75e89617e6e.html |archive-date=January 18, 2023 |date=November 6, 2019}}</ref> The performance saw her writhing "like a gymnastic clock inside a circular wall inset" surrounded by video imagery of pointing fingers, before doing a [[Bongo drum|bongo]] solo.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenblatt |first1=Leah |title=Madonna brings freewheeling intimacy to Madame X tour |url=https://ew.com/concerts/2019/09/20/madonna-madame-x-tour-review-brooklyn/ |work=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=May 18, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921024709/https://ew.com/concerts/2019/09/20/madonna-madame-x-tour-review-brooklyn/ |archive-date=September 21, 2019 |date=September 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pareles |first1=Jon |title=Madonna is still taking chances |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/18/arts/music/madame-x-madonna.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=May 18, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918162006/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/18/arts/music/madame-x-madonna.html |archive-date=September 18, 2019 |date=September |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/madonna-madame-x-tour-sheffield-887601/ |website=Rolling Stone |access-date=May 18, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920140528/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/madonna-madame-x-tour-sheffield-887601/ |archive-date=September 20, 2019 |date=September 20, 2019}}{{subscription}}</ref> The number ended with Madonna surrounded by 11 black women —including her daughters, Stella, Estere and Mercy James— chanting, "I'm not your bitch!".<ref name="RSMX" /> From ''[[Las Vegas Weekly]]'', Josh Bell considered "Human Nature" one of the songs that "fit best with the [concert's] theme of defiance". The song was included on both the [[Madame X (2021 film)|film that chronicled the tour]] and its [[Madame X: Music from the Theater Xperience|accompanying live album]].

old_content: The school started as Varkey International Private School in an effort to provide education to the [[Kerala Gulf diaspora|Keralite community]] living in the Emirates and was affiliated with the [[Kerala Board of Public Examination|Kerala State Board]]. The school was located in Al Gharoud until it moved to the current campus on Al Meydan Street. The school opened its doors to children in 1991 with Mrs. Annie George as its first principal who led the school until 1999. The school began with 438 students and 30 teachers and basic support staff. After its relocation in 2002, it was renamed Our Own Indian School in 2004 and again to its current name GEMS Our Own Indian School in 2012. Lalitha Suresh became the school's principal in 2012 along with other major changes that laid the foundation for the current school. The school received their first "Very-Good" DSIB rating for the academic year 2022-23. The school is expected to be a fully [[Mixed-sex education|co-ed]] school from the academic year 2024-25.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news |last=Saseendran |first=Sajila |date=December 13, 2016 |title=Ex-students, teachers reunite at silver jubilee of Dubai school |work=Gulf News |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/education/ex-students-teachers-reunite-at-silver-jubilee-of-dubai-school-1.1944367 |url-status=live |access-date=2023-05-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230429044455/https://gulfnews.com/uae/education/ex-students-teachers-reunite-at-silver-jubilee-of-dubai-school-1.1944367 |archive-date=29 April 2023}}</ref>

The school opened its doors to children in 1991 with Mrs. Annie George as its first principal who led the school until 1999. The school began with 438 students and 30 teachers and basic support staff. After its relocation in 2002, it was renamed Our Own Indian School in 2004 and again to its current name GEMS Our Own Indian School in 2012. The school received their first "Very-Good" DSIB rating for the academic year 2022-23. The school became a fully [[Mixed-sex education|co-ed]] school starting from the academic year 2024-25.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news |last=Saseendran |first=Sajila |date=December 13, 2016 |title=Ex-students, teachers reunite at silver jubilee of Dubai school |work=Gulf News |url=https://gulfnews.com/uae/education/ex-students-teachers-reunite-at-silver-jubilee-of-dubai-school-1.1944367 |url-status=live |access-date=2023-05-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230429044455/https://gulfnews.com/uae/education/ex-students-teachers-reunite-at-silver-jubilee-of-dubai-school-1.1944367 |archive-date=29 April 2023}}</ref>

old_content: *Article I states that the convention applies in "armed conflicts in which peoples are fighting against colonial domination and alien occupation and against racist régimes in the exercise of their right of self-determination."
new_content: *Article I states that the convention applies in "armed conflicts in which peoples are fighting against colonial domination and alien occupation and against racist régimes in the exercise of their right of self-determination", which has been interpreted as favoring terrorism,<ref>According to [https://scholarship.law.vanderbilt.edu/faculty-publications/636 "Exceptional Engagement: Protocol I and a World United Against Terrorism"] by Michael A. Newton (2009), ''Texas International Law Journal'' vol. 45, p 323: "The United States chose not to adopt the Protocol in the face of intensive international criticism because of its policy conclusions that the text contained overly expansive provisions resulting from politicized pressure to accord protection to terrorists who elected to conduct hostile military operations outside the established legal framework."</ref><ref>According to [https://ideaexchange.uakron.edu/akronlawreview/vol19/iss4/3 "Protocol I: Moving Humanitarian Law Backwards"] by Douglas J. Feith (1986), ''Akron Law Review'' vol. 19, issue 4, article 3, pg. 534: "In my view, the upshot of the Diplomatic Conference was a pro-terrorist treaty that calls itself humanitarian law. It is a vindication of the rhetoric, the aims, and the practices of terrorist organizations."</ref> and denying protections to Israel.<ref>According to "A Response to Douglas J. Feith's ''Law in the Service of Terror -- The Strange Case of the Additional Protocol''" by Waldemar A. Solf (1986), ''Akron Law Review'' vol. 20, issue 2, p. 285: "In view of the foregoing, it follows that the self determination provision in Art. 1(4) is largely symbolic and is not at all likely to present any practical problems in operations except that it automatically precludes Israel and South Africa from being parties to the Protocol, an unfortunate consequence in view of the military capability of both states in relation to their neighbors."</ref>

old_content: Thornton was recognized with the Medal of Honor for his actions of April 1972 by President [[Richard Nixon]] during a ceremony at the [[White House]] on October 15, 1973. He snuck Norris out of the hospital in the middle of the night so Norris could attend the ceremony. Norris was later awarded the Medal of Honor by President [[Gerald R. Ford]] in a White House ceremony on March 6, 1976. Thornton thus became the first Medal of Honor recipient recognized for saving the life of another Medal of Honor recipient. Norris lost an eye and part of his skull. He spent three years recovering from his injuries in the hospital and over a six-year period underwent many major surgeries. As a result of the head injury, he was medically retired from the Navy in May 1975.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.veterantributes.org/TributeDetail.php?recordID=2059|title=Veteran Tributes|website=www.veterantributes.org}}</ref>
new_content: Thornton was recognized with the Medal of Honor for his actions of April 1972 by President [[Richard Nixon]] during a ceremony at the [[White House]] on October 15, 1973. He snuck Norris out of the hospital in the middle of the night so Norris could attend the ceremony. Norris was later awarded the Medal of Honor by President [[Gerald R. Ford]] in a White House ceremony on March 6, 1976. Norris thus became the first Medal of Honor recipient recognized for their life having been saved by another Medal of Honor recipient. Norris lost an eye and part of his skull. He spent three years recovering from his injuries in the hospital and over a six-year period underwent many major surgeries. As a result of the head injury, he was medically retired from the Navy in May 1975.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.veterantributes.org/TributeDetail.php?recordID=2059|title=Veteran Tributes|website=www.veterantributes.org}}</ref>

old_content: The match will feature the winners of the [[2023–24 DFB-Pokal]] and [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]], the winners of the [[2023–24 Bundesliga]]. However, if Bayer Leverkusen beat [[1. FC Kaiserslautern]] in the [[2024 DFB-Pokal final]], completing a [[Double (association football)|domestic double]], the cup winners will be replaced by the runners-up of the Bundesliga. The winners of the DFB-Pokal (or runners-up of the Bundesliga) typically host the match, though this is subject to final confirmation by the DFL.
new_content: The match will feature the winners of the [[2023–24 DFB-Pokal]] and [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]], the winners of the [[2023–24 Bundesliga]]. However, if Bayer Leverkusen beat [[1. FC Kaiserslautern]] in the [[2024 DFB-Pokal final]], completing a [[Double (association football)|domestic double]], the cup winners will be replaced by the runners-up of the Bundesliga, [[VfB Stuttgart]]. The winners of the DFB-Pokal (or runners-up of the Bundesliga) typically host the match, though this is subject to final confirmation by the DFL.

old_content: On ''Glassheart'', Lewis reunites with [[Ryan Tedder]], record producer of her previous singles "[[Bleeding Love]]" and "[[Happy (Leona Lewis song)|Happy]]" and songwriter [[Andrea Martin (musician)|Andrea Martin]] who co-wrote "[[Better in Time]]", in addition to a number of new collaborators such as British duo [[Naughty Boy]] and [[Emeli Sandé]], [[Rodney "Darkchild" Jerkins]] and [[DJ Frank E]]. Producer [[Fraser T Smith]] executive produced the album after impressing Lewis with his work on ''[[Hurt: The EP]]'' (2011), a [[cover songs|cover]] song [[extended play]] (EP) that Lewis released to bridge the gap between ''[[Echo (Leona Lewis album)|Echo]]'' (2009) and ''Glassheart''.

old_content: Dufour has organized, co-organized or contributed essays to exhibitions and books on the art of Australian and Canadian modern and contemporary artists such as [[Howard Taylor]] (1985), Frank Nulf (1987), [[Dan Graham]] (1985), [[Max Pam]] (1986), [[Jochen Gerz]] (1994), and most famously, [[Jeff Wall]] (1990 and 2012)<ref name="RR " />, among others. old_content: Marsha P. Johnson was born Malcolm Michaels Jr. on August 24, 1945, in [[Elizabeth, New Jersey|Elizabeth]], [[New Jersey]],<ref name=BirthCertificate/><ref name=SSDI/> to father Malcolm Michaels Sr., an [[assembly line]] worker at [[General Motors]], and mother Alberta Claiborne, a housekeeper. They were raised alongside six siblings, and the family attended Mount Teman [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]].'''{{sfn|Chan|2018}}'''<ref name=AME-EJ>{{harvnb|Kasino|2012}}: events occur at 5:54. Note - Source misspells church name as "Mount Teamon". Website of church has correct spelling: [https://mttemaname.org/ Mount Teman AME Church] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210709185935/https://mttemaname.org/ |date=July 9, 2021 }}. old_content: On September 22, 2021, Titan Comics released under the Hard Case Crime imprint ''Gun Honey'' #1, Ardai's first written work for the comics medium. The book, which is drawn by Ang Hor Kheng, and features covers by [[Bill Sienkiewicz]], [[Robert McGinnis]], and [[Adam Hughes]], centers upon weapons smuggler Joanna Tan, who after helping a convict out of prison, is chosen by the U.S. government to track him down and return him.<ref name=CBR8.6.21/> The four-issue miniseries was conceived by Ardai when he conceived of Hard Case Crime Comics five years prior,<ref name=CBR6.25.21>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/titan-hard-case-crime-announce-gun-honey/|title=Titan and Hard Case Crime announce Gun Honey|publisher=Flickering Myth|author=Collinson, Gary|language=en-US|url-status=live|date=June 25, 2021|access-date=May 18, 2024|archive-date=May 18, 2024|archive-url=https://archive.ph/jiAu4}}</ref> and he has likened ''Gun Honey'' to other espionage action thrillers that influenced it, such as [[James Bond]],<ref name=FreakSugar>{{cite web|url=https://www.freaksugar.com/interview-charles-ardai-on-illusion-danger-in-heat-seeker-a-gun-honey-series/|publisher=Freak Sugar|title=INTERVIEW: CHARLES ARDAI ON ILLUSION & DANGER IN HEAT SEEKER: A GUN HONEY SERIES!|author=Keith, Jed W.|language=en-US|url-status=live|date=April 28, 2023|access-date=May 18, 2024|archive-date=May 18, 2024|archive-url=https://archive.ph/13JzB}}</ref> as well as action/adventure stories featuring female protagonists, such as [[Modesty Blaise]], ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]'', ''[[Kill Bill]]'',<ref name=CBR6.25.21/> and ''[[Barbarella (comics)|Barbarella]]''.<ref name=FreakSugar/> At the review aggregator website Comic Book Roundup, the debut issue has a rating of 8 out of 10, based on eight critics' reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbookroundup.com/comic-books/reviews/titan-books/gun-honey/1|title=Gun Honey #1|publisher=Comic Book Roundup|language=en-US|url-status=live|date=September 29, 2021|access-date=May 18, 2024|archive-date=September 29, 2021|archive-url=https://archive.ph/qkfYF}}</ref> The series was collected in [[trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]] form in May 2023 under the title ''Gun Honey: Honey for Blood''. The story was followed by a sequel, ''Gun Honey: Blood for Blood'', in which Joanna and her ally, a government agent named Brook Barrow, are framed for murder.<ref name=FreakSugar/> That miniseries premiered August 24, 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leagueofcomicgeeks.com/comics/series/156628/gun-honey-blood-for-blood|title=Gun Honey: Blood for Blood|publisher=League of Comic Geeks|language=en-US|url-status=live|date=August 24, 2022|access-date=May 18, 2024|archive-date=May 18, 2024|archive-url=https://archive.ph/dxJwL}}</ref> It was followed by a four-issue spinoff series, ''Heat Seeker: A Gun Honey Series'', also written by Ardai, with art by Ace Continuado, Jose Zapata, and Asifur Rahman. The book, whose debut issue was released on June 28, 2023, sees Tan going on the run after she is targeted for assassination by the U.S. government. Pursued by a beautiful sociopath hitwoman named Sarah Claride, Tan seeks help from her friend, stage magician and illusionist Dahlia Racers, who specializes in helping people disappear.<ref name=FreakSugar/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/titan-comics-gun-honey-spinoff-heat-seeker/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Titan's Pulp Spy Thriller Gun Honey Expands With New Spinoff Series|publisher=[[CBR.com]]|author=Schreuer, Brandon|language=en-US|url-status=live|date=February 20, 2023|access-date=May 18, 2024|archive-date=May 18, 2024|archive-url=https://archive.ph/tcHkJ}}</ref> The next installment in the series was the miniseries ''Gun Honey: Collision Course'', whose debut issue was released May 15, 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leagueofcomicgeeks.com/comics/series/174445/gun-honey-collision-course|title=Gun Honey: Collision Course|publisher=League of Comic Geeks|language=en-US|url-status=live|date=May 15, 2024|access-date=May 18, 2024|archive-date=May 18, 2024|archive-url=https://archive.ph/pMH3P}}</ref>

old_content: Notts started the season strongly; Hughes scored a [[hat-trick]] on the opening day as the Magpies defeated Bradford 5–0 at home with over 9,000 spectators in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8186374.stm |title=Notts County   5 - 0   Bradford |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=24 December 2023 |date=8 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090811003650/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_3/8186374.stm |archive-date=11 August 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> The team won 4–0 at [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] in its first away game,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8199993.stm |title=Macclesfield   0 - 4   Notts County |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=8 February 2024 |date=15 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210609044548/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_3/8199993.stm |archive-date=9 June 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> but then suffered its first defeat, losing 2–1 at [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8207188.stm |title=Chesterfield   2 - 1   Notts County |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=8 February 2024 |date=19 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221220030030/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8207188.stm |archive-date=20 December 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> During August, the club used its apparent new-found wealth to strengthen its squad, signing goalkeeper [[Kasper Schmeichel]] from [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] for an undisclosed fee believed to surpass the club record.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/notts_county/8201444.stm |title=Magpies snap up keeper Schmeichel |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=24 December 2023 |date=14 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090816232200/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/n/notts_county/8201444.stm |archive-date=16 August 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> Schmeichel made his debut in a 3–0 home win over [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.|Dagenham & Redbridge]] on 22 August.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8207887.stm |title=Notts County   3 - 0   Dag & Red |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=8 February 2024 |date=22 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201142818/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_3/8207887.stm |archive-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Three days later, Notts announced the signing of England international [[Sol Campbell]] on a five-year contract: "there were offers from the Premier League but that would have been short-term. I'm thinking of the future," he told the BBC.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/notts_county/8218136.stm |title=Campbell seals Notts County move |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=5 February 2024 |date=25 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221025124013/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/n/notts_county/8218136.stm |archive-date=25 October 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> Campbell did not play immediately, and Notts were beaten 1–0 at [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] in their final match of the month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8220671.stm |title=Barnet   1 - 0   Notts County |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=8 February 2024 |date=29 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201121220125/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/8220671.stm |archive-date=21 November 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>

old_content: In several places there is a statement of the number of churches and the number of countries that they have churches in, sourced only to themselves. This really really needs secondary sourcing, even if only to place their claims in the context of an independent review. Not only for the usual reasons (e.g what do they count as a "member", some orgs inflate numbers by counting anyone they even had contact with as a member) but their general lack of physical churches leaves room for definition of a "church" (and thus also "country with a church) different than the common meaning of a church. For example, counting two people who meet at someone's house a "church" and thus also as a country where they have a church. This is different that just self-sourcing things like beliefs, because it is prima facie an objective fact, and one very relevant for a reader wanting to learn about the church. ''North8000'' ([[User talk:North8000#top|talk]]) 13:19, 17 May 2024 (UTC)

old_content: '''X''' is an American [[social media]] company based in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], which operated and was named for [[Twitter|its flagship social media network]] prior to its rebrand as X. In addition to Twitter, the company previously operated the [[Vine (service)|Vine]] short video app and [[Periscope (service)|Periscope]] livestreaming service. In April 2023, Twitter merged with X Holdings<ref>{{Cite news |last=Conger |first=Kate |date=October 28, 2022 |title=How Twitter Will Change as a Private Company |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/28/technology/twitter-changes.html |url-access=limited |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221028102502/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/28/technology/twitter-changes.html |archive-date=October 28, 2022 |access-date=October 28, 2022 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and ceased to be an independent company, becoming a part of [[X Corp.]]<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Wei |first1=De Wei |last2=Katanuma |first2=Marika |date=April 11, 2023 |title=Twitter Company 'No Longer Exists,' Is Now Part of Musk's X |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-11/twitter-becomes-x-corp-as-musk-advances-everything-app-hopes |url-access=limited |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230411123949/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-11/twitter-becomes-x-corp-as-musk-advances-everything-app-hopes?leadSource=uverify%20wall |archive-date=April 11, 2023 |access-date=April 11, 2023 |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>
new_content: '''X''' is an American [[social media]] company based in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], which operated and was named for [[Twitter|its flagship social media network]]. In addition to Twitter, the company previously operated the [[Vine (service)|Vine]] short video app and [[Periscope (service)|Periscope]] livestreaming service. In April 2023, Twitter merged with X Holdings<ref>{{Cite news |last=Conger |first=Kate |date=October 28, 2022 |title=How Twitter Will Change as a Private Company |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/28/technology/twitter-changes.html |url-access=limited |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221028102502/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/28/technology/twitter-changes.html |archive-date=October 28, 2022 |access-date=October 28, 2022 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and ceased to be an independent company, becoming a part of [[X Corp.]]<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Wei |first1=De Wei |last2=Katanuma |first2=Marika |date=April 11, 2023 |title=Twitter Company 'No Longer Exists,' Is Now Part of Musk's X |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-11/twitter-becomes-x-corp-as-musk-advances-everything-app-hopes |url-access=limited |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230411123949/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-11/twitter-becomes-x-corp-as-musk-advances-everything-app-hopes?leadSource=uverify%20wall |archive-date=April 11, 2023 |access-date=April 11, 2023 |publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>

old_content: Pearl millet (''Pennisetum glaucum'') was domesticated in the Sahel region of West Africa from ''Pennisetum violaceum''.<ref name="D'Andrea Casey 2002"/>{{rp|160}} Early archaeological evidence in Africa  includes finds at [[Kintampo Complex|Birimi]] in northern Ghana (1740 [[Radiocarbon_dating#Reporting_dates|cal BC]]) and  [[Dhar Tichitt]] in [[Mauritania]] (1936–1683 cal BC) and the lower Tilemsi valley in [[Mali]] (2500 to 2000 cal BC).<ref name="D'Andrea Casey 2002"/><ref name="Manning Pelling Higham 2011"> Studies of [[isozyme|isozymes]] suggest domestication took place north east of the [[Senegal River]] in the far west of the Sahel and tentatively around 6000 BC.<ref name="D'Andrea Casey 2002">{{Cite journal  |last1=D'Andrea |first1=A. C. |last2=Casey |first2=J. |title=Pearl Millet and Kintampo Subsistence |journal=The African Archaeological Review |date=2002 |access-date=18 May 2024 |jstor=25130746 |issn=0263-0338 |volume=19 |issue=3 |pages=147–173 |url=https://link-springer-com.stanford.idm.oclc.org/article/10.1023/A:1016518919072 |doi=10.1023/A:1016518919072 |s2cid=162042735}}</ref><ref name="Manning Pelling Higham 2011">{{cite journal |last1=Manning |first1=Katie |last2=Pelling |first2=Ruth |last3=Higham |first3=Tom |last4=Schwenniger |first4=Jean-Luc |last5=Fuller |first5=Dorian Q. |title=4500-Year old domesticated pearl millet (Pennisetum glaucum) from the Tilemsi Valley, Mali: new insights into an alternatives are cereal domestication pathway |journal=Journal of Archaeological Science |doi=10.1016/j.jas.2010.09.007 |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=312–322 |year=2011 |bibcode=2011JArSc..38..312M }}</ref> Pearl millet had arrived in the [[Indian subcontinent]] by 2000 BC to 1700 BC.<ref name="Manning Pelling Higham 2011"/>

old_content: Many interpretations to the lyrics of "American Pie" have been proposed. ''[[The Washington Post]]'' stated that the song "includes references to [[Karl Marx]]; [[Vladimir Ilyich Lenin]] (or, more likely, [[John Lennon]]); the [[The Beatles|Fab Four]]; the [[Byrds]]; [[James Dean]]; [[Charles Manson]]; the [[Rolling Stones]]; the 'widowed bride,' [[Jackie Kennedy]]; and the [[Vietnam War]]".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/04/08/gloomy-don-mclean-reveals-meaning-of-american-pie-and-sells-lyrics-for-1-2-million/ |title=Archived copy |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=May 4, 2023 |archive-date=March 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309034527/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/04/08/gloomy-don-mclean-reveals-meaning-of-american-pie-and-sells-lyrics-for-1-2-million/ |url-status=live }}</ref> However, McLean has denied many of these interpretations, including claims that he was referencing the [[Beatles]] on the song.<ref name="Axelrod">{{Cite web|date=March 29, 2017|title=Don McLean explains why he won't reveal the meaning of "American Pie"|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/don-mclean-explains-why-he-wont-reveal-the-meaning-of-american-pie/|website=CBS News|access-date=March 30, 2017|quote="But the quartet practicing in the park, that's not the Beatles?" Axelrod asked. "No," McLean replied.|archive-date=March 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330024905/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/don-mclean-explains-why-he-wont-reveal-the-meaning-of-american-pie/|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Bob Dylan]] was also appointed to be the "jester" who "[stole] the limelight from [[Elvis Presley]] as the new messiah" in the line "And while the king was looking down / The jester stole his thorny crown", but McLean did not recognized this either, saying: "I certainly would have mentioned Dylan's name if I had meant to mention him. I would have said Bob or something else, but I didn't 'cause it ain't him".<ref>https://americansongwriter.com/13-american-pie-song-references-revealed-by-don-mclean-the-king-girl-who-sang-the-blues-and-more/</ref><ref name=guardian/> In 2017, Dylan was asked about how he was reportedly referenced in the song, and replied, "A jester? Sure, the jester writes songs like '[[Masters of War]]', '[[A Hard Rain's a-Gonna Fall]]', '[[It's Alright, Ma (I'm Only Bleeding)|It's Alright, Ma]]' – some jester. I have to think he's talking about somebody else. Ask him."<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bob-dylans-surprise-new-interview-9-things-we-learned-w473397|title=Bob Dylan's Surprise New Interview: 9 Things We Learned|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=March 23, 2017|access-date=March 26, 2017|archive-date=March 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325174348/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bob-dylans-surprise-new-interview-9-things-we-learned-w473397|url-status=live}}</ref> Apparent allusions to notable 1950s songs include [[Don Cornell]]'s "[[The Bible Tells Me So]]" ("If the Bible tells you so?"), [[Marty Robbins]]' "[[A White Sport Coat]]", the lonely teenager ("With a pink carnation") mirroring Robbins' narrator who is rejected in favor of another man for the prom, and [[The Monotones]]' "[[The Book of Love (The Monotones song)|The Book of Love]]" ("Did you write the book of love").<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shuck|first1=Raymond|title=Do You Believe in Rock and Roll?: Essays on Don McLean's "American Pie" |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ri4TR522ONQC|year=2012|isbn=978-0-786-47105-8|pages=55, 56 & 57|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]}}</ref>

old_content: '''Batteries Included''' was a [[computer software]] and [[computer hardware|hardware]] company based in the [[Toronto]] area.  It developed products for the [[Apple II]], [[Atari 8-bit family]], [[Atari ST]], [[Commodore 64]], and [[MS-DOS]].<ref name="atarimag">{{cite journal|title=New Products From Batteries Included|journal=Compute!|issue=74|page=117|year=1986|url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue74/news_and_products.php}}</ref> The company was best known in the 1980s for its [[PaperClip]] [[word processor]], which was available for the Atari 8-bit family and Commodore 64, and the [[DEGAS (software)|DEGAS]] bitmap painting program for the [[Atari ST]]. Batteries Included was acquired by [[Electronic Arts]] in 1987.
new_content: '''Batteries Included''' was a [[computer software]] and [[computer hardware|hardware]] company based in the [[Toronto]] area.  It developed products for the [[Apple II]], [[Atari 8-bit computers]], [[Atari ST]], [[Commodore 64]], and [[MS-DOS]].<ref name="atarimag">{{cite journal|title=New Products From Batteries Included|journal=Compute!|issue=74|page=117|year=1986|url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue74/news_and_products.php}}</ref> The company was best known in the 1980s for its [[PaperClip]] [[word processor]], which was available for the Atari 8-bit family and Commodore 64, and the [[DEGAS (software)|DEGAS]] bitmap painting program for the [[Atari ST]]. Batteries Included was acquired by [[Electronic Arts]] in 1987.

old_content: Dufour has organized, co-organized or contributed essays to exhibitions and books on the art of Australian and Canadian modern and contemporary artists such as [[Howard Taylor]] (1985), Frank Nulf (1987), [[Dan Graham]] (1985), [[Max Pam]] (1986), [[Jochen Gerz]] (1994), and most famously, [[Jeff Wall]] (1990 and 2012)<ref name="RR " />, among others. (Dufour edited Wall's ''Catalogue Raisonné: 2005-2021'', called a "lavish presentation" by [[Goodreads]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=article |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/61463048-jeff-wall |website=www.goodreads.com |publisher=Goodreads |access-date=17 May 2024}}</ref> In spring 2024, Dufour wrote articles about [[Morris Louis]] and [[Kenneth Noland]] for the Post-War & Contemporary Art catalogue, [[Heffel Fine Art Auction House]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web |title=Exhibitions |url=https://www.heffel.com/Auction/Lots_E?Request=iZTDNdl2DfJc8jRi4pFzNF4FyYcqe80krsL77dDV7HCow9OTQA64f+VG3CAWm7cEchYbhdamiG4QqZBq3+9/h3jCd2/G0rWJmZTIW29ZnNUDIwLR3xhVjKSt7bMZjbN20UrmehZOFtaXQaZ5Byn7VDjAeK2tE5LNb0h6Nv37XOoG1ulXf7wlnV6X5xvZ5t0oD4GsZjmNA/bDIOSckNJAYKSEiykQH/p195KqQhNw2QY= |website=www.heffel.com |publisher=Heffel Auction House |access-date=18 May 2024}}</ref>

old_content: On January 7, 2024, congressional appropriators reached an agreement on the topline spending levels for 2024 which was not substantially different from the deal negotiated by McCarthy.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bogage |first=Jacob |date=January 7, 2024 |title=Congressional leaders reach deal that would avert government shutdown |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2024/01/07/congress-budget-deal/ |access-date=January 7, 2024 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-01-09 |title=Opinion {{!}} House Republicans are right back where they started on spending |url=https://www.msnbc.com/opinion/msnbc-opinion/house-republicans-spending-deal-government-shutdown-rcna132860 |access-date=2024-03-25 |website=MSNBC.com |language=en}}</ref> Hardliners attempted to push Johnson to abandon the deal, initially claiming that he had done so before Johnson clarified that he hadn't.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Solender |first=Andrew and Brufke, Juliegrace |date=January 11, 2024 |title=Mike Johnson faces major test as rebels push to blow up spending deal |url=https://www.axios.com/2024/01/12/mike-johnson-spending-republicans-shutdown |access-date=March 25, 2024 |website=Axios}}</ref> As negotiations continued over the full-year funding bills, conservatives pushed Johnson to instead endorse a full-year continuing resolution, which under McCarthy's deal would result in automatic spending cuts.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Speaker Johnson is defying his right wing on budget deal. old_content: Nkosi was born to Nontlhantlha Daphne Nkosi in a village near [[Dannhauser]] in 1989.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4195336 "One Boy's Heroism in the Face of Aids"] ''NPR.org'' [Retrieved 27 March 2013]</ref> He never knew his father. Nkosi was HIV-positive from birth, and was legally [[adoption|adopted]] by Gail Johnson, a Johannesburg Public Relations practitioner, when his own mother, debilitated by the disease, was no longer able to care for him.<ref>{{cite news | title = Nkosi Johnson dies as he lived, a symbol of the tragedy of Aids |first=Mary|last=Braid | work = The Independent| date = 2001-06-02 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/nkosi-johnson-dies-as-he-lived-a-symbol-of-the-tragedy-of-aids-672533.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080405095453/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/africa/nkosi-johnson-dies-as-he-lived-a-symbol-of-the-tragedy-of-aids-672533.html | url-status = dead | archive-date = 5 April 2008 | accessdate = 2008-06-03}}</ref>

old_content: After the [[Japanese invasion of Manchuria]] in 1931, the state of Manchukuo was created in 1932. On February 27, 1933 the [[League of Nations]] voted 42–1 to condemn Japanese military occupation of Manchuria. Japan was the lone dissenter, with [[Siam]] abstaining and 13 other nations absent.<ref>"League Brands Japan Breaker of World Pact – Tokio Delegates Walk Out When Policy Is Condemned by Geneva Envoys", ''St. Petersburg Times'', February 24, 1933, p. 1; Piers Brendon, ''The Dark Valley: A Panorama of the 1930s'' (Random House Digital, 2002) p. 228</ref> El Salvador was one of the absentee countries at the vote.<ref name=q9>[https://www.proquest.com/historical-newspapers/league-unable-impeach-salvador-say-japan-jurists/docview/1416660294/se-2 League unable to impeach Salvador, say Japan jurists: Article 16 said to apply only to parties in 2- sided dispute, argue Nippon experts council yet has no official notification of puppet recognition; "Manchukuo" replies]. (The China Press. 1934, May 24)</ref>

old_content: [[Crossbows]] made with bronze parts were produced in [[China]] during the [[Warring States period]]. The [[Qin Shi Huang|Qin Emperor]] unified China at least in part by equipping large armies with these weapons, which were equipped with a sophisticated trigger mechanism made of interchangeable parts.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Mass-Produced Pre-Han Chinese Bronze Crossbow Triggers: Unparalleled Manufacturing Technology in the Ancient World |first=David |last=Williams |magazine=Arms & Armour |volume=5 |number=2 |date=October 2008 |pages= 142-153(12) |url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/maney/aaa/2008/00000005/00000002/art00003 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211212949/http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/maney/aaa/2008/00000005/00000002/art00003 |archive-date=11 December 2013}}</ref> The [[Terracotta Army]] guarding the Emperor's [[necropolis]] is also believed to have been created through the use of standardized molds on an [[assembly line]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TrPmZXt-wIEC&pg=PA27 |title=The Terra Cotta Warriors |work=National Geographic Museum |page=27 |access-date=7 December 2021 |archive-date=29 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230329073020/https://books.google.com/books?id=TrPmZXt-wIEC&pg=PA27 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Portal |first=Jane |title=The First Emperor: China's Terracotta Army |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DWRTFl36nksC |publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] |year=2007 |page=170 |isbn=978-0-674-02697-1 |access-date=7 December 2021 |archive-date=16 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231016112831/https://books.google.com/books?id=DWRTFl36nksC |url-status=live }}</ref>

old_content: '''George Kunkel''' (December 29, 1866 – November 8, 1937) was an American [[character actor]]<ref name="Katchmer">Katchmer, p. 194-195</ref> and opera singer.<ref name="Simpson"> Simpson, p. 152</ref> On screen, he was a star of the [[silent film]] era.<ref name="Wilson">Wilson, p. p. 418</ref> On the stage he portrayed comic [[tenor]] and [[baritone]] roles in [[light opera]]s,<ref name="Simpson"/> and also appeared in both comic and dramatic roles in plays. He should not be confused with his father; the theatre manager, minstrel show performer, and songwriter [[George Kunkel (theatre manager)|George Kunkel]] (1823–1885).
new_content: '''George Kunkel''' (December 29, 1866 – November 8, 1937) was an American [[character actor]]<ref name="Katchmer">Katchmer, p. 194-195</ref> and opera singer.<ref name="Simpson"> Simpson, p. 152</ref> On screen, he was a star of the [[silent film]] era from 1913-1921.<ref name="Wilson">Wilson, p. p. 418</ref> On the stage he portrayed comic [[tenor]] and [[baritone]] roles in [[light opera]]s,<ref name="Simpson"/> and also appeared in both comic and dramatic roles in plays. old_content: ''[[The Times]]'''s review of the first UK performance described it as being "in the spirit of the Brandenburg Concertos of Bach.  Indeed, Mr Holst has here come nearer to formal perfection than in any of his previous works, without abandoning his individual point of view."<ref>https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&retrievalId=1a76d03e-4f14-41e6-a081-f01086ae693e&hitCount=70&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=2&docId=GALE%7CCS118691148&docType=Review&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&pageNum=1&contentSet=GALE%7CCS118691148&searchId=R3&userGroupName=bright&inPS=true</ref>   However, one composer called it "desiccated",{{sfn|Holst|1958|p=88}} and many other early critical judgements were sparing of praise or outright hostile.  A second critique in ''The Times'' in 1924 conceded that it "is fun, of course, but rather heavy fun; the penalty of jokes is that they ill bear repetition";<ref>https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&retrievalId=ee7febb2-3d16-4ea4-840f-7a888f3ad6f1&hitCount=70&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=4&docId=GALE%7CCS202315388&docType=Review&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&pageNum=1&contentSet=GALE%7CCS202315388&searchId=R3&userGroupName=bright&inPS=true</ref> and a third in 1935 wrote of its "ingenious triviality".<ref>https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&retrievalId=d84485d0-024b-4d06-9e35-0342030962b2&hitCount=70&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=12&docId=GALE%7CCS235351223&docType=Review&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&pageNum=1&contentSet=GALE%7CCS235351223&searchId=R3&userGroupName=bright&inPS=true</ref>  The critic [[Dyneley Hussey]] thought the ''Fugal Concerto'' and the ''Fugal Overture'' "perverse exercises in the contrapuntal style, devoid of any warmth and with none of the real vitality which appears in the earlier '[[St Paul's Suite|St Paul's' Suite]] for strings."<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JzgrAQAAMAAJ&q=%22perverse+exercises+in+the+contrapuntal+style%22&dq=%22perverse+exercises+in+the+contrapuntal+style%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjtw9GXtJCGAxUfVEEAHUqjBXoQ6AF6BAgHEAI (see Man p. XLV for ref)</ref>  American reviews could be as bad.  [[Olin Downes]] wrote that it was "smoothly written, and if a certain middle-of-the-road and eminently respectable manner is really typical of English music, then it is evident that this music is English."  ''[[Musical America]]'' believed that it "scarcely explain[s] the great renown [Holst] enjoys".<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SnHpuUKDQ5MC&pg=PA212&dq=holst+%22fugal+concerto%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjPhoXl1YiGAxU2BNsEHZb9AF4Q6AF6BAgEEAI#v=onepage&q=holst%20%22fugal%20concerto%22&f=false</ref>  A 1967 recording of the work was similarly dismissed as "little more than an academic study"; it was "much less taking [than the ''[[Lyric Movement]]''] with none of [its] character or inspiration".<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uoVHAAAAMAAJ&q=%22little+more+than+an+academic+study%22+%22much+less+taking%22&dq=%22little+more+than+an+academic+study%22+%22much+less+taking%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiK7Muq6JKGAxW4WkEAHYPNAnQQ6AF6BAgIEAI</ref>

Indeed, Mr Holst has here come nearer to formal perfection than in any of his previous works, without abandoning his individual point of view."<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--not stated--> |date=12 October 1923 |title=The Promenade Concerts. Mr Holst's Fugal Concerto |work=The Times |location=London |page=7 }}</ref>   However, one composer called it "desiccated",{{sfn|Holst|1958|p=88}} and many other early critical judgements were sparing of praise or outright hostile.  A second critique in ''The Times'' in 1924 conceded that it "is fun, of course, but rather heavy fun; the penalty of jokes is that they ill bear repetition";<ref>https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&retrievalId=ee7febb2-3d16-4ea4-840f-7a888f3ad6f1&hitCount=70&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=4&docId=GALE%7CCS202315388&docType=Review&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&pageNum=1&contentSet=GALE%7CCS202315388&searchId=R3&userGroupName=bright&inPS=true</ref> and a third in 1935 wrote of its "ingenious triviality".<ref>https://go.gale.com/ps/retrieve.do?tabID=Newspapers&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&searchResultsType=SingleTab&retrievalId=d84485d0-024b-4d06-9e35-0342030962b2&hitCount=70&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=12&docId=GALE%7CCS235351223&docType=Review&sort=Pub+Date+Forward+Chron&contentSegment=ZTMA-MOD1&prodId=TTDA&pageNum=1&contentSet=GALE%7CCS235351223&searchId=R3&userGroupName=bright&inPS=true</ref>  The critic [[Dyneley Hussey]] thought the ''Fugal Concerto'' and the ''Fugal Overture'' "perverse exercises in the contrapuntal style, devoid of any warmth and with none of the real vitality which appears in the earlier '[[St Paul's Suite|St Paul's' Suite]] for strings."<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JzgrAQAAMAAJ&q=%22perverse+exercises+in+the+contrapuntal+style%22&dq=%22perverse+exercises+in+the+contrapuntal+style%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjtw9GXtJCGAxUfVEEAHUqjBXoQ6AF6BAgHEAI (see Man p. XLV for ref)</ref>  American reviews could be as bad.  [[Olin Downes]] wrote that it was "smoothly written, and if a certain middle-of-the-road and eminently respectable manner is really typical of English music, then it is evident that this music is English."  ''[[Musical America]]'' believed that it "scarcely explain[s] the great renown [Holst] enjoys".<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SnHpuUKDQ5MC&pg=PA212&dq=holst+%22fugal+concerto%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjPhoXl1YiGAxU2BNsEHZb9AF4Q6AF6BAgEEAI#v=onepage&q=holst%20%22fugal%20concerto%22&f=false</ref>  A 1967 recording of the work was similarly dismissed as "little more than an academic study"; it was "much less taking [than the ''[[Lyric Movement]]''] with none of [its] character or inspiration".<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uoVHAAAAMAAJ&q=%22little+more+than+an+academic+study%22+%22much+less+taking%22&dq=%22little+more+than+an+academic+study%22+%22much+less+taking%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiK7Muq6JKGAxW4WkEAHYPNAnQQ6AF6BAgIEAI</ref>

old_content: Social movements and organizations, such as [[Climate Justice Alliance|Climate Justice alliance]], We are Dissenters, Grassroots Global Justice Alliance, [[Indigenous Environmental Network]], call for a bigger emphasis on [[climate justice]] and [[environmental justice]] rather than climate security. Climate justice puts the emphasis on the root causes of climate change, like colonialism and [[neocolonialism]], [[global inequality]], [[globalization]] and exploitative economic systems such as the [[exploitation of natural resources]]. Many call this addressing the era of [https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2022/09/colonialism-climate-change-pakistan-floods/ climate colonialism]. Indeed, many proponents of climate justice call for bigger support for [[Climate change and indigenous peoples#:~:text=Effects of climate change on,floods, droughts and extreme weather.|Indigenous people]] and other frontline communities that are fighting for climate change and also already protecting 80% of Earth’s biodiversity.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2020-10-12 |title=Why protecting Indigenous communities can also help save the Earth |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/climate-academy/2020/oct/12/indigenous-communities-protect-biodiversity-curb-climate-crisis |access-date=2023-05-25 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

old_content: Lewis was born in [[Leonardtown, Maryland]], and raised in [[New Port Richey, Florida]]. In his youth, in the early and mid-seventies, he was a member of [[Yogi Bhajan|Yogi Bhajan's]] [[3HO]], a new religious movement combining the teachings of [[kundalini yoga]] and [[Sikhism]]. Feeling disenchanted with the organization, he formed a small and short-lived breakaway movement.<ref name="LewisMarburg">{{cite journal |author=Lewis |first=James R. |year=2010 |title=Autobiography of a Schism |url=http://www.uni-marburg.de/fb03/ivk/mjr/pdfs/2010/articles/lewis_2010.pdf |url-status=dead |journal=[[Marburg Journal of Religion]] |language=en-US |volume=15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719110206/http://www.uni-marburg.de/fb03/ivk/mjr/pdfs/2010/articles/lewis_2010.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-19}}</ref>

old_content: '''Maureen Matthews''' is the mother of [[Julie Matthews (Hollyoaks)|Julie Matthews]]. After Julie got engaged to [[Tony Hutchinson]] ([[Nick Pickard]]) in 1997, Maureen ended up obsessing over the wedding plans to Tony's chagrin. On their wedding day in August 1997, Maureen was left mortified when Julie jilted Tony at the altar and attempted to convince her to return to the church and marry Tony. However, Mr. Matthews ordered Maureen to be quiet and took Julie home.''
new_content: '''Maureen Matthews''' is the mother of [[Julie Matthews (Hollyoaks)|Julie Matthews]]. After Julie got engaged to [[Tony Hutchinson]] ([[Nick Pickard]]) in 1997, Maureen ended up obsessing over the wedding plans to Tony's chagrin. On their wedding day in August 1997, Maureen was left mortified when Julie jilted Tony at the altar and attempted to convince her to return to the church and marry Tony. However, Mr. Matthews ordered Maureen to be quiet and took Julie home.

old_content: '''Ayswaria Wariar'''<ref>{{Cite news |date=2013-03-14 |title=Engaging Mohiniyattam |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/dance/engaging-mohiniyattam/article4508399.ece |access-date=2024-05-18 |work=The Hindu |language=en-IN |issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2014-06-19 |title=Charmed and beyond |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/dance/charmed-and-beyond/article6129825.ece |access-date=2024-05-18 |work=The Hindu |language=en-IN |issn=0971-751X}}</ref> also known as Aishwarya Warrier (born 1975), is a [[Mohiniyattam]] dancer, art educator, choreographer, and researcher. Born in [[Calicut]], Kerala, Ayswaria grew up in [[Mumbai]] and later settled in Vadodara, [[Gujarat]]. She was initiated into the art of Indian classical dance at the age of five by her mother, Sreebala Menon. As a child, Ayswaria was also a voice over artist, working under the guidance of her father, Mukundan Menon, who was a speaker and script writer at the Films Division of India. Subsequently, Ayswaria trained in the two styles of [[Bharatanatyam]] and [[Mohiniyattam]] under eminent Gurus such as Dr.[[Sucheta Bhide Chapekar]], Udyogamandal Vikraman, and Kalamandalam Saraswathi.<ref>https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/lifestyle/news-detail-646698</ref> Ayswaria learnt the finer aspects of netrabhinaya from Margi Usha, and she obtained guidance in Sopana Sangeetham under [[Padma Bhushan]] [[Kavalam Narayana Panicker]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kannan |first=Arathi |date=2016-12-24 |title=Retelling ‘her’ stories through Mohiniyattam |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/thiruvananthapuram/2016/Dec/23/retelling-her-stories-through-mohiniyattam-1552399.html |access-date=2024-05-18 |website=The New Indian Express |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Kannan |first=Arathi |date=2017-04-01 |title=Beyond the blue yonder |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/kochi/2017/Apr/01/beyond-the-blue-yonder-1588356.html |access-date=2024-05-18 |website=The New Indian Express |language=en}}</ref> She is the artistic director of Nrityodaya School of Classical Dance, Vadodara, Gujarat and the Director at Ayswaria's Institute for Creative Expression (A I C E), Navi Mumbai, Maharashtra.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Backer |first=Anila |date=2015-11-07 |title=Spreading the Grace of Mohiniyattom |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/thiruvananthapuram/2015/Nov/07/spreading-the-grace-of-mohiniyattom-839949.html |access-date=2024-05-18 |website=The New Indian Express |language=en}}</ref>

old_content: The Library collects and maintains the internal documents of the tobacco companies and their trade organizations that were a party to the Master Settlement Agreement as well as documents from other litigation or companies not party to the settlement. Among the documents are more than 8,000 tobacco industry video and audio tapes including recordings of focus groups, internal corporate meetings, depositions of tobacco industry employees, government hearings, corporate communications, and commercials. Many of the acquired tapes are available for viewing or listening on the [[Internet Archive]] at the UCSF Tobacco Industry Videos Collection.<ref>{{Cite web|title=UCSF Tobacco Archives|url=https://archive.org/details/tobaccoarchives|url-status=live|access-date=2021-08-16|website=archive.org}}</ref>

old_content: The concept of existence played a central role in [[Islamic philosophy|Arabic-Persian philosophy]]. [[Avicenna]] (980–1037 CE) and [[Al-Ghazali]] (1058–1111 CE) discussed the relationship between existence and essence, and said the essence of an entity is prior to its existence. The additional step of instantiating the essence is required for the entity to come into existence. [[Mulla Sadra]] (1571–1636 CE) rejected this priority of essence over existence, and said essence is only a concept that is used by the mind to grasp existence. Existence, by contrast, encompasses the whole of reality, according to his view.<ref>{{multiref |1={{harvnb|Leaman|2002|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=_4crBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA77 77–78]}} |2={{harvnb|DeGrood|1976|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=3vYOp1AGpVUC&pg=PA37 37]}} |3={{harvnb|Dalal|2010|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=pNmfdAKFpkQC&pg=PA41 41–42]}} }}</ref>
new_content: The concept of existence played a central role in [[Islamic philosophy|Arabic-Persian philosophy]]. [[Avicenna]] (980–1037 CE) and [[Al-Ghazali]] (1058–1111 CE) discussed the relationship between existence and essence, and said the essence of an entity is prior to its existence. The additional step of instantiating the essence is required for the entity to come into existence. [[Mulla Sadra]] (1571–1636 CE) rejected this priority of essence over existence, and said essence is only a concept that is used by the mind to grasp existence. Existence, by contrast, encompasses the whole of reality, according to his view.<ref>{{multiref |1={{harvnb|Leaman|2002|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=_4crBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA77 77–78]}} |2={{harvnb|DeGrood|1976|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=3vYOp1AGpVUC&pg=PA37 37]}} |3={{harvnb|Dalal|2010a|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=pNmfdAKFpkQC&pg=PA41 41–42]}} }}</ref>

Co-owned [[KIKK (AM)|KIKK]] (650 AM) carried the [[Infinity Sports Network]] (formerly CBS Sports Radio) in the daytime, while KILT runs local sports shows. Co-owned [[KIKK (AM)|KIKK]] (650 AM) carried the CBS Sports Radio (now [[Infinity Sports Network]]) in the daytime until 2021 when making the switch to [[sports gambling]] as [[BetQL Network|The Bet]], while KILT runs local sports shows. old_content: After ''Gilligan's Island'', Johnson found himself somewhat typecast, making portraying more unsophisticated roles other than his signature role as the Professor more difficult. Nevertheless, he was able to resume a sufficient acting career,<ref name="citizensvoice">{{cite news| url=http://citizensvoice.com/arts-living/ashley-native-russell-johnson-rose-to-fame-on-gilligan-s-island-1.1625807| title=Ashley native Russell Johnson rose to fame on Gilligan's Island| first=William C.| last=Kashatus| newspaper=[[The Citizens' Voice]]| location=Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania| access-date=June 22, 2022}}</ref> appearing in several other movies and television shows, especially the latter. He appeared as a guest star in several dramatic series, including ''[[The Big Valley]]'' with [[Peter Breck]] (marking a reunion of sorts, since they co-starred together in ''Black Saddle'', an earlier Four Star Productions series), ''[[The Invaders]]'', ''[[Death Valley Days]]'', ''[[Owen Marshall: Counselor at Law]]'', ''[[Lassie (1954 TV series)|Lassie]]'', ''[[That Girl]]'', ''[[Ironside (TV series)|Ironside]]'', ''[[The F.B.I. old_content: While completing her Hodder and MacArthur fellowships, Adichie published short stories in various magazines.{{sfn|Obi-Young|2021}} Twelve of these stories were collected into her third book, ''[[The Thing Around Your Neck]]'', published by Knopf in 2009.{{sfn|''Kirkus Reviews''|2009}} The stories focused on the experiences of Nigerian women, living at home or abroad, examining the tragedies, loneliness, and feelings of displacement, which result from their marriages, relocations, or violent events.{{sfn|Forna|2009}}
new_content: While completing her Hodder and MacArthur fellowships, Adichie published short stories in various magazines.{{sfn|Obi-Young|2021}} Twelve of these stories were collected into her third book, ''[[The Thing Around Your Neck]]'', published by Knopf in 2009.{{sfn|''Kirkus Reviews''|2009}} The stories focused on the experiences of Nigerian women, living at home or abroad, examining the tragedies, loneliness, and feelings of displacement, which result from their marriages, relocations, or violent events.{{sfn|Forna|2009}} ''The Thing Around Your Neck'' was a bridge between Africa and the [[African diaspora]], which was also the theme of her fourth book, ''[[Americanah]]'' published in 2013.{{sfn|Obi-Young|2021}} It was the story of a young Nigerian woman and her male schoolmate, who had not studied the [[trans-Atlantic slave trade]] in school and had no understanding of the racism associated with being Black in the United States or class structures in the United Kingdom.{{sfn|''Fresh Air''|2013}}{{sfn|Day|2013}} It exploded the myth of a "shared Black consciousness", as both of the characters, one who went to Britain and the other to America, experience a loss of their identity when they try to navigate their lives abroad.{{sfn|Day|2013}} [[File:Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie at a book signing in Berlin, Germany on 16 May 2014.jpg|thumb|Adichie at the reading and signing of her work, ''[[Americanah]]'' in [[Berlin]], Germany (2014).]]

old_content: Activity during the 2002 season was generally near normal, with the number of tropical storms and hurricanes matching the respective 1991–2020 averages; however, the number of major hurricanes was above the average of four for the same period.<ref name="TCClimo"/><ref name="EPAC summary"/> Three major hurricanes—[[Hurricane Elida (2002)|Elida]], [[Hurricane Hernan (2002)|Hernan]], and [[Hurricane Kenna|Kenna]]—achieved [[List of Category 5 Pacific hurricanes|Category 5]] intensity on the [[Saffir–Simpson scale]], tying a record set in [[1994 Pacific hurricane season|1994]] for the most storms to do so in one season.<ref name="Masters">{{cite web|url=https://www.wunderground.com/cat6/Hyperactive-2018-Eastern-Pacific-Hurricane-Season-Ends|title=A Hyperactive 2018 Eastern Pacific Hurricane Season Ends|last=Masters|first=Jeff|website=[[Weather Underground (weather service)|Weather Underground]]|publisher=[[The Weather Company]]|date=November 28, 2018|access-date=May 18, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240516115536/https://www.wunderground.com/cat6/Hyperactive-2018-Eastern-Pacific-Hurricane-Season-Ends|archive-date=May 16, 2024|url-status=live}}</ref>
new_content: Activity during the 2002 season was generally near normal, with the number of tropical storms and hurricanes matching the respective 1991–2020 averages; however, the number of major hurricanes was above the average of four for the same period.<ref name="TCClimo"/><ref name="EPAC summary"/>{{rp|page=2379}} Three major hurricanes—[[Hurricane Elida (2002)|Elida]], [[Hurricane Hernan (2002)|Hernan]], and [[Hurricane Kenna|Kenna]]—achieved [[List of Category 5 Pacific hurricanes|Category 5]] strength on the [[Saffir–Simpson scale]], tying a record set in [[1994 Pacific hurricane season|1994]] for the most storms to do so in one season since reliable records began in 1971.<ref name="Masters">{{cite web|url=https://www.wunderground.com/cat6/Hyperactive-2018-Eastern-Pacific-Hurricane-Season-Ends|title=A Hyperactive 2018 Eastern Pacific Hurricane Season Ends|last=Masters|first=Jeff|website=[[Weather Underground (weather service)|Weather Underground]]|publisher=[[The Weather Company]]|date=November 28, 2018|access-date=May 18, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240516115536/https://www.wunderground.com/cat6/Hyperactive-2018-Eastern-Pacific-Hurricane-Season-Ends|archive-date=May 16, 2024|url-status=live}}</ref>

old_content: '''Lee H. Pappas''' (born 1957) is an American entrepreneur and founder of several technology publications. He co-founded [[Atari 8-bit family]] enthusiast magazine ''[[ANALOG Computing]]'' in 1981. ANALOG also produced a line of video games including ''Buried Bucks'' which was later licensed Imagic and released under the title ''[[Chopper Hunt]]''. After the [[Atari ST]] was released, ''[[ANALOG Computing|ANALOG]]'' spun off a magazine for that computer: ''ST-Log''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Index of ''ST-Log'' article by Lee H. Pappas |url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/st-log/index/index.php?author=Lee+H.+Pappas |publisher=atarimagazines.com |access-date=December 7, 2010}}</ref> ''[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment]]'' also started as a section within ''ANALOG Computing'' before becoming a separate publication.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Paper Trail: VideoGames & Computer Entertainment #1 |url=http://www.1up.com/do/blogEntry?bId=9009373 |access-date=June 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709052655/http://www.1up.com/do/blogEntry?bId=9009373 |archive-date=July 9, 2012 }}</ref> Pappas later founded  print magazines ''PC Laptop'', ''[[TurboPlay]]'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Powerful Champions of Turbo Literature |url=http://www.thebrothersduomazov.com/2009/09/powerful-champions-of-turbo-literature.html/ |access-date=June 14, 2013}}</ref> ''VISIO'', ''Picture This!'', ''Popular Home Automation!'', and ''Home Theater Builder''.

old_content: Causality is an [[abstraction]] that indicates how the world progresses.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mackie|first1=J.L. |title=The Cement of the Universe: a Study of Causation|year=2002 |orig-year=1980|publisher=Oxford University Press|place=Oxford|page=1|quote= ... it is part of the business of philosophy to determine what causal relationships in general are, what it is for one thing to cause another, or what it is for nature to obey causal laws. As I understand it, this is an ontological question, a question about how the world goes on.}}</ref> As such a basic concept, it is more apt as an explanation of other concepts of progression than as something to be explained by others more basic. The concept is like those of [[wikt:agency|agency]] and [[wikt:efficacy|efficacy]]. For this reason, a leap of [[intuition]] may be needed to grasp it.<ref>[[Alfred North Whitehead|Whitehead, A.N.]] (1929). ''Process and Reality. An Essay in Cosmology. Gifford Lectures Delivered in the University of Edinburgh During the Session 1927–1928'', Macmillan, New York; Cambridge University Press, Cambridge UK, [https://archive.org/stream/AlfredNorthWhiteheadProcessAndReality/Alfred%20North%20Whitehead%20-%20Process%20and%20Reality#page/n47/mode/2up "The sole appeal is to intuition."]</ref><ref name="Cheng1997">{{cite journal | last1 = Cheng | first1 = P.W. | year = 1997 | title = From Covariation to Causation: A Causal Power Theory | journal = Psychological Review | volume = 104 | issue = 2| pages = 367–405 | doi=10.1037/0033-295x.104.2.367}}</ref> Accordingly, causality is implicit in the logic and structure of ordinary language,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Copley |first1=Bridget |title=Causation in Grammatical Structures |date=27 January 2015 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199672073 |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/causation-in-grammatical-structures-9780199672073 |access-date=30 January 2016}}</ref> as well as explicit in the language of [[Causal notation|scientific causal notation]].
new_content: Causality is an [[abstraction]] that indicates how the world progresses.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mackie|first1=J.L. |title=The Cement of the Universe: a Study of Causation|year=2002 |orig-year=1980|publisher=Oxford University Press|place=Oxford|page=1|quote= ... it is part of the business of philosophy to determine what causal relationships in general are, what it is for one thing to cause another, or what it is for nature to obey causal laws. As I understand it, this is an ontological question, a question about how the world goes on.}}</ref> As such it is a basic concept; it is more apt to be an explanation of other concepts of progression than something to be explained by other more fundamental concepts. The concept is like those of [[wikt:agency|agency]] and [[wikt:efficacy|efficacy]]. For this reason, a leap of [[intuition]] may be needed to grasp it.<ref>[[Alfred North Whitehead|Whitehead, A.N.]] (1929). ''Process and Reality. An Essay in Cosmology. Gifford Lectures Delivered in the University of Edinburgh During the Session 1927–1928'', Macmillan, New York; Cambridge University Press, Cambridge UK, [https://archive.org/stream/AlfredNorthWhiteheadProcessAndReality/Alfred%20North%20Whitehead%20-%20Process%20and%20Reality#page/n47/mode/2up "The sole appeal is to intuition."]</ref><ref name="Cheng1997">{{cite journal | last1 = Cheng | first1 = P.W. | year = 1997 | title = From Covariation to Causation: A Causal Power Theory | journal = Psychological Review | volume = 104 | issue = 2| pages = 367–405 | doi=10.1037/0033-295x.104.2.367}}</ref> Accordingly, causality is implicit in the logic and structure of ordinary language,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Copley |first1=Bridget |title=Causation in Grammatical Structures |date=27 January 2015 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199672073 |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/causation-in-grammatical-structures-9780199672073 |access-date=30 January 2016}}</ref> as well as explicit in the language of [[Causal notation|scientific causal notation]].

old_content: It is a false myth that a slave named Stephan discovered how to cure the leaf, according to Drew Sawnson.<ref>Drew A. Swanson,  ''A Golden Weed: Tobacco and Environment in the Piedmont South'' (Yale University Press, 2014) </ref> Instead bright tobacco was the historical product of decades of experimentation with various curing methods, seed varieties and soil types. The farmers realized that consumers would pay more for the sweeter and more aromatic qualities of the bright yellow leaf. Their efforts showed that the sandy, nitrogen-poor soil of the Piedmont region in south central Virginia and neighboring North Carolina worked best for creating the mild flavor tobacco chewers craved to the point of addiction. The solution included new methods of curing the [[Tobacco#Brightleaf tobacco|Bright Leaf tobacco]] variety (a lighter flavored tobacco leaf) with [[charcoal]] taken from a local blacksmith's fire rather than the usual [[logwood]]. This fire burned hotter and faster and accelerated the curing process.<ref>Prince, pp. 47–48.</ref> The process was refined further to include a furnace in which heat from the charcoal was applied through flues, so that dark soot and off flavors did not come in contact with the tobacco.<ref>Prince, p. 48.</ref> This changed the curing process of a lighter leaf and produced a new, lighter tobacco which was able to be inhaled. This, linked together with the European taste for cigarettes, led to an emerging export market.<ref>Gately, p. 184.</ref>
new_content: It is a false myth that a slave named Stephan discovered how to cure the leaf, according to Drew Sawnson.<ref>Drew A. Swanson,  ''A Golden Weed: Tobacco and Environment in the Piedmont South'' (Yale University Press, 2014)</ref> Instead bright tobacco was the historical product of decades of experimentation with various curing methods, seed varieties and soil types. The farmers realized that consumers would pay more for the sweeter and more aromatic qualities of the bright yellow leaf. Their efforts showed that the sandy, nitrogen-poor soil of the Piedmont region in south central Virginia and neighboring North Carolina worked best for creating the mild flavor tobacco chewers craved to the point of addiction. The solution included new methods of curing the [[Tobacco#Brightleaf tobacco|Bright Leaf tobacco]] variety (a lighter flavored tobacco leaf) with [[charcoal]] taken from a local blacksmith's fire rather than the usual [[logwood]]. This fire burned hotter and faster and accelerated the curing process.<ref>Prince, pp. 47–48.</ref> The process was refined further to include a furnace in which heat from the charcoal was applied through flues, so that dark soot and off flavors did not come in contact with the tobacco.<ref>Prince, p. 48.</ref> This changed the curing process of a lighter leaf and produced a new, lighter tobacco which was able to be inhaled. This, linked together with the European taste for cigarettes, led to an emerging export market.<ref>Gately, p. 184.</ref>
