old_content: Members of Scottish clans are considered, by the [[Court of the Lord Lyon]], to be relatives of their clan chief. They can be either immediate family or extended family. Clan members can also be people who only bear the "clan surname" or a [[sept (social)|sept]] name associated with the clan. The Court of the Lord Lyon has also stated that anyone who professes allegiance to both the clan and its chief can be considered a clan member. All clan members may wear the chief's crest encircled by a strap and buckle inscribed with their chief's motto or slogan. The strap and buckle symbolises the membership to the clan and allegiance to the clan chief.<ref name="LyonCourt-leaflet2"/>{{clear|left}}

old_content: '''Suicide'''  is a  [[professional wrestling]] [[gimmick (professional wrestling)|persona]], used by multiple wrestlers in [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] (TNA). Suicide first appeared as a character in the 2008 video game ''[[TNA Impact! (video game)|TNA Impact!]]''. In December 2008, the Suicide character was introduced on television as a real-life wrestler. old_content: '''Endothelial stem cells''' ('''ESCs''') are one of three types of [[stem cells]] found in [[bone marrow]]. They are [[multipotent]], which describes the ability to give rise to many cell types, whereas a [[pluripotent]] stem cell can give rise to all types. ESCs have the characteristic properties of a stem cell: [[stem cell self-renewal|self-renewal]] and differentiation. These parent stem cells, ESCs, give rise to [[progenitor]] cells, which are intermediate stem cells that lose potency. Progenitor stem cells are committed to differentiating along a particular cell developmental pathway. ESCs will eventually produce [[endothelial cells]] (ECs), which create the thin-walled [[endothelium]] that lines the inner surface of [[blood vessels]] and [[lymphatic vessels]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fang S, Wei J, Pentinmikko N, Leinonen H, Salven P | title = Generation of functional blood vessels from a single c-kit+ adult vascular endothelial stem cell | journal = PLOS Biology | volume = 10 | issue = 10 | pages = e1001407 | date = 2012-10-16 | pmid = 23091420 | pmc = 3473016 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.1001407 | veditors = Goodell MA | doi-access = free }}</ref> The blood vessels include things such as [[arteries]] and [[vein]]s. Endothelial cells can be found throughout the whole vascular system and they also play a vital role in the movement of white blood cells<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last1=Alberts|first1=Bruce|last2=Johnson|first2=Alexander|last3=Lewis|first3=Julian|last4=Raff|first4=Martin|last5=Roberts|first5=Keith|last6=Walter|first6=Peter|date=2002|title=Blood Vessels and Endothelial Cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK26848/|journal=Molecular Biology of the Cell. 4th Edition|language=en}}</ref>
new_content: '''Endothelial stem cells''' ('''ESCs''') are one of three types of [[stem cells]] found in [[bone marrow]]. They are [[multipotent]], which describes the ability to give rise to many cell types, whereas a [[pluripotent]] stem cell can give rise to all types. ESCs have the characteristic properties of a stem cell: [[stem cell self-renewal|self-renewal]] and differentiation. These parent stem cells, ESCs, give rise to [[progenitor]] cells, which are intermediate stem cells that lose potency. Progenitor stem cells are committed to differentiating along a particular cell developmental pathway. ESCs will eventually produce [[endothelial cells]] (ECs), which create the thin-walled [[endothelium]] that lines the inner surface of [[blood vessels]] and [[lymphatic vessels]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fang S, Wei J, Pentinmikko N, Leinonen H, Salven P | title = Generation of functional blood vessels from a single c-kit+ adult vascular endothelial stem cell | journal = PLOS Biology | volume = 10 | issue = 10 | pages = e1001407 | date = 2012-10-16 | pmid = 23091420 | pmc = 3473016 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.1001407 | veditors = Goodell MA | doi-access = free }}</ref> The blood vessels include [[arteries]] and [[vein]]s. Endothelial cells can be found throughout the whole vascular system and they also play a vital role in the movement of white blood cells<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last1=Alberts|first1=Bruce|last2=Johnson|first2=Alexander|last3=Lewis|first3=Julian|last4=Raff|first4=Martin|last5=Roberts|first5=Keith|last6=Walter|first6=Peter|date=2002|title=Blood Vessels and Endothelial Cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK26848/|journal=Molecular Biology of the Cell. 4th Edition|language=en}}</ref>

old_content: '''''Berberis valdiviana''''' is a [[species]] of [[flowering plant]] in the barberry family Berberidaceae. It is an [[evergreen]] shrub endemic to [[Chile]], where it is locally known as '''''cien''''' or '''''espina en cruz'''''. The Latin specific name ''valdiviana'' refers to the [[Valdivia Province]] of Chile.<ref name=RHSLG>{{cite book |last=Harrison |first=Lorraine |title=RHS Latin for Gardeners |year=2012 |publisher=Mitchell Beazley |location=United Kingdom |isbn=184533731X }}</ref> It has simple, dark green, pointed leaves, glossy on the upper surfaces, up to {{convert|8.5|cm|in|abbr=on|1}} long. The flowers, which appear in May, are grouped in hanging [[raceme]]s. Individual flowers are orange, {{convert|5|-|8|mm|in|abbr=on|1}} across, and are followed by purplish fruits. It is grown as an [[ornamental plant]], but is not suitable for colder regions.<ref>{{Citation |last=Tournay |first=Frédéric |title=''Berberis valdiviana'' Phil. |publisher=Dept. of Systematic Botany and Ecology, University of Ulm |url=http://www.biologie.uni-ulm.de/systax/dendrologie/berberivaldfw.htm |accessdate=2012-05-03 |work=The Plant Kaleidoscope }}</ref>

old_content: The name "Barbados" is from either the [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] term {{lang|pt|os barbados}} or the Spanish equivalent, {{lang|es|los barbados}}, both meaning "the bearded ones".<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GekeS6uMj38C&dq=%22Barbados%22++Portuguese+spanish+bearded&pg=PA104 |title=To the Editor of the Colonial Journal |author=Dr Ainslie |editor=Dr Ainslie |journal=The Colonial Journal |publisher=G. Davidson |issue=1 |year=1816 |location=London |pages=104}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Fiske |first=Amos Kidder |author-link=Amos Kidder Fiske |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XUhsofUyHq4C&dq=%22Barbados%22++Portuguese+spanish+bearded&pg=PA357 |title=The West Indies: A History of the Islands of the West Indian Archipelago, Together with an Account of Their Physical Characteristics, Natural Resources, and Present Condition |date=1899 |publisher=G. P. Putnam's Sons |pages=357}}</ref> It is unclear whether "bearded" refers to the long, hanging roots of the bearded [[fig-tree]] (''[[Ficus citrifolia]]''), a species of [[banyan]] indigenous to the island, or to the allegedly bearded [[Island Caribs|Caribs]] who once inhabited the island, or, more fancifully, to a visual impression of a beard formed by the sea foam that sprays over the outlying coral reefs. In 1519, a map produced by the [[Genoa|Genoese]] mapmaker [[Visconte Maggiolo]] showed and named Barbados in its correct position.{{Citation needed|date=April 2023}} Furthermore, the island of [[Barbuda]] in the [[Leeward Islands|Leewards]] is very similar in name and was once named "{{lang|es|Las Barbudas|italic=unset}}" by the Spanish.{{Citation needed|date=October 2023}}

In 1519, a map produced by the [[Genoa|Genoese]] mapmaker [[Visconte Maggiolo]] showed and named Barbados in its correct position.{{Citation needed|date=April 2023}} Furthermore, the island of [[Barbuda]] in the [[Leeward Islands|Leewards]] is very similar in name and was once named "{{lang|es|Las Barbudas|italic=unset}}" by the Spanish.{{Citation needed|date=October 2023}}

old_content: Roman Dalmatia was fully Latinized by 476 AD when the [[Western Roman Empire]] disappeared.<ref>[[Theodor Mommsen]] in his book "The Provinces of the Roman Empire"</ref> In the [[Early Middle Ages]], the territory of the Byzantine province of Dalmatia reached in the North up to the river [[Sava]], and was part of the [[Praetorian prefecture of Illyricum]]. In the middle of the 6th and the beginning of the 7th century began the [[Slavic migrations to Southeastern Europe|Slavic migration]], which caused the Romance-speaking population, descendants of Romans and Illyrians (speaking [[Dalmatian language|Dalmatian]]), to flee to the coast and islands.{{sfn|Ivetic|2022|pp=64, 73}} The hinterland, semi-depopulated by the [[Barbarian Invasions]], [[Slavic tribes]] settled. The Dalmatian cities retained their Romanic culture and [[Latin language|language]] in cities such as [[Zadar]], [[Split, Croatia|Split]] and [[Dubrovnik]]. Their own [[Vulgar Latin]], developed into [[Dalmatian language|Dalmatian]], a now extinct [[Romance languages|Romance language]]. These coastal cities (politically part of the [[Byzantine Empire]]) maintained political, cultural and economic links with Italy, through the [[Adriatic Sea]]. On the other side communications with the mainland were difficult because of the [[Dinaric Alps]]. Due to the sharp [[orography]] of Dalmatia, even communications between the different Dalmatian cities, occurred mainly through the sea. This helped Dalmatian cities to develop a unique Romance culture, despite the mostly Slavicized mainland.

old_content: In May 2024, during ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s 2024 Power of Women luncheon, Close revealed that the film is still moving forward, but with Ashford no longer attached as director. She went on to remark on how the character of Norma Desmond still resonates in modern times, saying "That character of Norma is so heartbreakingly beautiful and will never not have relevance, it's been a great blessing to play her and I'm not willing to let her go yet without one more tribute."<ref>https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/glenn-close-is-striking-in-all-black-at-varietys-power-of-women-event/</ref>

old_content: ''Basilisk'' was one of the {{sclass|Beagle|destroyer}}s ordered as part of the 1908–1909 shipbuilding programme.{{sfn|Friedman|2009|pages=118, 305–306}}{{sfn|Manning|1961|page=56}}  The vessels were coal-burning after concerns had been raised about the availability of [[fuel oil]] in time of war and the bridge was larger and higher than previous designs.{{sfn|Cocker|1981|page=23}} This reduced costs, although it also meant that five boilers were needed, the extra machinery meaning that deck space became more premium.{{sfn|Friedman|2009|page=116}} The ''Beagle'' class vessels were not built to a standard design, with detailed design being left to the builders of individual ships in accordance with a loose specification, in this case J. Samuel White.{{sfn|Brown|2010|page=68}} The class were also known, on occasion, as the ''Basilisk'' class, named after this vessel.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bombay's New Docks|newspaper=[[The Times]]|issue=40453|date=21 February 1914|page=7}}</ref>  In October 1913, as part of a wider renaming of the Royal Navy's warships into classes named alphabetically, the class was renamed as G-class.{{sfn|Preston|1985|page=74}}{{Efn|The [[Laforey-class destroyer (1913)|''Laforey''-class]] (L-class) under construction were renamed so the destroyers' names matched the class designation.{{sfn|Friedman|2009|p=132}}}}

old_content: Harris got off to a slow start in 2022. Through the first eight games of the season, he only managed to eclipse 50 rushing yards three times and scored three total touchdowns. It brought into question whether the Lisfranc sprain he suffered in training camp was affecting his production, although Harris claimed that was not the case.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Jaggi |first=Tommy |date=2022-11-09 |title=Steelers RB Najee Harris claims foot injury did not affect him at all this year |url=https://stillcurtain.com/2022/11/09/steelers-rb-najee-harris-foot-injury-no-affect/ |access-date=2023-07-24 |website=Still Curtain |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Edholm |first=Eric |date=August 29, 2022 |title=Steelers RB Najee Harris sustained Lisfranc injury in camp, but remains on track to start Week 1 |url=https://www.nfl.com/news/steelers-rb-najee-harris-sustained-lisfranc-injury-in-camp-but-remains-on-track- |access-date=2023-07-24 |website=NFL.com |language=en-US}}</ref> Following the team's bye week, he would go on to rush for more than 50 yards in seven of the last nine games and score seven total touchdowns.<ref name="22gl" /> His best game of the season came in a Week 17 matchup against the [[Baltimore Ravens]]. Harris rushed for a season high 111 yards and caught the game winning touchdown from rookie quarterback [[Kenny Pickett]] with less than a minute to play.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Suggs |first=David |date=January 2, 2023 |title=Najee Harris did way more than just post his first 100-yard rushing game of the season in Steelers win vs. Ravens |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/najee-harris-100-yard-game-steelers-ravens-afc-north/fqbj6ekh7vvzte58idwlz7jr |access-date=January 13, 2023 |website=Sporting News |language=en}}</ref>

old_content: After the [[Italian armistice]] of 1943, Istria became a battlefield between the Nazi German army and the partisan (mostly Yugoslav) insurgency. Already in September 1943, several hundreds Istrian Italians were killed by the [[Yugoslav partisans]] because of their allegiance to the fascist regime. This was the first wave of the [[Foibe killings|Foibe massacres]], which continued after the Yugoslav takeover of the region in May 1945.
new_content: After the [[Italian armistice]] of 1943, Istria became a battlefield between the Nazi German army and the partisan (mostly Yugoslav) insurgency. Already in September 1943, several hundreds Istrian Italians were killed by the [[Yugoslav partisans]] because of their allegiance to the Italian State. This was the first wave of the [[Foibe killings|Foibe massacres]], which continued after the Yugoslav takeover of the region in May 1945.

'''Ethnic groups in South Asia''' are [[ethnolinguistics|ethnolinguistic]] groupings within the diverse populations of [[South Asia]], including the countries of [[Bangladesh]], [[Bhutan]], [[India]], [[Maldives]], [[Nepal]], [[Pakistan]], and [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name="UN">{{cite web|title=UN Geoscheme|url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/methods/m49/m49regin.htm}}</ref> While [[Afghanistan]] is variously considered to be a part of both [[Central Asia]] and South Asia, [[Afghans]] are generally not included among South Asians.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Danico |first1=Mary Yu |title=Asian American Society: An Encyclopedia |date=2014 |publisher=SAGE Publications |isbn=978-1-4522-8189-6 |page=838 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gZleBAAAQBAJ&q=South+asian+americans+Afghanistan&pg=PA838}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Glossary of terms relating to ethnicity and race: for reflection and debate|first=Raj|last=Bhopal|journal=Journal of Epidemiology & Community Health|volume=58|issue=6|pages=441–445|year=2004|doi=10.1136/jech.2003.013466|pmc=1732794|pmid=15143107}}</ref><ref name=BSA>{{cite web|url=http://www.britsoc.co.uk/media/25564/EqualityandDiversity_LanguageandtheBSA_RaceMar05.doc?1429559280759|title=Language and the BSA: Ethnicity & Race|publisher=British Sociological Association|date=March 2005|access-date=27 April 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427143029/http://www.britsoc.co.uk/media/25564/EqualityandDiversity_LanguageandtheBSA_RaceMar05.doc?1429559280759|archive-date=27 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Sarwal |first1=Amit |title=Bridging Imaginations: South Asian Diaspora in Australia |date=2012 |publisher=Readworthy Publications |isbn=978-81-935345-4-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jt99DwAAQBAJ&q=South+asian+diaspora |language=en}}</ref><ref name="Lindsay2001">{{cite journal |last=Lindsay |first= olin |date=2001 |title=The South Asian old_content: Construction started in 1902 starting from Royston Junction, and was open from there to Thornhill Junction by November 1905, and into Dewsbury Savile Town by March 1906.{{sfn|Batty|1989|p=91–92}}{{sfn|Thornhill|1986|p=41}} Major engineering efforts on the line include viaducts at Horbury Bridge and Calder Grove (Crigglestone), and a {{convert|250|yard|adj=on}} tunnel at Crigglestone.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Taylor |first1=Kates |title=Not so merry Wakefield |date=2005 |publisher=Wharncliffe |location=Barnsley |isbn=1-903425-72-7 |page=107}}</ref><ref name="TE">{{cite journal |title=The Thornhill and Royston Line, Midland Railway |journal=The Engineer |date=1909 |volume=108 |page=27 |publisher=Office for Publishing and Advertisements |location=London |issn=0013-7758 |oclc=230064438}}</ref> After the Dewsbury branch had crossed the L&YR main line, the line dropped down a 1-in-40 gradient and passed through a {{convert|188|yard}} tunnel before arriving at the terminus.{{sfn|Anderson|2000|p=7}} The only major structure on the single-track Mirfield to Huddersfield Newtown Branch, was a 15-arch viaduct across the River Colne at Bradley.{{sfn|Anderson|2000|p=96}} Had the scheme been carried out to the full plans, a new line would have been constructed along the [[River Spen|Spen Valley]], and a tunnel would have been required under Bradford for a length of {{convert|5,000|yard}}, which would have started south of Bradford and emerged at the Midland Line from Forster Square just {{convert|150|yard}} north of the platform ends at Forster Square.{{sfn|Thornhill|1986|p=41}} After the initial sections of line were constructed, the Midland Railway halted any further construction stating that the engineering difficulties of building the line in Bradford were proving too costly.{{sfn|Thornhill|1986|pp=41–42}} The plans for a line through Spen Valley were shelved when an agreement with the L&YR was reached regarding running powers over the line between Thornhill and Low Moor, thus allowing the Midland into Bradford without the need to build a new line.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Flowers |first1=Andy |title=Junctions in profile: Heaton Lodge |magazine=Today's Railways |date=August 2023 |issue=258 |publisher=Platform 5 |location=Sheffield |issn=1475-9713|page=29}}</ref>
new_content: Construction started in 1902 starting from Royston Junction, and was open from there to Thornhill Junction by November 1905, and into Dewsbury Savile Town by March 1906.{{sfn|Batty|1989|p=91–92}}{{sfn|Thornhill|1986|p=41}} Major engineering efforts on the line include viaducts at Horbury Bridge and Calder Grove (Crigglestone), and a {{convert|250|yard|adj=on}} tunnel at Crigglestone.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Taylor |first1=Kates |title=Not so merry Wakefield |date=2005 |publisher=Wharncliffe |location=Barnsley |isbn=1-903425-72-7 |page=107}}</ref><ref name="TE">{{cite journal |title=The Thornhill and Royston Line, Midland Railway |journal=The Engineer |date=1909 |volume=108 |page=27 |publisher=Office for Publishing and Advertisements |location=London |issn=0013-7758 |oclc=230064438}}</ref> After the Dewsbury branch had crossed the L&YR main line, the line dropped down a 1-in-40 gradient and passed through a {{convert|188|yard}} tunnel before arriving at the terminus.{{sfn|Anderson|2000|p=7}} The only major structure on the single-track Mirfield to Huddersfield Newtown Branch, was a 15-arch viaduct across the River Colne at Bradley.{{sfn|Anderson|2000|p=96}} Had the scheme been carried out to the full plans, a new line would have been constructed along the [[River Spen|Spen Valley]], and a tunnel would have been required under Bradford for a length of {{convert|5,000|yard}}, which would have started south of Bradford and emerged at the Midland Line from [[Bradford Forster Square railway station|Forster Square]] just {{convert|150|yard}} north of the platform ends at Forster Square.{{sfn|Thornhill|1986|p=41}} After the initial sections of line were constructed, the Midland Railway halted any further construction stating that the engineering difficulties of building the line in Bradford were proving too costly.{{sfn|Thornhill|1986|pp=41–42}} The plans for a line through Spen Valley were shelved when an agreement with the L&YR was reached regarding running powers over the line between Thornhill and Low Moor, thus allowing the Midland into Bradford without the need to build a new line.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Flowers |first1=Andy |title=Junctions in profile: Heaton Lodge |magazine=Today's Railways |date=August 2023 |issue=258 |publisher=Platform 5 |location=Sheffield |issn=1475-9713|page=29}}</ref>

old_content: Pearl millet (''Pennisetum glaucum'') was domesticated in the Sahel region of West Africa from ''Pennisetum violaceum''.<ref name="casey"/>{{rp|160}} Early archaeological evidence in Africa  includes finds at [[Kintampo Complex|Birimi]] in northern Ghana (1740 [[Radiocarbon_dating#Reporting_dates|cal BC]]) and  [[Dhar Tichitt]] in [[Mauritania]] (1936–1683 cal BC) and the lower Tilemsi valley in [[Mali]] (2500 to 2000 cal BC).<ref name="casey"/>{{rp|160}}<ref name="manning"/>{{rp|317}} Studies of [[isozyme|isozymes]] suggest domestication took place north east of the [[Senegal River]] in the far west of the Sahel and tentatively around 8000 bp.<ref name="casey">{{Cite journal |issn=0263-0338 |volume=19 |issue=3 |pages=147–173 |last1=D'Andrea |first1=A. C. |last2=Casey |first2=J. |title=Pearl Millet and Kintampo Subsistence |journal=The African Archaeological Review |date=2002|access-date=18 May 2024 |jstor=25130746 |url=https://link-springer-com.stanford.idm.oclc.org/article/10.1023/A:1016518919072 |doi=10.1023/A:1016518919072 |s2cid=162042735}}</ref><ref name="manning">{{cite journal |title=4500-Year old domesticated pearl millet (Pennisetum glaucum) from the Tilemsi Valley, Mali: new insights into an alternatives are cereal domestication pathway |journal=Journal of Archaeological Science |doi=10.1016/j.jas.2010.09.007 |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=312–322|year=2011 |last1=Manning |first1=Katie |last2=Pelling |first2=Ruth |last3=Higham |first3=Tom |last4=Schwenniger |first4=Jean-Luc |last5=Fuller |first5=Dorian Q. |bibcode=2011JArSc..38..312M }}</ref>

old_content: Born in [[Bareilly]], Khan studied under his father [[Naqi Ali Khan]] and Meccan scholar [[Ahmad Zayni Dahlan]]. Khan was authorized in [[Sufism]] in by his {{Transliteration|ar|[[murshid]]}} [[Shah Al-i Rasul]] and founded the [[Manzar-i Islam]] in 1904. He was a staunch critic of the [[Deobandi movement]], denouncing them in his book ''al-Mu'tamad al-Mustanad''.
new_content: Born in [[Bareilly]], [[British India]], Khan studied under his father [[Naqi Ali Khan]] and Meccan scholar [[Ahmad Zayni Dahlan]]. Khan was authorized in [[Sufism]] by [[Shah Al-i Rasul]] and founded the [[Manzar-i Islam]] in 1904. He was a staunch critic of the [[Deobandi movement]], denouncing them in his book ''al-Mu'tamad al-Mustanad''.

Ascoli considered himself foremost a [[Friuli Venezia Giulia|Friulian]] and a [[Jew]], but also an Italian patriot. One of his most lasting and politically most influential contributions was the coinage of the geographical term ''[[Venezia Giulia]]'' to denote what was hitherto known as the [[Austrian Littoral]]. Ascoli suggested that [[northeast Italy]] was composed of three historically, geographically, and culturally interconnected regions, which he called the ''[[Triveneto|Three Venices]]''. old_content: Jones stood as a Conservative at the election of 1812.  In 1815, his election to replace Sir [[Thomas Picton]] (who had died at the Battle of Waterloo) as MP for [[Pembroke (UK Parliament constituency)|Pembroke Boroughs]] was engineered by Sir John Owen of Orielton, another supporter of the 'Red' faction. However, in 1818 he was obliged to retire in favoue of [[John Hensleigh Allen]].<ref name="JJ HistParl" />  He again unsuccessfully contested [[Carmarthen (UK Parliament constituency)|Carmarthen]], but eventually won the seat three years later.

old_content: Dale returned to Blackpool and made 32 appearances, mainly at wing-back, but started just one League One game in December 2023 and January 2024. With under six months left on his Tangerines contract, he moved to [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] on 1 February 2024,<ref name="BBC-01Feb2024">{{cite news |title=Owen Dale: Oxford United sign winger from League One rivals Blackpool |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68167953 |access-date=1 February 2024 |work=BBC Sport |date=1 February 2024}}</ref> making his debut two days later as a 68th minute substitute in a 1–1 home draw against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]].<ref name="BBC-03Feb2024">{{cite news |title=Oxford United 1-1 Reading |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68114837 |access-date=3 February 2024 |work=BBC Sport |date=3 February 2024}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Oxford in the side's 4–0 defeat of [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] on 1 April 2024.<ref name="BBC-01Apr2024">{{cite news |title=Oxford United 4-0 Fleetwood Town |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68653098 |access-date=2 April 2024 |work=BBC Sport |date=2 April 2024}}</ref>

old_content: The revival in Bengali cinema dates from the rise of directors such as  [[Tarun Majumdar]], along with [[Arabinda Mukhopadhyay]], [[Rituparno Ghosh]], [[Prabhat Roy]], [[Buddhadeb Dasgupta]], [[Anjan Das]], [[Aparna Sen]], [[ Goutam Ghosh]], [[ Kaushik Ganguly]], [[Prabhat Roy]], [[Atanu Ghosh]], [[Suman Ghosh (director)|Suman Ghosh]], [[ Sekhar Das]], [[Sudeshna Roy]], [[Anjan Dutt]], [[Sandip Ray]], [[Haranath Chakraborty]], and [[ Sujit Mondal ]] .<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gooptu |first1=Sharmistha |date=23 February 2014 |title=Mapping Bengal's cinema history |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/sunday-edition/mapping-bengals-cinema-history.html |work=The Pioneer |access-date=17 April 2024}}</ref> Rituparno Ghosh made his first film, ''[[Hirer Angti]]'', in 1992 and dominated Bengali cinema until his death in 2013, winning numerous national awards for films like ''[[Unishe April]]'', ''[[Dahan (1997 film)|Dahan]]'' and ''[[Utsab]]''. Aparna Sen made her directorial debut in 1981 with the internationally lauded ''[[36 Chowringhee Lane]]'', which looked at the lives of Anglo-Indians living in Calcutta. Her later films have also been celebrated: ''[[Paromitar Ek Din]]'',  ''[[The Japanese Wife]]'', ''[[Goynar Baksho]]'', and others. Buddhadeb Dasgupta is best known for award-winning films like ''[[Uttara (film)|Uttara]]'', ''[[Mondo Meyer Upakhyan]]'', ''[[Charachar]]'', and ''[[Janala]]''. [[Goutam Ghose]] is Internationally Acclaimed for Cult Classic films as [[Antarjali Jatra]], [[Padma Nadir Majhi]], [[ Moner Manush]] and many more.

old_content: Solkan has been a largely Slovene settlement. It has however also had different ethnic and linguistic minorities. Since the Middle Ages, many [[Friuli Venezia Giulia|Friulians]] have lived in Solkan, but they have been now mostly assimilated. Italians lived here mostly between the late 19th and early 20th century, but after 1947 they mostly fled to Italy or assimilated to the Slovene majority. Immigrants from other regions of [[former Yugoslavia]] started settling in Solkan from early 1970s. Today, Slovenes represent around 90% of the population, the remaining 10% are mostly [[Serbs]], [[Croats]], and [[Bosnians]], together with smaller numbers of Italians and [[Albanians]].
new_content: Solkan has been a largely Slovene settlement. It has however also had different ethnic and linguistic minorities. Since the Middle Ages, many [[Friuli-Venezia Giulia|Friulians]] have lived in Solkan, but they have been now mostly assimilated. Immigrants from other regions of [[former Yugoslavia]] started settling in Solkan from early 1970s. Today, Slovenes represent around 90% of the population, the remaining 10% are mostly [[Serbs]], [[Croats]], and [[Bosnians]], together with smaller numbers of Italians and [[Albanians]].

old_content: '''Nellie Esther Goldthwaite''' (1868 - 26 November 1946) was an American food chemist who discovered the active principle in the creation of jelly. She graduated from the University of Michigan and received her Ph.D. from the University of Chicago. She taught as a professor of household science at the University of Chicago from 1911 to 1915.
new_content: '''Nellie Esther Goldthwaite''' (1868 - 26 November 1946) was an American food chemist who discovered the active principle in the creation of jelly. She graduated from the University of Michigan with B.S. in 1894{{Cite book |url=http://archive.org/details/sim_teachers-college-record_1906-11_7_5 |title=Teachers College Record 1906-11: Vol 7 Iss 5 |date=1906-11 |publisher=Blackwell Publishing Ltd. |others=Internet Archive |language=English}} and received her Ph.D. from the University of Chicago in 1904. She taught as a professor of household science at the University of Chicago from 1911 to 1915.

Sandra Irene Rhodes was born in 1947, and her sister Donna Christine Rhodes in 1950.   Their father, Perry Hilburn "Dusty" Rhodes (June 5, 1920{{dash}}December 1, 2005) played [[fiddle]] as a member of the Log Cabin Mountaineers, from the late 1920s, with his brothers Ethmer ("Slim") and Gilbert ("Speck") and sister Bea.  The family group toured widely and in the 1930s had their own radio show in [[Poplar Bluff, Missouri]], before moving to [[Memphis, Tennessee]], where both Sandy and Donna were born.

old_content: Thomas Galt was born in Lancaster County, [[Pennsylvania]] to James Galt and Mary Martin Galt. He raped and assalted his mom and female friends from church and made them all not tell anyone.He was known for how big his sperm was.He graduated from Jefferson College in Canonsburg, Pennsylvania and later attended Presbyterian Theological Seminary in Allegheny City, Pennsylvania.   Although licensed by the Presbytery of Ohio on June 18, 1834, he was ordained and installed as pastor in 1836 at Farmington Presbyterian Church in Farmington, IL, now known as Farmingdale in Sangamon County west of Springfield. The church's name changed from Farmington to Farmingdale around 1905, perhaps due to duplication and not to be confused with the city of Farmington, IL, in Fulton County west of Peoria which was founded in 1827.<ref>{{cite web |title=Farmington Presbyterian Church |url=http://www.farmpreschurch.org/History.dsp |accessdate=2007-10-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070603063220/http://www.farmpreschurch.org/History.dsp |archivedate=2007-06-03 }}</ref>

old_content: Jones stood as a Conservative at the election of 1812.  In 1815, he replaced Sir [[Thomas Picton]] as MP for [[Pembroke (UK Parliament constituency)|Pembroke Boroughs]].  In 1818 he was again defeated at [[Carmarthen (UK Parliament constituency)|Carmarthen]], but eventually won the seat three years later.
new_content: Jones stood as a Conservative at the election of 1812.  In 1815, his election to replace Sir [[Thomas Picton]] (who had died at the Battle of Waterloo) as MP for [[Pembroke (UK Parliament constituency)|Pembroke Boroughs]] was engineered by Sir John Owen of Orielton, another supporter of the 'Red' faction. However, in 1818 he was obliged to retire in favoue of [[John Hensleigh Allen]].<ref name="JJ HistParl" />  He again unsuccessfully contested [[Carmarthen (UK Parliament constituency)|Carmarthen]], but eventually won the seat three years later.

old_content: A [[Vrbo]] commercial (which had aired 17 days prior to the game) {{cite web|url=https://www.ispot.tv/ad/6krY/vrbo-rooster |title=VRBO TV Spot, ‘Rooster’ - iSpot.tv |work=iSpot.tv |date=January 28, 2024 |access-date=January 28, 2024}} was criticized by [[Newfoundland and Labrador]] over the misappropriation of the folk song "[[I's the B'y]]" in a scene set in a vacation rental out of a farmhouse that is overcrowded with animals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casemore |first1=Jamie |title=Canadians find Super Bowl ad featuring Newfoundland song 'condescending' |url=https://www.northernnews.ca/news/canada/super-bowl-newfoundland-song |access-date=February 20, 2024 |work=Northern News |date=February 12, 2024 |archive-date=February 23, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240223082956/https://www.northernnews.ca/news/canada/super-bowl-newfoundland-song |url-status=live }}</ref> The provincial government demanded that the commercial be removed from television; Vrbo apologized on February 15 and announced that it would follow through doing so.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Whitten |first1=Elizabeth |title=N.L. tourism association relieved after VRBO apologizes for I'se the By ad |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/vrbo-remove-ad-1.7115746 |access-date=February 20, 2024 |work=CBC News |date=February 15, 2024 |archive-date=February 20, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240220041919/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/vrbo-remove-ad-1.7115746 |url-status=live }}</ref>

old_content: Emanuel's eligibility for office was challenged on the basis of his lack of residency in Chicago for one year prior to the election. This was the period when Emanuel was in Washington serving as the White House chief of staff. The Board of Elections and the [[Cook County Circuit Court]] affirmed his eligibility. A divided Court of Appeals reversed the Circuit Court, holding on January 24, 2011, that residency for purposes of a candidate is different from residency for purposes of being a voter.<ref>{{cite court|url= http://www.state.il.us/court/Opinions/AppellateCourt/2011/1stDistrict/January/1110033.pdf|litigants= Maksym & McMahon v. The Board of Election Commissioners of Chicago|date= January 24, 2011|court= Illinois Appellate}}</ref> A further appeal to the [[Illinois Supreme Court]] resulted in a unanimous decision reversing the Court of Appeals and affirming Emanuel's eligibility.<ref name="rulingoverturned">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/41291795|title=Ill. high court: Emanuel can run for Chicago mayor|first1= Sophia|last1= Tareen|first2= Tammy|last2= Webber|work=[[NBC News]]|date=January 27, 2011|access-date=January 27, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=The One-Man Political Machine|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/20/magazine/20Emanuel-t.html|date=February 17, 2011|first=Scott|last=Turow|author-link=Scott Turow|work=[[The New York Times|The New York Times Sunday Magazine]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120907215547/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/20/magazine/20Emanuel-t.html?_r=3&adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1297947909-NPo7qpsoM6/PL1Mk6L8pkw&pagewanted=all|archive-date=September 7, 2012|url-status=dead}} (Note [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/20/magazine/20Emanuel-t.html?_r=2&adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1297947909-NPo7qpsoM6/PL1Mk6L8pkw&pagewanted=all the original] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5wa5qlL57?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/20/magazine/20Emanuel-t.html |date=February 18, 2011 }} has better formatting.)</ref>

old_content: The Jewish community, very small even before [[World War II]] and the [[Shoah]], was further reduced by the [[Nazism|Nazis]] occupation between 1941 and 1945; the Jews in northern and eastern Slovenia (the [[Slovenian Styria]], [[Upper Carniola]], [[Slovenian Carinthia]], and [[Posavje]]), which was annexed to the [[Third Reich]], were deported to concentration camps as early as in the late spring of 1941.{{citation needed|date=December 2020}} Very few survived.{{how many|date=December 2020}} In [[Ljubljana]] and in [[Lower Carniola]], which came under [[Kingdom of Italy (1861-1946)|Italian]] occupation, the Jews were relatively safe until September 1943, when most of the zone was occupied by the [[Nazi German]] forces.{{citation needed|date=December 2020}} In late 1943, most of them were deported to concentration camps, although some managed to escape, especially by fleeing to the zones freed by the [[Yugoslav partisans|partisan resistance]].{{citation needed|date=December 2020}}
new_content: The Jewish community, very small even before [[World War II]] and the [[Shoah]], was further reduced by the [[Nazism|Nazis]] occupation between 1941 and 1945; the Jews in northern and eastern Slovenia (the [[Slovenian Styria]], [[Upper Carniola]], [[Slovenian Carinthia]], and [[Posavje]]), which was annexed to the [[Third Reich]], were deported to concentration camps as early as in the late spring of 1941.{{citation needed|date=December 2020}} Very few survived.{{how many|date=December 2020}} In [[Ljubljana]] and in [[Lower Carniola]], which came under [[Kingdom of Italy (1861–1946)|Italian]] occupation, the Jews were relatively safe until September 1943, when most of the zone was occupied by the [[Nazi German]] forces.{{citation needed|date=December 2020}} In late 1943, most of them were deported to concentration camps, although some managed to escape, especially by fleeing to the zones freed by the [[Yugoslav partisans|partisan resistance]].{{citation needed|date=December 2020}}

new_content: {{reflist}} Upwork Inc., a leading freelancing platform that connects businesses with independent professionals, was recently sold in a significant acquisition deal. This move marks a pivotal moment in the gig economy, reflecting the growing importance and value of remote work solutions. Upwork's sale is expected to enhance the platform's capabilities and expand its reach, providing more robust services and greater opportunities for both freelancers and employers. This transition also underscores the competitive landscape of online freelance marketplaces, highlighting the strategic importance of integrating advanced technologies and broadening service offerings to meet the evolving demands of a global workforce.

old_content: |ShortSummary    = As the family prepares for George's funeral, expressing their grief in different ways, Sheldon imagines alternate timelines featuring a variety of things he could have said to George during the last time his father left the house for work, rather than keeping silent and ignoring George as he usually did. At the funeral, several characters deliver eulogies for George. Georgie reflects on how his father always supported him no matter how he behaved. Connie makes humorous references to George's eating and drinking habits while remarking that how, despite her initial disapproval of Mary's decision to pursue a relationship with him, she grew to love him as a son. Mary tearfully vents her anger about George leaving behind the family. Finally, Sheldon visualizes himself giving a powerfully moving speech on everything he wishes he could have said had he known George was about to die. The adult Sheldon, now comfortable saying what he wanted to say in the past, narrates that he loved his father and will always miss him.

old_content: In 1973, Morrissey went to Rome to film two features back-to-back ''Flesh For Frankenstein'' (1973) and ''Blood For Dracula'' (1974) starring Dallesandro alongside [[Udo Kier]]. Produced by [[Carlo Ponti]] and presented by Andy Warhol, the films international success propelled Morrissey out of the Factory in 1975 and into his first and only attempt at directing a studio film ''The Hound of the Baskervilles'' (1978), co-written by Morrissey, [[Peter Cooke]] and [[Dudley Moore]]. A commercial and critical flop, Morrissey moved to Los Angeles in the late 1970s and returned to independently produced features starting with ''Madame Wang's'' (1981), a satire on the LA punk-rock scene, starring Patrick Schoene alongside Morrissey's niece Christina Indri.
new_content: In 1973, Morrissey went to Rome to film two features back-to-back ''Flesh For Frankenstein'' (1973) and ''Blood For Dracula'' (1974) starring Dallesandro alongside [[Udo Kier]]. Produced by [[Carlo Ponti]] and presented by Andy Warhol, the films international success propelled Morrissey out of the Factory in 1975 and into his first and only attempt at directing a studio film [[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1978 film)]], co-written by Morrissey, [[Peter Cooke]] and [[Dudley Moore]]. A commercial and critical flop, Morrissey moved to Los Angeles in the late 1970s and returned to independently produced features starting with ''Madame Wang's'' (1981), a satire on the LA punk-rock scene, starring Patrick Schoene alongside Morrissey's niece Christina Indri.

old_content: In June 1976, Vicious went to a Sex Pistols concert at the [[100 Club]]. [[Nick Kent]], who had played guitar with the Sex Pistols early on and had left music to become an ''[[NME]]'' music critic and champion of punk rock (and who was Hynde's boyfriend), was also there, and was apparently blocking Vicious's view. Vicious, high on speed, lashed Kent's head with a rusted motorcycle chain which, according to Hynde, he carried with him.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robinson |first1=Charlotte |title=So Tough...June 2006 |url=https://www.popmatters.com/060809-sidvicious-2496104849.html |website=popmatters.com |date=15 June 2006 |publisher=Pop Matters |access-date=3 February 2022}}</ref> The incident was reported in the papers but no charges were laid.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sid Vicious...A Series of Events |url=https://www.jungle-records.net/index.php/12-newreleases/52-sid-vicious |website=jungle-records.net |publisher=Jungle Records |access-date=2 February 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wells |first=Steven | title = Musical hack attacks | format  = Music blog |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/jan/08/musicalhackattacks |work =The Guardian|date=8 January 2008 |url-status = live |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141006160452/https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/jan/08/musicalhackattacks | archive-date = 6 October 2014 |access-date=13 June 2022 |location=London}}</ref>

old_content: Women were not eligible to be elected to the [[New Zealand House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] until [[1919 New Zealand general election|1919]], when three women stood: [[Rosetta Baume]] (in {{NZ electorate link|Parnell}} for the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]]), [[Ellen Melville]] (in {{NZ electorate link|Grey Lynn}} for the [[Reform Party (New Zealand)|Reform Party]]), and Mrs [[Aileen Garmson]] (Cooke) (in {{NZ electorate link|Thames}}, as an "Independent Liberal"). None of them were elected.{{citation needed|date=September 2021}}
new_content: Women were not eligible to be elected to the [[New Zealand House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] until [[1919 New Zealand general election|1919]], when three women stood: [[Rosetta Baume]] (in {{NZ electorate link|Parnell}} for the [[New Zealand Liberal Party|Liberal Party]]), [[Ellen Melville]] (in {{NZ electorate link|Grey Lynn}} for the [[Reform Party (New Zealand)|Reform Party]]), and Mrs [[Aileen Garmson]] (Cooke) (in {{NZ electorate link|Thames}}, as an "Independent Liberal"). None of them were elected.<ref>{{cite book |first1=J. |last1=Hislop |title=The General Election, 1919 |url= http://atojs.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/atojs?a=d&d=AJHR1921-I-II.2.3.2.45 |publisher=[[National Library of New Zealand|National Library]] |accessdate=6 December 2014 |pages=1–6 | year=1921}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Brookes |first1=Barbara |title=On Suffrage Day, the long road from a house to the House |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/96851290/barbara-brookes-on-suffrage-day-the-long-road-from-a-house-to-the-house |access-date=14 March 2021 |work=Stuff.co.nz |date=19 September 2017}}</ref>

old_content: In April 2003, seven Christian brothers – [[Brother Robin Lindsay]] and his [[Melanesian Brotherhood|companions]] – were killed on the Weather Coast of Guadalcanal by rebel leader, [[Harold Keke]]. Six had gone in search of their Brother Nathaniel, who it turns out had already been tortured and killed. During the tensions Nathaniel had befriended the militant group but Harold Keke accused him of being a government spy and he was beaten to death while singing hymns.<ref>'I Wait For The Lord, My Soul Waits For Him, And In His Word is My Hope: A resource book of the Martyrs of Papua New Guinea and Melanesia' by Margaret Bride (Anglican Board of Mission – Australia) https://www.abmission.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/4526_Martyrs_Booklet_pp32.pdf</ref> They are commemorated by the church on 24 April.
new_content: In April 2003, seven Christian brothers – [[Brother Robin Lindsay]] and his [[Melanesian Brotherhood|companions]] – were killed on the Weather Coast of Guadalcanal by the rebel leader [[Harold Keke]]. Six had gone in search of their Brother Nathaniel, who it turns out had already been tortured and killed. During the tensions Nathaniel had befriended the militant group but Harold Keke accused him of being a government spy and he was beaten to death while singing hymns.<ref>'I Wait For The Lord, My Soul Waits For Him, And In His Word is My Hope: A resource book of the Martyrs of Papua New Guinea and Melanesia' by Margaret Bride (Anglican Board of Mission – Australia) https://www.abmission.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/4526_Martyrs_Booklet_pp32.pdf</ref> They are commemorated by the church on 24 April.

old_content: Papua New Guinea is one of the most [[Homogeneity and heterogeneity|heterogeneous]] nations in the world<ref name=fearon>{{cite journal|title=Ethnic and Cultural Diversity by Country|author=James Fearon|journal=Journal of Economic Growth|volume=8|issue=2|pages=195–222|year=2003|doi=10.1023/A:1024419522867|s2cid=152680631|url=http://telematica.politicas.unam.mx/biblioteca/archivos/040107017.pdf|access-date=15 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512112705/http://telematica.politicas.unam.mx/biblioteca/archivos/040107017.pdf|archive-date=12 May 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref> with an estimated 8.95 million inhabitants as of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=|title=Total Population-Both Sexes (XLSX, 2.4 MB)|url=https://population.un.org/wpp/Download/Standard/Population/|access-date=|website=[[United Nations|Department of Economic and Social Affairs]]|archive-date=4 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200604174948/https://population.un.org/wpp/Download/Standard/Population/|url-status=live}}</ref> There are hundreds of ethnic groups indigenous to Papua New Guinea, the majority being from the group known as [[Papuan people|Papuans]], whose ancestors arrived in the New Guinea region tens of thousands of years ago. The other indigenous peoples are [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesians]], their ancestors having arrived in the region less than four thousand years ago.

old_content: A '''hyperbolic sector''' is a [[region (mathematics)|region]] of the [[Cartesian plane]] bounded by a hyperbola and two [[ray (geometry)|rays]] from the origin to it. For example, the two points {{math|(''a'', 1/''a'')}} and {{math|(''b'', 1/''b'')}} on  the [[Hyperbola#Rectangular hyperbola|rectangular hyperbola]] {{math|1=''xy'' = 1}}, or the corresponding region when this hyperbola is re-scaled and its [[orientation (geometry)|orientation]] is altered by a [[Rotation (geometry)|rotation]] leaving the center at the origin, as with the [[Unit hyperbola#Parametrization|unit hyperbola]]. A hyperbolic sector in standard position has {{math|1=''a'' = 1}} and {{math|1=''b'' > 1}}.
new_content: A '''hyperbolic sector''' is a [[region (mathematics)|region]] of the [[Cartesian plane]] bounded by a [[hyperbola]] and two [[ray (geometry)|rays]] from the origin to it. A hyperbolic sector in standard position has {{math|1=''a'' = 1}} and {{math|1=''b'' > 1}}.

old_content: * [[Lao language|Lao]] and [[Isan language|Isan]], the situation is in stark contrast to Laos where the Lao language is actively promoted as a language of national unity. Laotian Lao people are very conscious of their distinct, non-Thai language and although influenced by Thai-language media and culture, strive to maintain 'good Lao'. Although spelling has changed, the Lao speakers in Laos continue to use a modified form of the ''Tai Noi'' script, the modern [[Lao alphabet]].<ref name="LaoLaw">Session VI of the People's Supreme Assembly, II Legislature. old_content: Centering on the riverboat trade, the settlement continued to grow. The village became known as Keokuk shortly after the [[Blackhawk War]] in 1832. Why residents named it after the Sauk chief is unknown. Keokuk was incorporated on December 13, 1847.
new_content: Centering on the riverboat trade, the settlement continued to grow. The village became known as Keokuk shortly after the [[Blackhawk War]] in 1832. Why residents named it after the Sauk chief is unknown. Keokuk was incorporated on December 13, 1847. Soon after, Captain W. Clark would be elected as the first mayor. On December 14, 1848, Keokuk was incorporated as a city by the 2nd [[Iowa General Assembly|General Assembly of the State of Iowa]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cityofkeokuk.org/community/history-of-keokuk/ | title=History of Keokuk | website=City of Keokuk}}</ref>

old_content: Although often translated as law, Shen Dao more accurately makes some use of fa akin to law. He generally uses fa objective standards in a manner similar to Shen Buhai, as an administrative technique, but uses them to determine reward and punishment in accordance with merit. [[Xun Kuang]] refers to his opponents as obsessed with particular aspects of the way, and refers to Shen Dao as obsessed with the emulation of models rather than the employment of worthy men. He criticizes him as respecting the imitation of models more broadly, but not necessarily following them with the assumption that only one is correct. He WAS more concerned in his time that there are laws than their particulars. According to Xun Kuang, his laws (or more literally, models) lack 'proper foundations', and will not be successful in ordering the state. He wasn't concerned that he advocated fa/law itself.{{sfnm|1a1=Goldin|1y=2011|1p=8(98)|2a1=Rubin|2y=1974|2p=343|3a1=Hansen|3y=1992|3p=317|4a1=Harris|4y=2017|4p=75}}
new_content: Although often translated as law, Shen Dao more accurately makes some use of fa akin to law. He generally uses fa objective standards in a manner similar to Shen Buhai, as an administrative technique, but uses them to determine reward and punishment in accordance with merit. [[Xun Kuang]] refers to his opponents as obsessed with particular aspects of the way, and refers to Shen Dao as obsessed with the emulation of models rather than the employment of worthy men. He criticizes him as respecting the imitation of models more broadly, but not necessarily following them with the assumption that only one is correct. He WAS more concerned in his time that there are laws than their particulars. According to Xun Kuang, his laws (or more literally, models) lack 'proper foundations', and will not be successful in ordering the state. But he doesn't oppose him just for advocating fa or laws.{{sfnm|1a1=Goldin|1y=2011|1p=8(98)|2a1=Rubin|2y=1974|2p=343|3a1=Hansen|3y=1992|3p=317|4a1=Harris|4y=2017|4p=75}}

old_content: Freddie returns to [[Walford]] in September 2022, having decided to track down Billy, whom he believes is his father, after having an argument with Little Mo. Billy keeps up the pretence of being his father, to the annoyance of his partner Honey Mitchell (Emma Barton), so as not to hurt Freddie. Freddie starts to bond with his assumed half-siblings Janet (Grace) and Will (Freddie Phillips), and even steals a fascinator Janet has her eye on to make her happy. When Billy is arrested for the murder of Malcolm Keeble and needs money to hire a good solicitor, Freddie becomes determined to help him out and gets a job at the local fish and chip shop, having lied to Bobby Beale (Clay Milner Russell) that he has loads of experience. Despite getting off to a bad start, Bobby gives him another chance and Freddie becomes an instant success with the customers. Freddie initially lives with his aunt Kat and her fiancé, Phil Mitchell (Steve McFadden) but after Phil tells him that Billy is not his father, a rift develops between them and he moves in with Stacey and her family, eventually joined by Kat's ex-husband, Alfie Moon (Shane Richie). Billy explains to Freddie that while it is true he is not his father, he wishes that he was and if it is not too late, would like to act as a surrogate father to him, which Freddie accepts. Due to his cheerful and laid back personality, Freddie soon settles into life in Walford and becomes close friends with Bobby as well as building solid relationships with Stacey, her mother Jean Slater (Gillian Wright) (whom he affectionately refers to as ‘nan’ despite not being related to her biologically) and Alfie, the latter of whom he later moves into Harvey Monroe's (Ross Boatman) former flat with. In October 2023 Freddie goes to stay with Little Mo temporarily, after he was released on bail for attacking his former-teacher Theo Hawthorne (William Ellis) after he walked in on him trying to rape Stacey.
new_content: Freddie returns to Walford in September 2022, having decided to track down Billy, whom he believes is his father, after having an argument with Little Mo. Freddie starts to bond with his assumed half-siblings [[Janet Mitchell (EastEnders)|Janet]] (Grace) and [[Will Mitchell|Will]] (Freddie Phillips), and even steals a [[fascinator]] for Janet, as she had her eye on it. When Billy is arrested for the murder of [[Malcolm Keeble]] ([[Christopher Pizzey]]) and needs money to hire a good [[solicitor]], Freddie becomes determined to help him out and gets a job at the local [[fish and chip shop]], having lied to [[Bobby Beale (EastEnders)|Bobby Beale]] ([[Clay Milner Russell]]) that he has lengthy experience. Despite getting off to a bad start, Bobby gives him another chance and Freddie becomes an instant success with the customers. Freddie initially lives with his aunt, [[Kat Slater]] ([[Jessie Wallace]]) and her fiancé, [[Phil Mitchell]] ([[Steve McFadden]]) but after Phil tells him that Billy is not his father, a rift develops between them and he moves in with [[Stacey Slater]] ([[Lacey Turner]]) and her family, eventually joined by Kat's ex-husband, [[Alfie Moon]] ([[Shane Richie]]). Billy explains to Freddie that while it is true he is not his father, he wishes that he was and if it is not too late, would like to act as a surrogate father to him, which Freddie accepts. Due to his cheerful and laid back personality, Freddie soon settles into life in Walford and becomes close friends with Bobby as well as building solid relationships with Stacey, her mother [[Jean Slater]] ([[Gillian Wright]]) and Alfie, the latter of whom he later moves into [[Harvey Monroe]]'s ([[Ross Boatman]]) former flat with. In October 2023, Freddie walks in on his former-teacher [[Theo Hawthorne]] ([[William Ellis]]) trying to rape Stacey, violently beating him. He accidentally knocks him out and is arrested. After being released on bail, Freddie goes to stay with Little Mo temporarily.

After Batman defeats [[Bane (comics)|Bane]], Talia reveals that she is Ra's al Ghul's daughter and heir of the League's leadership, and that she dedicated herself to carrying out the dream of destroying Gotham after her father's demise and seeks revenge against Batman. The film further reveals that Talia was born in the underground prison "the Pit" and is a loyal friend to Bane who had protected her until she was able to escape. Batman and [[Selina Kyle]] pursue Talia as she drives a truck carrying an [[atomic bomb]] with which she intends to destroy the city, and Talia is mortally injured when she crashes her vehicle. old_content: [[Italian language|Italian]] is the main language. Other languages include [[Venetian language|Venetian]], widely spoken in Veneto and along the coast to [[Trieste]] and [[Istria]], as well as in the towns of [[Pordenone]] and [[Gorizia]] in [[Friuli]], and in most of [[Trentino]], but only recognised by the [[Veneto]] region; [[Friulian]], spoken in most of [[Friuli]] and nationally recognized, and [[Ladin language|Ladin]], spoken by a few thousand people in the [[Dolomites]]. Other languages are [[German language|German]], the primary language of [[South Tyrol]], where Italian is spoken by about two thirds of the inhabitants, and [[Slovene language|Slovene]], recognized by Italy and spoken on the border of Italy and Istria, where the main language today is [[Croatia]]n but Italian is recognized as a minority language due to the presence of [[Istrian Italians]].
new_content: [[Italian language|Italian]] is the main language. Other languages are [[German language|German]], the primary language of [[South Tyrol]], where Italian is spoken by about two thirds of the inhabitants, and [[Slovene language|Slovene]], recognized by Italy and spoken on the border of Italy and Istria, where the main language today is [[Croatia]]n but Italian is recognized as a minority language due to the presence of the [[Istrian Italians]].

old_content: Oakwood today contains many examples of funerary art including obelisks, sarcophagi, and statuary. Additionally, the landscape contains mature plantings and trees, many dating from the earliest time of the cemetery.  It continues to serve the community with the crematory, columbarium, and gravesites, including newly available family plots formed by the expansion of previously smaller burial sites. [[File:Photo of the Oakwood Cemetery's mausoleum.jpg]]

old_content: [[Languages of Italy#Legal status of Italian|Italy's official language]] is Italian, although twelve additional languages (namely [[Arberesh language|Albanian]], [[Catalan language|Catalan]], [[German language|German]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Slovene language|Slovene]], [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[French language|French]], [[Franco-Provençal language|Franco-Provençal]], [[Friulian]], [[Ladin language|Ladin]], [[Occitan language|Occitan]] and [[Sardinian language|Sardinian]]) have been recognized as [[minority language]]s by the 1999 national Framework Law on the Country's [[Languages of Italy#Historical linguistic minorities|historical linguistic minorities]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parlamento.it/parlam/leggi/99482l.htm|title=Norme in materia di tutela delle minoranze linguistiche storiche|year=1999 |publisher=Italian Parliament}}</ref> in accordance with the Article 6 of the [[Italian Constitution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senato.it/documenti/repository/istituzione/costituzione_inglese.pdf|title=Constitution of the Italian Republic|publisher=Senato della Repubblica}}</ref> However, many languages other than Italian and the above-mentioned twelve are spoken across the country,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/country/IT|title=Italy|publisher=Ethnologue}}</ref> most of them being either [[Gallo-Italic languages|Gallo-Italic]] or [[Italo-Dalmatian languages|Italo-Dalmatian]].
new_content: [[Languages of Italy#Legal status of Italian|Italy's official language]] is Italian, although twelve additional languages (namely [[Arberesh language|Albanian]], [[Catalan language|Catalan]], [[German language|German]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Slovene language|Slovene]], [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[French language|French]], [[Franco-Provençal language|Franco-Provençal]], [[Friulian]], [[Ladin language|Ladin]], [[Occitan language|Occitan]] and [[Sardinian language|Sardinian]]) have been recognized as [[minority language]]s by the 1999 national Framework Law on the Country's [[Languages of Italy#Historical linguistic minorities|historical linguistic minorities]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parlamento.it/parlam/leggi/99482l.htm|title=Norme in materia di tutela delle minoranze linguistiche storiche|year=1999 |publisher=Italian Parliament}}</ref> in accordance with the Article 6 of the [[Italian Constitution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senato.it/documenti/repository/istituzione/costituzione_inglese.pdf|title=Constitution of the Italian Republic|publisher=Senato della Repubblica}}</ref> However, many languages other than Italian and the above-mentioned twelve are spoken across the country,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/country/IT|title=Italy|publisher=Ethnologue}}</ref> most of them being either [[Gallo-Italic languages|Gallo-Italic]] or [[Italo-Dalmatian languages|Italo-Dalmatian]], which lack any sort of official recognition and protection.

|url=https://playbill.com/article/george-hearn-thora-birch-and-michel-altieri-to-star-in-dracula-off-broadway-com-173663|title=George Hearn, Thora Birch and Michel Altieri to Star in Dracula old_content: The name of the town of Slavic origin and comes from the [[Slovene language|Slovene]] word {{lang|sl|gorica}} 'little mountain', which is a common [[toponym]] in [[Slovene Lands|Slovene-inhabited areas]]. old_content: In 2016, after [[Ireland v Commission|a two-year investigation]], the European Commission claimed that Apple's use of a hybrid [[Double Irish arrangement|Double Irish]] tax arrangement constituted "illegal state aid" from Ireland, and ordered Apple to pay 13 billion euros ($14.5 billion) in unpaid taxes, the largest corporate tax fine in history. This was later annulled, after the [[General Court (European Union)|European General Court]] ruled that the commission had provided insufficient evidence.<ref>{{Cite news |date=July 15, 2020 |title=Apple ne devra pas rembourser 13 milliards d'euros à l'Irlande, a conclu la justice européenne |language=fr |work=Le Monde |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2020/07/15/la-justice-europeenne-annule-la-decision-sommant-apple-de-rembourser-13-milliards-d-euros-a-l-irlande_6046257_3234.html |access-date=June 22, 2021 |archive-date=August 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210816095531/https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2020/07/15/la-justice-europeenne-annule-la-decision-sommant-apple-de-rembourser-13-milliards-d-euros-a-l-irlande_6046257_3234.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="IT11">{{cite news |last=Brennan |first=Joe |date=July 15, 2020 |title=Ireland wins appeal in €13bn Apple tax case |newspaper=[[Irish Times]] |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/ireland-wins-appeal-in-13bn-apple-tax-case-1.4305044 |access-date=July 15, 2020 |archive-date=July 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200715093010/https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/ireland-wins-appeal-in-13bn-apple-tax-case-1.4305044 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, Apple repatriated $285 billion to America, resulting in a $38 billion tax payment spread over the following eight years.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Wakabayashi |first1=Daisuke |last2=Chen |first2=Brian X. |date=January 17, 2018 |title=Apple, Capitalizing on New Tax Law, Plans to Bring Billions in Cash Back to U.S. |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/17/technology/apple-tax-bill-repatriate-cash.html}}</ref>

This was later annulled, after the [[General Court (European Union)|European General Court]] ruled that the commission had provided insufficient evidence.<ref>{{Cite news |date=July 15, 2020 |title=Apple ne devra pas rembourser 13 milliards d'euros à l'Irlande, a conclu la justice européenne |language=fr |work=Le Monde |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2020/07/15/la-justice-europeenne-annule-la-decision-sommant-apple-de-rembourser-13-milliards-d-euros-a-l-irlande_6046257_3234.html |access-date=June 22, 2021 |archive-date=August 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210816095531/https://www.lemonde.fr/economie/article/2020/07/15/la-justice-europeenne-annule-la-decision-sommant-apple-de-rembourser-13-milliards-d-euros-a-l-irlande_6046257_3234.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="IT11">{{cite news |last=Brennan |first=Joe |date=July 15, 2020 |title=Ireland wins appeal in €13bn Apple tax case |newspaper=[[Irish Times]] |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/ireland-wins-appeal-in-13bn-apple-tax-case-1.4305044 |access-date=July 15, 2020 |archive-date=July 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200715093010/https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/ireland-wins-appeal-in-13bn-apple-tax-case-1.4305044 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, Apple repatriated $285 billion to America, resulting in a $38 billion tax payment spread over the following eight years.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Wakabayashi |first1=Daisuke |last2=Chen |first2=Brian X. |date=January 17, 2018 |title=Apple, Capitalizing on New Tax Law, Plans to Bring Billions in Cash Back to U.S. |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/17/technology/apple-tax-bill-repatriate-cash.html}}</ref>

old_content: '''Ara Més''' ({{trans|Now More}}) was an [[electoral alliance]] formed in the [[Balearic Islands]] in April 2022 between [[Més per Mallorca|More for Mallorca]] (Més), [[Més per Menorca|More for Menorca]] (Més Menorca), [[Ara Eivissa|Now Eivissa]] (Ara Eivissa) and independent people from [[Formentera]], with the intention to contest the [[2023 Spanish general election]].<ref>{{cite news |date=30 April 2022 |url=https://cadenaser.com/2022/04/30/nace-ara-mes-un-nuevo-proyecto-politico-progresista-e-insularista-para-lograr-una-voz-efectiva-en-madrid/ |title=Nace Ara Més, un nuevo proyecto político progresista e insularista "para lograr una voz efectiva en Madrid" |language=es |publisher=Cadena SER |location=Ibiza |access-date=8 June 2023}}</ref> In June 2023, following the [[early election]] call after the 28 May [[2023 Spanish local elections|local]] and [[2023 Spanish regional elections|regional]] elections, the alliance started talks to join [[Yolanda Díaz]]'s [[Sumar (electoral platform)|Sumar]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Porcel |first=Guillem |date=31 May 2023 |url=https://www.diariodemallorca.es/mallorca/2023/05/31/mes-apunta-coalicion-sumar-exigira-88140977.html |title=Més apunta a una coalición con Sumar pero exigirá autonomía total |language=es |newspaper=Diario de Mallorca |location=Palma |access-date=8 June 2023}}</ref> reaching an agreement as [[Sumar Més]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Porcel |first=Guillem |date=9 May 2023 |url=https://www.diariodemallorca.es/mallorca/2023/06/09/vicenc-vidal-candidato-sumar-mes-88495343.html |title=Vicenç Vidal, candidato de Sumar Més a las generales: "Estamos cansados de que se diga una cosa aquí y otra en Madrid" |language=es |newspaper=Diario de Mallorca |location=Palma |access-date=10 June 2023}}</ref> with the exception of Ara Eivissa, that rejected to be part of the coalition.<ref>{{cite news |last=Crespí |first=Miquel |date=9 June 2023 |url=https://www.arabalears.cat/politica/ara-eivissa-unic-partit-ara-mes-rebutjat-coalicio-sumar_1_4725872.html |title=Ara Eivissa, l'únic partit d'Ara Més que ha rebutjat la coalició amb Sumar per a les generals |language=ca |newspaper=Ara Balears |location=Palma |access-date=10 June 2023}}</ref> Despite this, Ara Eivissa contested the Senate election as part of the [[Ibiza and Formentera in the Senate]] coalition.

Menorca|More for Menorca]] (Més Menorca), [[Ara Eivissa|Now Eivissa]] (Ara Eivissa) and independent people from [[Formentera]], with the intention to contest the [[2023 Spanish general election]].<ref>{{cite news |date=30 April 2022 |url=https://cadenaser.com/2022/04/30/nace-ara-mes-un-nuevo-proyecto-politico-progresista-e-insularista-para-lograr-una-voz-efectiva-en-madrid/ |title=Nace Ara Més, un nuevo proyecto político progresista e insularista "para lograr una voz efectiva en Madrid" |language=es |publisher=Cadena SER |location=Ibiza |access-date=8 June 2023}}</ref> In June 2023, following the [[early election]] call after the 28 May [[2023 Spanish local elections|local]] and [[2023 Spanish regional elections|regional]] elections, the alliance started talks to join [[Yolanda Díaz]]'s [[Sumar (electoral platform)|Sumar]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Porcel |first=Guillem |date=31 May 2023 |url=https://www.diariodemallorca.es/mallorca/2023/05/31/mes-apunta-coalicion-sumar-exigira-88140977.html |title=Més apunta a una coalición con Sumar pero exigirá autonomía total |language=es |newspaper=Diario de Mallorca |location=Palma |access-date=8 June 2023}}</ref> reaching an agreement as [[Sumar Més]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Porcel |first=Guillem |date=9 May 2023 |url=https://www.diariodemallorca.es/mallorca/2023/06/09/vicenc-vidal-candidato-sumar-mes-88495343.html |title=Vicenç Vidal, candidato de Sumar Més a las generales: "Estamos cansados de que se diga una cosa aquí y otra en Madrid" |language=es |newspaper=Diario de Mallorca |location=Palma |access-date=10 June 2023}}</ref> with the exception of Ara Eivissa, that rejected to be part of the coalition.<ref>{{cite news |last=Crespí |first=Miquel |date=9 June 2023 |url=https://www.arabalears.cat/politica/ara-eivissa-unic-partit-ara-mes-rebutjat-coalicio-sumar_1_4725872.html |title=Ara Eivissa, l'únic partit d'Ara Més que ha rebutjat la coalició amb Sumar per a les generals |language=ca |newspaper=Ara Balears |location=Palma |access-date=10 June 2023}}</ref> Despite this, Ara Eivissa contested the Senate election as part of the [[Ibiza and Formentera in the Senate]] coalition.

old_content: Spanish officials concluded that the crash had been caused by pilot error. During the approach to Bilbao, the autopilot's altitude select system failed to engage due to undetermined reasons, enabling the aircraft to descend past its target altitude. The altitude alarm had sounded to inform the crew that they had reached the intended altitude.  However, both crew members misinterpreted it and caused the aircraft to fly even lower. The left wing eventually struck a television antenna, shearing it off and causing the aircraft to crash.<ref name="CIAIAC">{{Cite web |last= |first= |date= |title=Accident that occurred on February 19, 1985 involving a Boeing 727-256 aircraft, registration EC-DDU, at Monte Oiz (Vizcaya) |url=http://www.fomento.es/NR/rdonlyres/FCDC0DE3-4C05-43AE-AEF2-703A6AA6FDD1/13043/1985_009_A_ENG.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924035010/http://www.fomento.es/NR/rdonlyres/FCDC0DE3-4C05-43AE-AEF2-703A6AA6FDD1/13043/1985_009_A_ENG.pdf |archive-date=2015-09-24 |access-date=2013-11-19 |website= |publisher=Civil Aviation Accident and Incident Investigation Commission |language=en}}</ref>
new_content: Spanish officials concluded that the crash had been caused by pilot error. During the approach to [[Bilbao]], the autopilot's altitude select system failed to engage due to undetermined reasons, enabling the aircraft to descend past its target altitude. The altitude alarm had sounded to inform the crew that they had reached the intended altitude.  However, both crew members misinterpreted it and caused the aircraft to fly even lower. The left wing eventually struck a television antenna, shearing it off and causing the aircraft to crash.<ref name="CIAIAC">{{Cite web |last= |first= |date= |title=Accident that occurred on February 19, 1985 involving a Boeing 727-256 aircraft, registration EC-DDU, at Monte Oiz (Vizcaya) |url=http://www.fomento.es/NR/rdonlyres/FCDC0DE3-4C05-43AE-AEF2-703A6AA6FDD1/13043/1985_009_A_ENG.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924035010/http://www.fomento.es/NR/rdonlyres/FCDC0DE3-4C05-43AE-AEF2-703A6AA6FDD1/13043/1985_009_A_ENG.pdf |archive-date=2015-09-24 |access-date=2013-11-19 |website= |publisher=Civil Aviation Accident and Incident Investigation Commission |language=en}}</ref>

old_content: '''Gerald Dempsey''' "'''Buster'''" '''Posey III'''<ref>Baggarly 2011, p. 10.</ref> (born March 27, 1987) is an American former [[professional baseball]] [[catcher]]. old_content: ''Basilisk'' was [[keel laying|laid down]] by [[J. Samuel White]] at [[East Cowes]] on the [[Isle of Wight]] with the yard number 1293 on 11 May 1909, and [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 9 February the following year.{{sfn|Williams|Sprake|1993|page=86}} The ship cost £109.729.{{sfn|March|1966|page=85}} ''Basilisk'' was the ninth to serve in the [[Royal Navy]] named for the [[Basilisk|mythical creature]].{{sfn|Manning|Walker|1959|page=99}} The vessel was commissioned at Portsmouth and joined the [[1st Destroyer Flotilla|First Destroyer Flotilla]] on 17 September.<ref>{{cite news|title=Naval And Military Intelligence|newspaper=The Times|issue=39380|date=17 September 1910|page=7}}</ref>  In 1912, a reorganisation of the [[Home Fleet]] resulted in the ships of the ''Beagle'' class forming the [[3rd Destroyer Flotilla|Third Destroyer Flotilla]].{{sfn|Manning|1961|page=25}} The vessel remained part of the Third Flotilla in March 1913..<ref>{{cite journal|title=Fleets and Squadrons in Commission at Home and Abroad: Flotillas of the First Fleet|journal=The Navy List|date=March 1913|page=269a|url=https://digital.nls.uk/british-military-lists/archive/94246518 |access-date=10 May 2024 |via=National Library of Scotland}}</ref> ''Basilisk'' was transferred, along with the rest of the class, to the newly-formed [[5th Destroyer Flotilla|Fifth Destroyer Flotilla]] as part of the [[Mediterranean Fleet]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Naval And Military Intelligence: Fifth Destroyer Flotilla for the Mediterranean|newspaper=The Times|issue=40358|date=1 November 1913|page=14}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Fleets and Squadrons in Commission at Home and Abroad: Mediterranean Fleet |journal=The Monthly Navy List |date=November 1913 |url=https://digital.nls.uk/british-military-lists/archive/94327994 |page=270a |access-date=10 May 2024 |via=National Library of Scotland}}</ref>

old_content: Among the changes to the prayer book and its liturgies that Jones sought in order to effect comprehension was the removal of the Athanasian Creed (due to its complexity rather than any error), excessive repetition of the [[Lord's Prayer]] and ''[[Gloria Patri]]'', and anything not permitted by the [[Bible]].<ref>{{harvnb|Jasper|1954|p=3}}; {{harvnb|Hefling|2021|p=211}}</ref> The [[lectionary]] and [[liturgical calendar]] were scrutinized, with Jones suggesting that [[proper (liturgy)|proper]] psalms be assigned to each Sunday.<ref name=JasperRev15/> Jones's Puritan-like views were made evident in urging for the [[sign of the cross]] in the baptismal office be made optional and private baptism abolished.<ref name=Cuming177178>{{harvnb|Cuming|1969|pp=177–178}}</ref> The matters of the sign of the cross and ending the practice of [[Godparent|sponsors]] at [[baptism]] were raised due to Jones's identification of these actions as vestiges of Catholicism that should be expunged. A similar grievance was raised about prohibitions on marriages occurring during particular seasons of the year.<ref>{{harvnb|Peaston|1940|pp=40–41}}</ref> The only explicit doctrinal change suggested in ''Free and Candid Disquisitions'' is the alteration or outright cessation of [[infant baptism]].<ref name=Marshall115>{{harvnb|Marshall|2004|p=115}}</ref>
new_content: Among the changes to the prayer book and its liturgies that Jones sought in order to effect comprehension was the removal of the Athanasian Creed (due to its complexity rather than any error), the deletion of excessive repetition of the [[Lord's Prayer]] and ''[[Gloria Patri]]'', and the excision of anything not permitted by the [[Bible]].<ref>{{harvnb|Jasper|1954|p=3}}; {{harvnb|Hefling|2021|p=211}}</ref> The [[lectionary]] and [[liturgical calendar]] were scrutinized, with Jones suggesting that [[proper (liturgy)|proper]] psalms be assigned to each Sunday.<ref name=JasperRev15/> Jones's Puritan-like views were made evident in urging for the [[sign of the cross]] in the baptismal office be made optional and private baptism abolished.<ref name=Cuming177178>{{harvnb|Cuming|1969|pp=177–178}}</ref> The matters of the sign of the cross and ending the practice of [[Godparent|sponsors]] at [[baptism]] were raised due to Jones's identification of these actions as vestiges of Catholicism that should be expunged. A similar grievance was raised about prohibitions on marriages occurring during particular seasons of the year.<ref>{{harvnb|Peaston|1940|pp=40–41}}</ref> The only explicit doctrinal change suggested in ''Free and Candid Disquisitions'' is the alteration or outright cessation of [[infant baptism]].<ref name=Marshall115>{{harvnb|Marshall|2004|p=115}}</ref>

old_content: In the early 1990s, Matacena was involved in the Olimpia maxi investigation, when the District Anti-Mafia Directorate of Reggio Calabria reconstructed some events of a criminal nature, including around a hundred murders, as well as the relationships between the 'Ndrangheta and politics, starting from the early 1980s.<ref name="ANSA 2014"/><ref name="Bongiovanni 2022"/><ref name="Quotidiano Nazionale 2022"/> On 14 July 1995, Matacena was summoned by the Public Prosecutor of [[Catanzaro]] as part of an investigation that accused him of having contributed, supported, and facilitated the complex and multiple activities and criminal purposes of the 'Ndrangheta, a mafia association present in the Calabrian and national territory.<ref name="Vita 2014"/> Among the charges were that Matacena had offered and delivered a sum of money to a local affiliate of Scilla during the 1988 Italian local elections, requested and obtained electoral consensus from members of numerous gangs in favour of a candidate for the Chamber of Deputies in 1992, and used the intimidating force of the gangs of the [[Gioia Tauro]] plain.<ref name="Vita 2014"/> The Public Prosecutor's Office requested a [[precautionary detention]] order for Matacena; the investigating judge of Catanzaro, citing a lack of conditions of the "serious indications of guilt", did not accept the request.<ref name="Vita 2014"/> The investigation was then transferred to the Prosecutor's Office of Reggio Calabria. In March 1998, Matacena was interrogated, and the Reggio Calabria Prosecutor's Office requested his indictment.<ref name="Vita 2014"/>
new_content: In the early 1990s, Matacena was involved in the Olimpia maxi investigation, when the District Anti-Mafia Directorate of Reggio Calabria reconstructed some events of a criminal nature, including around a hundred murders, as well as the relationships between the 'Ndrangheta and politics, starting from the early 1980s.<ref name="ANSA 2014"/><ref name="Bongiovanni 2022"/><ref name="Quotidiano Nazionale 2022"/> On 14 July 1995, Matacena was summoned by the Public Prosecutor of [[Catanzaro]] as part of an investigation that accused him of having contributed, supported, and facilitated the complex and multiple activities and criminal purposes of the 'Ndrangheta, a mafia association present in the Calabrian and national territory.<ref name="Vita 2014"/> Among the charges were that Matacena had offered and delivered a sum of money to a local affiliate of Scilla during the 1988 Italian local elections, requested and obtained electoral consensus from members of numerous gangs in favour of a candidate for the Chamber of Deputies in 1992, and used the intimidating force of the gangs of the [[Gioia Tauro]] plain.<ref name="Vita 2014"/> The Public Prosecutor's Office of Catanzaro requested a [[precautionary detention]] order for Matacena; the investigating judge of Catanzaro, citing a lack of conditions of the "serious indications of guilt", did not accept the request.<ref name="Vita 2014"/> The investigation was then transferred to the Prosecutor's Office of Reggio Calabria. In March 1998, Matacena was interrogated, and the Reggio Calabria Prosecutor's Office requested his indictment.<ref name="Vita 2014"/>
