old_content: Oxford have a number of independent supporters' clubs and groups such as OxVox (the Oxford United Supporters' Trust) with a current membership of over 400, and the Oxford United Exiles.<ref>{{cite news|title = Oxvox Homepage|url = http://www.oxvox.org.uk/|publisher = Oxvox.org.uk|access-date = 23 August 2007|archive-date = 30 August 2007|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070830104034/http://www.oxvox.org.uk/|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title = Oxford Exiles|url = http://www.ouexiles.org.uk/home.php|publisher = Ouexiles.org.uk|access-date = 23 March 2012|url-status = dead|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120430183350/http://www.ouexiles.org.uk/home.php|archive-date = 30 April 2012|df = dmy-all}}</ref> OxVox was formed in 2002, to replace the disbanded FOUL group, which broke up after the immediate future of the club was secured.<ref>Brodetsky p.100</ref> It was the fiftieth supporters trust created under the [[Supporters' trust]] banner. The club itself also runs a Juniors club, aimed at younger fans and offering a number of bonuses to the club's members such as birthday cards and a free T-shirt.<ref>{{cite news|title = Join the Juniors|url = http://www.oufc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Juniors/0,,10342,00.html|publisher = Oxford United|access-date = 13 January 2009|url-status = dead|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080915094244/http://www.oufc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Juniors/0,,10342,00.html|archive-date = 15 September 2008|df = dmy-all}}</ref> The official matchday programme for home games costs £3 and was voted best Conference Premier Programme of the Year for the 2007–08 season.<ref>{{cite news|title = Matchday Programme|url = http://www.oufc.co.uk/page/Programme/0,,10342,00.html|publisher = Oxford United|access-date = 27 January 2009|url-status = dead|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090206221206/http://www.oufc.co.uk/page/Programme/0,,10342,00.html|archive-date = 6 February 2009|df = dmy-all}}</ref>  A number of songs are sung during home games, such as "[[Yellow Submarine (song)|Yellow Submarine]]" (with adapted lyrics) and songs relating to the old Manor Ground.

old_content: Cave challenges previous historical conclusions that the Euro-American [[Puritans]] were motivated by the desire to advance self-interest through material gains in brutally executing the Pequot War. These were material gains such as "fear of Indian attack or greed for Pequot land, [[wampum]], animal pelts, and slaves."<ref name=Grumet/> Rather Cave argues that Puritans viewed the Pequots as untrustworthy savages and as a dangerous threat. These feelings led to a war with the Native Americans. However, it did result in the Puritans taking control of the land and its resources, as well as disenfranchising the Pequots as a political entity.<ref name=Hall/><ref name=Grumet/>
new_content: Cave challenges previous historical conclusions that the Euro-American [[Puritans]] were motivated by the desire to advance self-interest through material gains in brutally executing the Pequot War. old_content: '''Multaka – Museum as Meeting Point''' is an intercultural project initiated in 2015 by art history museums in [[Berlin]] with and for [[Arabic]] and [[Persian language|Persian]] speaking refugees and migrants. “Multaka” (Arabic: meeting point) was designed as an innovative project for educational exchange between refugees and other visitors from countries in the [[Middle East]] and [[North Africa]]. about cultural objects and their historical contexts with the exhibitions in Berlin museums.
new_content: '''Multaka – Museum as Meeting Point''' is an intercultural project initiated in 2015 by art history museums in [[Berlin]] with and for [[Arabic]] and [[Persian language|Persian]] speaking refugees and migrants. “Multaka” (Arabic: meeting point) was designed as an innovative project for educational exchange between refugees and other visitors from the [[Middle East]] and [[North Africa]]. Visitor-centered discussions with migrants in their languages focus on the [[Provenance|historical context and aquisition]] of the cultural objects, including the visitors' own understanding of their country's [[cultural heritage]].

old_content: As the [[World War I|First World War]] approached, ''Basilisk'' was part of the Second Division of the Fifth Flotilla and based in [[Alexandra]].{{sfn|Naval Staff Monograph No. 4|1919|page=179}} The destroyer sailed to [[Malta Dockyard|Malta]], joining the rest of the flotilla on 9 August.{{sfn|Naval Staff Monograph No. 4|1919|page=202}} The island had a coal shortage, which restricted the vessel's activity.{{sfn|Naval Staff Monograph No. 21|1923|page=8}} On 6 August 1914, the Second Division was deployed searching for the German warships {{SMS|Goeben||2}} and {{SMS|Breslau||2}} but this was curtailed by a lack of fuel.{{sfn|Naval Staff Monograph No. 21|1923|pages=35–36}} On 18 August, the destroyer was deployed to [[Suez]] to deter the Ottoman Empire from restricting British access to the [[Suez Canal]].{{sfn|Naval Staff Monograph No. 21|1923|page=57}} From 25 October, the destroyer, along with [[sister ship]] {{HMS|Racoon|1910|2}}, patrolled the Gulf of Suez.{{sfn|Naval Staff Monograph No. 21|1923|page=74}} The ship subsequently joined the force based in the Suez Canal and [[Red Sea]] to protect the sea lane for Allied shipping.{{sfn|Naval Staff Monograph No. 21|1923|page=79}}

old_content: Jamie King studied Fish Fingers at the [[University of Southampton]], where he received a PhD for his thesis, "''The Cultural Construction of fish fingers".'' He also attended the prestigious University of Preston whilst living with his parents. He was an original member of the ''[[Mute (magazine)|Mute]]'' editorial team and served as the bread and butter selector, Information politics editor and deputy editor.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hintz |first=Arne |date=2009 |title=Civil Society Media and Global Governance: Intervening Into the World Summit on the Information Society |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6Lcr_sXAh1EC&q=jamie+king+mute+magazine+activist&pg=PA164 |publisher=LIT Verlag Münster |page=164 |isbn=9783825818067}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work =Meta Mute |title =Terror is a Network |date =3 October 2002 |url =http://www.metamute.org/editorial/articles/terror-network-and-network-you}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work =The Independent |title =Technofile: Political Correction |url =https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/technofile-political-correction-1165054.html|date =14 June 1998 }}</ref>  During this time, he also published columns on the development of online culture for [[ITN]] and [[Channel 4]] News.<ref>{{cite web|work =Channel 4 |title =Coincidence of bomb exercises? |url =http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/uk/coincidence+of+bomb+exercises/109010.html}}</ref>

old_content: In the early morning hours of March 21, 2020, David entered Gretchen's home in [[Abacoa, Florida]], dressed in dark clothing. Surveillance footage captured David lurking on Gretchen's patio. The footage also captured muffled audio from Gretchen, who unsuccessfully attempted to call [[9-1-1]] through [[Amazon Alexa]]. A neighbor of Gretchen's later claimed to have heard a woman screaming as though she was being attacked. Additional footage captured David subsequently loading items into Gretchen's car.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W15mTlMEtjQ&t=202s|title=Court Cam: Murderer Blames His Crimes on COVID-19 {{!}} A&E|website=[[YouTube]]|publisher=[[A&E (TV network)|A&E]]|date=November 19, 2021|access-date=June 7, 2023}}</ref>

old_content: Cude was born in [[Barry, Vale of Glamorgan|Barry]], [[Wales]] in 1906, although his birthdate has been commonly listed as being in 1910.<ref name=thrj>{{cite journal |first=Lorne |last=Bell |title=Wilf Cude:Superstitions and Steak |journal=The Hockey Research Journal |issue=Volume XIX, 2015/16}}</ref> His father Harry Cude relocated the family to [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]] in search of employment. Wilf began playing ice hockey in Winnipeg and played for the St. Vital Saints and the Winnipeg Wellingtons in Winnipeg. Wilf was a childhood friend of [[Charlie Gardiner (ice hockey)|Charlie Gardiner]], who would also play in the National Hockey League.<ref name=thrj/> Wilf was a two-sport athlete. He was an outside right as a soccer player.
new_content: Cude was born in [[Barry, Vale of Glamorgan|Barry]], [[Wales]] in 1906, although his birthdate has been commonly listed as being in 1910.<ref name=thrj>{{cite journal |first=Lorne |last=Bell |title=Wilf Cude:Superstitions and Steak |journal=The Hockey Research Journal |issue=Volume XIX, 2015/16}}</ref> In 1913, the family moved to [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada. After [[World War I]] broke out, the family relocated to England where his father Harry was serving with a Canadian contingent. The family returned to Canada in 1919. Harry had war injuries and the family moved to [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]] for the drier climate.<ref name="gaz1935">{{cite news |work=The Montreal Gazette |title=From A Rink-Side Seat |first=Marc T. |last=McNeil |date=February 4, 1935 |page=14}}</ref> Wilf began playing ice hockey in Winnipeg and played for the St. Vital Saints and the Winnipeg Wellingtons in Winnipeg. The Expert Panel | journal = Archives of Internal Medicine | volume = 148 | issue = 1 | pages = 36–69 | date = January 1988 | pmid = 3422148 | doi = 10.1001/archinte.148.1.36 }}</ref> The [[American Heart Association]] provides a similar set of guidelines for total (fasting) blood cholesterol levels and risk for heart disease:<ref name=aha-prev/> Statins are effective in lowering LDL cholesterol and widely used for [[primary prevention]] in people at high risk of cardiovascular disease, as well as in [[secondary prevention]] for those who have developed cardiovascular disease.<ref name="AlenghatDavis2019">{{cite journal | vauthors = Alenghat FJ, Davis AM | title = Management of Blood Cholesterol | journal = JAMA | volume = 321 | issue = 8 | pages = 800–801 | date = February 2019 | pmid = 30715135 | pmc = 6679800 | doi = 10.1001/jama.2019.0015 }}</ref> The average global mean total Cholesterol for humans has remained at about 4.6 mmol/L (178 mg/dL) for men and women, both crude and age standardized, for nearly 40 years from 1980 to 2018, with some regional variations and reduction of total Cholesterol in Western nations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mean total cholesterol trends Global estimates |url=https://www.who.int/data/gho/data/indicators/indicator-details/GHO/mean-fasting-blood-glucose-age-standardized-estimate |website=World Health Organization |access-date=27 April 2024}}</ref>

old_content: Outside film, Taylor has appeared in television series such as ''[[Almost Human (TV series)|Almost Human]]'' (2013–2014) and ''[[Hemlock Grove (TV series)|Hemlock Grove]]'' (2013–2014). For her portrayal of Anne Blaine on three seasons of ''[[American Crime (TV series)|American Crime]]'' (2015–2017), she was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Limited or Anthology Series or Movie|Primetime Emmy for Outstanding Lead Actress]]. She received a further two [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series|Emmy nominations]] for her roles as Marty Glenn on [[The X-Files (season 5)|''The X-Files'']] (1998) and Lisa Kimmel on ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'' (2002–2005). Taylor's stage credits include [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] productions of [[Anton Chekhov]]'s ''[[Three Sisters (play)|Three Sisters]]'' (1997) and [[Scott McPherson]]'s ''[[Marvin's Room (play)|Marvin's Room]]'' (2017). She is married to playwright [[Nick Flynn]], with whom she has a daughter.
new_content: Outside film, Taylor has appeared in television series such as ''[[Almost Human (TV series)|Almost Human]]'' (2013–2014), ''[[Hemlock Grove (TV series)|Hemlock Grove]]'' (2013–2014), and ''[[Outer Range]]'' (2022-). She received a further two [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series|Emmy nominations]] for her roles as Marty Glenn on [[The X-Files (season 5)|''The X-Files'']] (1998) and Lisa Kimmel on ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'' (2002–2005). She is married to playwright [[Nick Flynn]], with whom she has a daughter.

old_content: ECs were first thought to arise from extraembryonic tissues because blood vessels were observed in the avian and mammalian embryos. However, after histological analysis, it was seen that ECs were found just in the embryo. This meant that blood vessels come from an intraembryonic source, the mesoderm.<ref name=Ferguson>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ferguson JW, Kelley RW, Patterson C| year = 2005 | title = Mechanisms of endothelial differentiation in embryonic vasculogenesis| journal = Journal of the American Heart Association | volume = 25 | issue = 11 | pages = 2246–2254| doi=10.1161/01.atv.0000183609.55154.44| pmid = 16123328 | doi-access = free}}</ref> Since these cells come from the mesoderm, it can become a wide variety of different things found in many different parts of the body.<ref name=":0" /> Role of insulin-like growth factors in endothelium differentiation
new_content: ECs were first thought to arise from extraembryonic tissues because blood vessels were observed in the avian and mammalian embryos. However, after histological analysis, it was seen that ECs were found just in the embryo. old_content: The [[food chain]] is based on [[chemosynthesis]] by methane- and sulfur-oxidizing bacteria, which in turn release nutrients for [[fungi]] and other [[bacteria]]. This forms [[microbial mat]]s on the cave walls and the surface of lakes and ponds which are grazed on by some of the animals. The grazers are then preyed on by predatory species.<ref>{{cite web |title=Microbial food webs in Movile Cave |url=https://gtr.ukri.org/projects?ref=NE%2FG017956%2F1 |website=UK Research and Innovation }}</ref> ''[[Nepa (insect)|Nepa]] anophthalma'' is the only known [[Stygofauna|cave-adapted]] water scorpion in the world.<ref name=Decu1994>{{cite journal |last1=Decu |first1=Vasile |last2=Gruia |first2=Magdalena |last3=Keffer |first3=S. L. |last4=Sarbu |first4=Serban Mircea |title=Stygobiotic Waterscorpion, Nepa anophthalma, n. sp. (Heteroptera: Nepidae), from a Sulfurous Cave in Romania |journal=Annals of the Entomological Society of America |date=1 November 1994 |volume=87 |issue=6 |pages=755–761 |doi=10.1093/aesa/87.6.755 }}</ref> While animals have lived in the cave for 5.5 million years, not all of them arrived simultaneously. One of the most recent animals recorded is the cave's only species of snail, ''[[Heleobia#Species|Heleobia dobrogica]]'', which has inhabited the cave for slightly more than 2 million years.<ref name=Nag2017>{{cite news |last1=Nag |first1=Oishimaya Sen |title=Movile Cave - An Oddity Of Romania |url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/movile-cave-an-oddity-of-romania.html |work=WorldAtlas |date=25 April 2017 }}</ref><ref name=FoxSkelly2015 /><ref name=Falniowski2008>Andrzej Falniowski, Magdalena Szarowska, Ioan Sirbu, Alexandra Hillebrand, Mihai Baciu: [https://www.mapress.com/mr/content/v28/2008f/n3p170.htm ''Heleobia dobrogica'' (Grossu & Negrea, 1989)(Gastropoda: Rissooidea: Cochliopidae) and the estimated time of its isolation in a continental analogue of hydrothermal vents]. In: Molluscan Research 28(3): pp 165-170. 22 Dec 2008. ISSN 1323-5818</ref>

old_content: '''Isaac Lowe''' (born January 1, 1994, Lancaster, Lancashire, United Kingdom) is a professional boxer. In 2018 he won the WBC International featherweight title when he defeated Lucan Rafael Baez by knockout. Lowe defeated [[Marco McCullough]] for the Commonwealth featherweight title.<ref>{{cite web|last=Damerell |first=Richard |url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12040/10184630/carl-frampton-v-scott-quigg-isaac-lowe-stops-marco-mccullough-in-commonwealth-clash |title=Carl Frampton vs Scott Quigg: Isaac Lowe stops Marco McCullough in Commonwealth clash | Boxing News |publisher=Sky Sports |date=2016-02-12 |accessdate=2017-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jmu-journalism.org.uk/fighting-for-his-future-with-fury-behind-him |title=Fighting for his future with Fury behind him - JMU Article |date=26 November 2018 }}</ref> He won the English [[British Boxing Board of Control]] featherweight title over Jamie Speight and defended the title in a draw against [[Ryan Doyle]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Adam Lord Email |url=http://www.thevisitor.co.uk/sport/isaac-lowe-stars-on-big-stage-to-lift-english-title-1-7446210 |title=Isaac Lowe stars on big stage to lift English title |publisher=The visitor |date=2015-09-06 |accessdate=2017-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://firstclassboxing.com/lowe-retains-english-title-with-split-draw-against-doyle/ |title=Lowe Retains English Title With Split Draw Against Ryan Doyle |publisher=First Class Boxing |date=2015-11-21 |accessdate=2017-02-25}}</ref> He fought [[Dennis Ceylan]] for the [[European Boxing Union]] featherweight title, with the match ending in a technical draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/dennis-ceylan-vs-isaac-lowe-euro-title-clash-on-march-18--112704 |title=Dennis Ceylan vs. Isaac Lowe Euro Title Clash on March 18 – ''Boxing News'' |publisher=Boxingscene.com |date=2017-01-16 |accessdate=2017-02-25}}</ref>

Or is it just about timber profits?|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/2018/02/11/can-cutting-trees-good-indiana-forests-just-timber-profits/1079825001/|accessdate=Feb 25, 2018|agency=Indy Star|date=Feb 11, 2018}}</ref> The Division of Forestry also points out that the state forests in Indiana exist partly to serve as a source of commodities for the state.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Janzen|first1=Nick|title=Hoosiers Debate Use Of State Forests As Logging Rates Increase|url=https://www.wfyi.org/news/articles/hoosiers-debate-use-of-state-forests-as-logging-rates-increase|accessdate=May 3, 2018|agency=WFYI Indianapolis|date=Aug 5, 2016}}</ref> Moreover, the Division of Forestry is required by Indiana state law to log timber in state forests that has worthy commercial value.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Indiana Department of Natural Resources|title=Timber Harvests in Indiana State Forests|url=https://www.in.gov/dnr/forestry/9656.htm|website=IN.gov|accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref>

old_content: In 1945 Dönitz continued with the same approach : type VII {{lang|de|schnorkel}} U-boats mounted 113 patrols to British waters from Norway and Germany. Sixty-five U-boats were lost by the end of the war. Another nineteen type IX U-boats sailed for the Americas; these U-boats sank three small warships and three merchants for the loss of nine of their own. Of the much awaited {{lang|de|elektroboote}}, only five Type XIII coastal {{lang|de|elektroboote}} made seven patrols in 1945 which sank five small freighters. Only one of the big type XXI {{lang|de|elektroboote}} embarked upon a patrol before the end of the war but it did not see action.{{Sfn|Blair|1996b|pp=662-690}} In the last month of the war, many U-boats fled the Baltic ports as they were overrun by the Russian army. Eight {{lang|de|elektroboote}} and nine other U-boats were sunk by Allied aircraft as they fled towards [[German U-boat bases in occupied Norway|bases in Norway]].{{Sfn|Blair|1996b|p=761}}

old_content: Afghanistan is rich in natural resources, including [[lithium]], [[iron]], [[zinc]], and [[copper]]. It is the second largest producer of [[cannabis resin]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=Morocco seizes over 840 kg of cannabis – Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-08/06/c_138288434.htm |access-date=2022-10-18 |website=xinhuanet.com}}</ref> and third largest of both [[saffron]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Afghanistan's Saffron on Media {{!}} AfGOV |url=https://www.mail.gov.af/en/afghanistan%E2%80%99s-saffron-media |access-date=2022-10-18 |website=mail.gov.af}}</ref> and [[Cashmere wool|cashmere]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Taliban Takeover Puts Afghanistan's Cashmere, Silk Industries at Risk |url=https://www.businessoffashion.com/news/global-markets/taliban-takeover-puts-afghanistans-cashmere-silk-industries-at-risk/ |access-date=2022-10-18 |website=The Business of Fashion |date=25 August 2021 |language=en}}</ref> The country is a member of the [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation]] and a founding member of the [[Organization of Islamic Cooperation]]. Due to the effects of war in recent decades, the country has dealt with high levels of [[terrorism]], [[Poverty in Afghanistan|poverty]], and [[Undernutrition in children|child malnutrition]]. Afghanistan remains among the world's [[least developed countries]], ranking 180th in the [[Human Development Index]]. Afghanistan's [[gross domestic product]] (GDP) is $81 billion by [[purchasing power parity]] and $20.1 billion by nominal values. Per capita, its GDP is amongst the lowest of any country {{As of|2020|lc=y}}.

old_content: Jessie Keyser is a 13-year-old girl from the village of Clifton, Indiana, in the 1840s. During a village-wide outbreak of [[diphtheria]], Jessie's mother reveals it is really 1996, and Clifton Village is a tourist attraction. Also, there are cameras all around watching them, but there are some blind spots. Jessica's mother takes her to a blind spot for the reveal because all the adults were contracted to not tell the kids.  Clifton is a replica of a historical village with the tourists hidden, watching the village's activity by video from under the ground. Originally it was much more lenient with its villagers when a man named Miles Clifton founded it, but is now very strict and prevents anyone from leaving. Her mother asks her to retrieve a cure now that her own sister Katie has taken ill; the owners of the attraction ceased to provide modern medical care to the villagers in order to preserve its authenticity. She tells Jessie to get the cure from a man named Isaac Neeley, who protested the opening of Clifton. Jessie's escape will be difficult because Clifton is guarded to ensure that none of the villagers leave or find out it is 1996. Jessie's mother shows her a hidden escape route that has not been sealed.

Her mother asks her to retrieve a cure now that her own sister Katie has taken ill; the owners of the attraction ceased to provide modern medical care to the villagers in order to preserve its authenticity. She tells Jessie to get the cure from a man named Isaac Neeley, who protested the opening of Clifton. Jessie's escape will be difficult because Clifton is guarded to ensure that none of the villagers leave or find out it is 1996. Jessie's mother shows her a hidden escape route that has not been sealed.

old_content: '''China–Switzerland relations''' officially began in 1918.<ref name="EDA">Yufang Zhou, Die Exterritorialitätsrechte der Schweiz in China (1918–1946), Frankfurt am Main und Bern 2003</ref> Relations between the two nations have been excellent, particularly in economic affairs, although relations have become somewhat strained due to Swiss criticism of the [[Persecution of Uyghurs in China|China's persecution of the Uyghurs]] and the [[2020 Hong Kong national security law]].
new_content: '''China–Switzerland relations''' officially began in 1918.<ref name="EDA">Yufang Zhou, Die Exterritorialitätsrechte der Schweiz in China (1918–1946), Frankfurt am Main und Bern 2003</ref> Economic relations between the two nations grew substantially in the 21st century, although relations have become somewhat strained since 2020 due to Swiss criticism of the [[Persecution of Uyghurs in China|China's persecution of the Uyghurs]] and the [[2020 Hong Kong national security law]].

old_content: The sequence of the island formation has been generally characterized as: Santa Maria (8.12 Ma), São Miguel (4.1 Ma), Terceira (3.52 Ma), Graciosa (2.5 Ma), Flores (2.16 Ma), Faial (0.7 Ma), São Jorge (0.55 Ma), Corvo (0.7 Ma) and the youngest, Pico (0.27 Ma).<ref name="Carine, 2010, p. 78">Carine, 2010, p. 78</ref> All islands have experienced volcanism during their geological history, with Late Holocene volcanism being recorded from Flores<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Andrade |first1=Mariana |last2=Ramalho |first2=Ricardo S. |last3=Pimentel |first3=Adriano |last4=Hernández |first4=Armand |last5=Kutterolf |first5=Steffen |last6=Sáez |first6=Alberto |last7=Benavente |first7=Mario |last8=Raposeiro |first8=Pedro M. |last9=Giralt |first9=Santiago |date=29 September 2021 |title=Unraveling the Holocene Eruptive History of Flores Island (Azores) Through the Analysis of Lacustrine Sedimentary Records |journal=[[Frontiers in Earth Science]] |volume=9 |page=889 |doi=10.3389/feart.2021.738178 |doi-access=free |bibcode=2021FrEaS...9..889A |issn=2296-6463 }}</ref> and Faial.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Góis-Marques |first1=C.A. |last2=Rubiales |first2=J.M. |last3=de Nascimento |first3=L. |last4=Menezes de Sequeira |first4=M. |last5=Fernández-Palacios |first5=J.M. |last6=Madeira |first6=J. |date=February 2020 |title=Oceanic Island forests buried by Holocene (Meghalayan) explosive eruptions: palaeobiodiversity in pre-anthropic volcanic charcoal from Faial Island (Azores, Portugal) and its palaeoecological implications |url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0034666719302386 |journal=[[Review of Palaeobotany and Palynology]] |language=en |volume=273 |pages=104116 |doi=10.1016/j.revpalbo.2019.104116 |bibcode=2020RPaPa.27304116G |hdl=10451/51565 |access-date=5 May 2024 |via=Elsevier Science Direct}}</ref> Within recorded "human settlement" history the islands of Santa Maria, Graciosa, Flores, and Corvo have not experienced any volcanic eruptions; in addition to active fumaroles and hot-springs, the remaining islands have had sporadic eruptions since the 14th century. Apart from the Capelinhos volcano in 1957–1958, the last recorded instance of "island formation" occurred off the coast of São Miguel, when the island of [[Sabrina Island (Azores)|Sabrina]] was briefly formed.

old_content: Born and raised in [[San Francisco, California]], Camilli attended [[Sacred Heart Cathedral Preparatory]]. He had an eight-year [[Minor League Baseball|minor league]] career before making his major league debut with the [[Chicago Cubs]] at the end of the {{Baseball year|1933}} season. He was traded to the Phillies in June 1934, and in each year from 1935 to 1937 he hit 25 or more home runs, [[batting average (baseball)|batting]] a career-high .339 and leading the National League in [[on-base percentage]] in the last season. But he also had a free-swinging style that led to numerous [[strikeout]]s; in his {{Baseball year|1934}} rookie season, he tied [[Hack Wilson]]'s modern National League record of 94 strikeouts, and in {{Baseball year|1935}} he set a new league mark with 113.
new_content: Born and raised in [[San Francisco, California]], Camilli attended [[Sacred Heart Cathedral Preparatory]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Trezza |first=Joe |date=February 2, 2017 |title=Who are the top 5 all-time players from San Francisco? |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/top-5-all-time-players-from-san-francisco-c214998904 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221026034826/https://www.mlb.com/news/top-5-all-time-players-from-san-francisco-c214998904 |archive-date=October 26, 2022 |access-date=April 2, 2024 |website=MLB.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Dolph Camilli |url=https://bashof.org/inductee/dolph-camilli/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240402130444/https://bashof.org/inductee/dolph-camilli/ |archive-date=April 2, 2024 |access-date=April 2, 2024 |website=Bay Area Sports Hall of Fame |language=en-US}}</ref> He had an eight-year [[Minor League Baseball|minor league]] career before making his major league debut with the [[Chicago Cubs]] at the end of the {{Baseball year|1933}} season. He was traded to the Phillies in June 1934, and in each year from 1935 to 1937 he hit 25 or more home runs, [[batting average (baseball)|batting]] a career-high .339 and leading the National League in [[on-base percentage]] in the last season. But he also had a free-swinging style that led to numerous [[strikeout]]s; in his {{Baseball year|1934}} rookie season, he tied [[Hack Wilson]]'s modern National League record of 94 strikeouts, and in {{Baseball year|1935}} he set a new league mark with 113.

old_content: The '''SNCASE S.E.5000 Baroudeur''' was a French single-engined [[light fighter|lightweight fighter]] designed by [[SNCASE]] (''Sud-Est'') for the NATO [[NBMR-1]] "Light Weight Strike Fighter" competition. An unusual design without a conventional landing gear, it used a wheeled trolley for take-off and three retractable skids to land. The Baroudeur did not enter production.
new_content: The '''SNCASE S.E.5000 Baroudeur'''  ({{lang-fr|Adventurer}}) was a French single-engined [[light fighter|lightweight fighter]] designed by [[SNCASE]] (''Sud-Est'') for the NATO [[NBMR-1]] "Light Weight Strike Fighter" competition. An unusual design without a conventional landing gear, it used a wheeled trolley for take-off and three retractable skids to land. The Baroudeur did not enter production.

Tajiks are a minority in [[Uzbekistan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Tajik Tragedy of Uzbekistan |url=https://thediplomat.com/2016/09/the-tajik-tragedy-of-uzbekistan/ |work=The Diplomat |date=6 September 2016 |access-date=12 February 2022 |archive-date=19 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200619165415/https://thediplomat.com/2016/09/the-tajik-tragedy-of-uzbekistan/ |url-status=live }}</ref> More than 3 million Tajik citizens were officially registered in Russia in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |title=Doctor Drain: 'Exodus' Of Tajiks To Russia Seen As Migration Laws Eased |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/tajikistan-russia-exodus-migration-brain-drain/31700293.html |work=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=12 February 2022 |access-date=12 February 2022 |archive-date=12 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220212165000/https://www.rferl.org/a/tajikistan-russia-exodus-migration-brain-drain/31700293.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

old_content: O'Reilly has sponsored and supported a wide range of charitable activities and continues to do so. Many of these, such as the many-year support of a Professorship in Australian Studies at UCD, were arranged together with his first wife, and likewise today, he and his current wife will often jointly support an activity, such as sponsorship of a gallery at the '''National Science Historical Museum''' adjacent to [[Birr Castle]]. He has shown a particular interest in ''naming rights'', where a contribution to a project, generally of 5% to 20%, allows a donor to add a name to the project, and has received at least one such "name" as a gift.
new_content: O'Reilly sponsored and supported a wide range of charitable activities. Many of these, such as the many-year support of a Professorship in Australian Studies at UCD, were arranged together with his first wife, and likewise later, he and his second wife would often jointly support an activity, such as sponsorship of a gallery at the '''National Science Historical Museum''' adjacent to [[Birr Castle]]. He showed a particular interest in ''naming rights'', where a contribution to a project, generally of 5% to 20%, allows a donor to add a name to the project, and has received at least one such "name" as a gift.

old_content: Mwedihanga began his soccer career playing for Teenagers Football club in [[Ongwediva]].  He then moved to [[United Africa Tigers]], where he made a name for himself as a no nonsense centre back. In 2012, he joined [[AmaZulu F.C.|Amazulu FC]]. He later left [[AmaZulu F.C.|Amazulu FC]] at the end of 2014/2015 season after they got relegated and joined [[University of Pretoria]]. old_content: The term ''acqui-hire'' was coined in 2005. The phenomenon gained widespread attention in the 2010s due to media coverage of [[Silicon Valley]] tech firms, although acqui-hiring has been reported in a variety of industries. With acqui-hiring, the company is aiming to acquire not only talented individuals but a cohesive group of people that are productive jointly. The capital expenditure of purchasing may be more tax advantaged compared to [[employee poaching]]. Compared to other mergers and acquisitions, acqui-hires are smaller, faster, and involve startups that have not earned any revenue. Acqui-hiring is most likely when talent is scarce.

old_content: The use of intimacy coordinators on film and television sets had drawn both criticism and support within the industry. Actors and filmmakers including [[Gaspar Noé]], [[Mia Hansen-Løve]], [[Toni Collette]], [[Michael Douglas]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Ruimy|first=Jordan|title=Michael Douglas Says Intimacy Coordinators “Take Control Away From Filmmakers”|url=https://www.worldofreel.com/blog/2024/5/9/michael-douglas-says-intimacy-coordinators-take-control-away-from-filmmakers|work=WorldofReel|date=9 May 2024}}</ref> [[Michael Caine]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Gearan|first=Hannah|title=“We Never Had That In My Day”: Michael Caine Questions The Need For Intimacy Coordinators On Set|url=https://screenrant.com/michael-caine-intimacy-coordinators-opinion-response/|work=Screenrant|date=26 September 2023}}</ref> and [[Sean Bean]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Yossman|first=K.J.|title=‘Games of Thrones’ Star Sean Bean Says Intimacy Coordinators ‘Spoil the Spontaneity,’ Decries Censorship|url=https://variety.com/2022/tv/news/sean-bean-intimacy-coordinators-1235335687/|work=Variety|date=8 August 2022}}</ref> have all criticized the use of intimacy coordinators within the industry. old_content: '''The Petersfield School''' ('''TPS''') is located in [[Petersfield, Hampshire|Petersfield]], [[Hampshire]], in southern [[England]]. A human being is a sympathetic entity. No matter how terrible a person might be, someone with an artist’s point of view will try to render his individuality without condescension or contempt. That’s the natural function of a dramatist. The movies I’ve made have no connection to my personal beliefs. They don’t say, "Do this", or "Don't do that". They portray a kind of emptiness in people who are living through a transitional cultural period when they don’t know who they are or what to do."{{Cite web |title=Conversation with Paul Morrissey (Part I) {{!}} Jonathan Rosenbaum |url=https://jonathanrosenbaum.net/2021/12/conversation-with-paul-morrissey-part-i/ |access-date=2024-05-18 |website=jonathanrosenbaum.net}}

old_content: MSNBC is generally regarded as having a liberal political stance.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |title=MSNBC |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]] |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/MSNBC |access-date=2022-07-06 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220722131530/https://www.britannica.com/topic/MSNBC |archive-date=July 22, 2022}}</ref>{{bettersource}} In November 2007, a ''New York Times'' article stated that MSNBC's primetime lineup was tilting more to the left.<ref name="NYT">{{Cite news |last=Steinberg |first=Jacques |date=November 6, 2007 |title=Cable Channel Nods to Ratings and Leans Left |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/06/business/media/06msnb.html?_r=2&oref=slogin&pagewanted=print&oref=slogin |access-date=August 24, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220503123902/https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/06/business/media/06msnb.html?_r=2&oref=slogin&pagewanted=print&oref=slogin |archive-date=May 3, 2022}}</ref> Since then, commentators have argued that MSNBC has a bias towards [[liberalism|liberal politics]] and the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. ''[[Washington Post]]'' media analyst [[Howard Kurtz]] said in 2008 that the channel's evening lineup "has clearly gravitated to the left in recent years and often seems to regard itself as the antithesis of Fox News."<ref name="Kurtz" /> In 2011, ''[[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]'' referred to MSNBC as "left-leaning",<ref name="MSNBC host coaxes Ron Paul to run">{{Cite news |last=Barr |first=Andy |date=April 5, 2011 |title= MSNBC host coaxes Ron to run |work=[[Politico]] |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0411/52608.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408135433/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0411/52608.html |archive-date=April 8, 2011}}</ref> and Steve Kornacki of ''[[Salon.com]]'' stated that, "MSNBC's prime-time lineup is now awash in [[Contemporary progressivism|progressive]] politics."<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Kornacki |first1=Steve |author-link1=Steve Kornacki |date=January 22, 2011 |title=Is Olbermann the victim of his own success? |work=[[Salon.com|Salon]] |url=http://www.salon.com/2011/01/22/countdown_rip |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114162215/http://www.salon.com/2011/01/22/countdown_rip |archive-date=November 14, 2013}}</ref> Regarding changes in the channel's evening programming, senior vice president of NBC News Phil Griffin said that "it happened naturally. old_content: Ryan, who went to [[Xavier College]], was cleared to Collingwood from [[Williamstown Football Club|Williamstown]], in the [[Victorian Football Association]].<ref name=Ency>{{cite book |last1=Holmesby |first1=Russell |last2=Main |first2=Jim |title=The Encyclopedia Of AFL Footballers| publisher=BAS Publishing|year=2007|isbn=9781920910785}}</ref> In 1941, his debut season, Ryan was one of five Collingwood players to appear in all 18 rounds.<ref name=AFLTables>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/T/Ted_Ryan0.html| title=Ted Ryan| publisher=AFL Tables}}</ref> Due to wartime service in the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] he did not play senior football again until 1944, when he made 11 appearances while on leave.<ref name=AFLTables/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11815097 |title=LEAGUE PLAYERS TRAIN WELL. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne|date=31 May 1944 |accessdate=5 March 2014 |page=11 |publisher=National Library}}</ref> A defender, Ryan played four more games, two in 1946 and another two in 1947.<ref name=AFLTables/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article22441616 |title=COLLINGWOOD MAKE TWO SURPRISE CHANGES. |newspaper=The Argus |location=Melbourne, Vic|date=22 August 1947 |page=21}}</ref>

old_content: [[Transparency International]]'s 2023 [[Corruption Perceptions Index]], which scored 180 countries on a scale from 0 ("highly corrupt") to 100 ("very clean"), gave Kazakhstan a score of 39. When ranked by score, Kazakhstan ranked 93rd among the 180 countries in the Index, where the country ranked first is perceived to have the most honest public sector.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The ABCs of the CPI: How the Corruption Perceptions Index is calculated |url=https://www.transparency.org/en/news/how-cpi-scores-are-calculated |access-date=30 March 2023 |website=Transparency.org |date=20 December 2021 |language=en}}</ref> For comparison with worldwide scores, the best score was 90 (ranked 1), the average score was 43, and the worst score was 11 (ranked 180).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2023: Kazakhstan |url=https://www.transparency.org/en/cpi/2023/index/kaz |access-date=30 March 2024 |website=Transparency.org |language=en}}</ref> For comparison with regional scores, the highest score among Eastern European and Central Asian countries {{efn|Albania, Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kosovo, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Montenegro, North Macedonia, Russia, Serbia, Tajikistan, Turkey, Turkmenistan, Ukraine, Uzbekistan}} was 53, the average score was 35 and the lowest score was 18.<ref>{{Cite web |title=CPI 2023 for Eastern Europe & Central Asia: Autocracy & weak justice systems enabling widespread corruption  |url=https://www.transparency.org/en/news/cpi-2023-eastern-europe-central-asia-autocracy-weak-justice-systems-widespread-enabling-corruption |access-date=30 March 2024  |website=Transparency.org|language=en}}</ref>

He was suspended one game by the [[Big Ten Conference]] for his role in the brawl.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Borzello |first1=Jeff |last2=Rittenberg |first2=Adam |title=Michigan men's basketball coach Juwan Howard suspended for rest of Wolverines' regular season after postgame altercation at Wisconsin |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/33343690/michigan-men-basketball-coach-juwan-howard-suspended-rest-regular-season-altercation-wisconsin-sources-say |access-date=22 February 2022 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=21 February 2022}}</ref> Diabaté was named to the Big Ten All-Freshman Team.<ref name=B10Awards>{{cite press release|url=https://bigten.org/news/2022/3/8/2021-22-big-ten-mens-basketball-postseason-honors-announced.aspx|title=2021-22 Big Ten Men's Basketball Postseason Honors Announced|publisher=[[Big Ten Conference]] |date=March 8, 2022 |accessdate=March 8, 2022}}</ref> He averaged 9.0 points and 6.0 rebounds in his freshman season. old_content: The [[DC Universe (franchise)|DC Universe]] (DCU) is an American [[media franchise]] and [[Shared universe|shared]] [[fictional universe]] that is the setting of [[superhero film]]s and [[Superhero fiction#Live-action television series|television series]] produced by [[DC Studios]], based on characters that appear in [[DC Comics]] publications. DC Studios developed the DCU as a "[[Reboot (fiction)|soft reboot]]" of the prior DC Comics-based franchise the [[DC Extended Universe]] (DCEU) that retains certain cast members of the DCEU while replacing others. No actor would be playing multiple characters, with DC Studios co-CEOs [[James Gunn]] and [[Peter Safran]] expecting the same actors to play characters across mediums, including animation. The DCU's first slate of content is Chapter One: Gods and Monsters, which includes five feature films: ''[[Superman (2025 film)|Superman]]'' (2025), ''[[Supergirl: Woman of Tomorrow]]'' (2026), ''[[The Authority (film)|The Authority]]'', ''[[The Brave and the Bold (film)|The Brave and the Bold]]'', and ''[[Swamp Thing (upcoming film)|Swamp Thing]]'', and five series: the animated ''[[Creature Commandos (TV series)|Creature Commandos]]'' (2024), ''[[Waller (TV series)|Waller]]'' (2024), ''[[Lanterns (TV series)|Lanterns]]'', ''[[Paradise Lost (upcoming TV series)|Paradise Lost]]'', ''[[Booster Gold (TV series)|Booster Gold]]'', and the [[Peacemaker season 2|second season]] of ''[[Peacemaker (TV series)|Peacemaker]]''. An [[untitled Arkham series]] is also in development for the DCU. As the franchise will be composed of films and series adapted from a variety of DC Comics properties, there will be multiple lead actors.

old_content: In Batesian mimicry, the mimic effectively copies the coloration of an aposematic animal, known as the model, to deceive predators into behaving as if it were distasteful.{{efn|This is often described as parasitizing the honest signals.<ref name="Gohli Högstedt 2010">{{cite journal |last1=Gohli |first1=Jostein |last2=Högstedt |first2=Göran |title=Reliability in aposematic signaling |journal=Communicative & Integrative Biology |publisher=Informa UK Limited|volume=3 |issue=1 |year=2010 |issn=1942-0889 |doi=10.4161/cib.3.1.9782 |pages=9–11|pmid=20539774 |pmc=2881232 |doi-access=free }}</ref>}} The success of this dishonest display depends on the level of toxicity of the model and the abundance of the model in the geographical area. The more toxic the model is, the more likely it is that the predator will avoid the mimic.<ref name=Caro2014>{{cite journal |author=Caro, T. |author-link=Tim Caro |year=2014 |title=Antipredator deception in terrestrial vertebrates |journal=Current Zoology |volume=60 |pages=16–25|doi=10.1093/czoolo/60.1.16 |doi-access=free }}</ref> The abundance of the model species is also important for the success of the mimic because of [[frequency-dependent selection]]. When the model is abundant, mimics with imperfect model patterns or slightly different coloration from the model are still avoided by predators. This is because the predator has a strong incentive to avoid potentially lethal organisms, given the likelihood of encountering one.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Kikuchi, D. W. |author2=Pfennig, D. W. |year=2009 |title=High-model abundance may permit the gradual evolution of Batesian mimicry: an experimental test |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B |volume=277 |issue=1684 |pages=1041–1048 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2009.2000 |pmid=19955153 |pmc=2842773}}</ref> However, in areas where the model is scarce or locally extinct, mimics are driven to accurate aposematic coloration. This is because predators attack imperfect mimics more readily where there is little chance that they are the model species.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Akcali, C. K. |author2=D. W. Pfennig.  |name-list-style=amp |year= 2014 |title=Rapid evolution of mimicry following local model extinction |journal=Biology Letters |volume=10 |issue=6  |page=4 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2014.0304 |pmid=24919704 |pmc=4090552}}</ref> Frequency-dependent selection may also have driven Batesian mimics to become polymorphic in rare cases where a single genetic switch controls appearance, as in the swallowtail butterflies (the [[Papilionidae]]) such as the [[Battus philenor|pipevine swallowtail]],<ref name=JoronMallet>{{cite journal |last1=Joron |first1=Mathieu |last2=Mallet |first2=James L. B. |title=Diversity in mimicry: paradox or paradigm? |journal=Tree |date=11 November 1998 |volume=13 |issue=11 |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/taxome/jim/pap/JoronMalletTREE98.pdf |pages=461–466 |doi=10.1016/s0169-5347(98)01483-9|pmid=21238394 }}</ref> and in the New Zealand stonefly ''Zelandoperla fenestrata''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foster |first1=Brodie |last2=McCulloch |first2=Graham |last3=Foster |first3=Yasmin |last4=Kroos |first4=Gracie |last5=King |first5=Tania |last6=Waters |first6=Jonathan |title=ebony underpins Batesian mimicry in melanic stoneflies |journal=Molecular Ecology |date=July 2023 |volume=32 |issue=18 |pages=4986–4998 |doi=10.1111/mec.17085 |pmid=37503654 |doi-access=free |bibcode=2023MolEc..32.4986F }}</ref>

old_content: Kurtz's mother was half [[English people|English]], his father was half [[French people|French]] and thus "All Europe contributed to the making of Kurtz." As the reader finds out at the end, Kurtz is a multitalented man—painter, musician, writer, promising politician. He starts out, years before the novel begins, as an [[imperialism|imperialist]] in the best tradition of the "[[white man's burden]]". The reader is introduced to a painting of Kurtz's, depicting a blindfolded woman bearing a torch against a nearly black background, and clearly symbolic of his former views. Kurtz's painting suggests that he saw himself as a civilizing force, aiming to educate and enlighten the African continent, which was then often referred to as the "dark continent" due to its perceived unknownness and perceived backwardness by European colonizers.<ref>{{Cite web |title=A Critical Analysis of Kurtz's Painting in ''Heart of Darkness'' |url=https://literaryanalysishub.blogspot.com/2024/05/kurtz-painting-symbolism-heart-of-darkness.html |access-date=2024-05-15 |website=Literary Analysis Hub |date=9 May 2024 }}</ref> Kurtz is also the author of a pamphlet regarding the civilization of the natives.

old_content: In 2021, [[Renfe]], the national operator of Spain announced it was proposing competing London to Paris services.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/transport/renfe-channel-tunnel-high-speed-service-london-paris-eurostar-b962795.html|title=Spain's state-owned train operator Renfe plans to launch high-speed London to Paris service |date = 28 October 2021 | work=Evening Standard | location=London}}</ref> In 2022, [[Getlink]], the owner of the [[Channel Tunnel]] had reportedly considered purchasing trains suitable for competing services, leasing them to rival operations.,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/rivals-to-eurostar-in-advanced-talks-264580/ |title=Eurostar could face rival high speed rail service as Getlink in talks with Spanish rail firm Renfe | date=27 March 2022 |work=Kent Online }}</ref> while in 2023, [[Mobico Group]], the owner of [[National Express]] has also been reported to be considering cross-Channel services named 'Evoyln'.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.railtech.com/all/2023/08/02/channel-tunnel-hopefuls-mount-another-challenge-to-eurostar/ |title=Channel Tunnel hopefuls mount another challenge to Eurostar|date=2 August 2023|work=Rail Tech}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.railtech.com/rolling-stock/2022/03/25/how-getlink-wants-to-clear-a-hurdle-for-new-operators-to-run-trains-through-the-channel-tunnel/|title=How Getlink wants to clear a hurdle for new operators to run trains through the Channel Tunnel|date=25 March 2022|work=Rail Tech}}</ref>

old_content: Professor [[Alec Jeffreys]], the forensic scientist who invented DNA fingerp 315.1C, which is present in more than 99% of people of European descent.<ref name="independent2">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/jack-the-ripper-id-hinges-on-a-decimal-point-as-scientists-flag-up-dna-error-in-book-that-claims-to-identify-the-whitechapel-killer-9804325.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019021203/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/jack-the-ripper-id-hinges-on-a-decimal-point-as-scientists-flag-up-dna-error-in-book-that-claims-to-identify-the-whitechapel-killer-9804325.html |archive-date=2014-10-19 |url-access=limited |url-status=live|title=Jack the Ripper: Scientist who claims to have identified notorious killer has 'made serious DNA error'|date=19 October 2014|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref>
new_content: Professor [[Alec Jeffreys]], the forensic scientist who invented DNA fingerprinting in 1984, initially commented that the find was "an interesting but remarkable claim that needs to be subjected to peer review, with detailed analysis of the provenance of the shawl and the nature of the claimed DNA match with the perpetrator's descendants and its power of discrimination".<ref name="independent"/> Jeffreys and others later stated that a claim presented in the book as a statistically significant match with the DNA from Eddowes's descendant—a sequence variation described as 314.1C and claimed to be rare—was the result of an error in nomenclature for the common sequence variation 315.1C, which is present in more than 99% of people of European descent.<ref name="independent2">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/jack-the-ripper-id-hinges-on-a-decimal-point-as-scientists-flag-up-dna-error-in-book-that-claims-to-identify-the-whitechapel-killer-9804325.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019021203/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/jack-the-ripper-id-hinges-on-a-decimal-point-as-scientists-flag-up-dna-error-in-book-that-claims-to-identify-the-whitechapel-killer-9804325.html |archive-date=2014-10-19 |url-access=limited |url-status=live|title=Jack the Ripper: Scientist who claims to have identified notorious killer has 'made serious DNA error'|date=19 October 2014|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref>

old_content: '''''Assassin's Creed Shadows''''' is an upcoming [[Action role-playing game|action role-playing]] [[video game]] developed by [[Ubisoft Quebec]] and published by [[Ubisoft]], set to release in November 2024. The game is the fourteenth major installment in the ''[[Assassin's Creed]]'' series and the successor to 2023's ''[[Assassin's Creed Mirage]]'', as well as the first title to be included in the ''[[Assassin's Creed: Infinity]]'' platform. Set in 16th-century [[Japan]] towards the end of the [[Sengoku period]], the game will focus on the millenia-old struggle of the [[Order of Assassins|Assassin Brotherhood]], who fight for peace and liberty, and the [[Knights Templar|Templar Order]], who desire peace through control, from the perspective of two protagonists: Naoe, a female [[Ninja|shinobi]], and Yasuke, an African [[samurai]] inspired by the [[Yasuke|historical figure of the same name]]. The two characters control differently and provide a unique gameplay style, allowing quests to be approached in multiple ways.

old_content: '''Beastie Boys Square''' is a dedicated historic location at the intersection of Ludlow and Rivington in the Manhattan borough of NYC.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bocanegra |first=Michelle |last2= |date=2023-09-09 |title=NYC officially renames Ludlow and Rivington streets 'Beastie Boys Square' |url=https://gothamist.com/arts-entertainment/nyc-officially-renames-ludlow-and-rivington-streets-beastie-boys-square |access-date=2024-05-18 |website=Gothamist |language=en}}</ref> The intersection was immortalized when it appeared on the Beastie Boys' 1989 album Paula's Boutique.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Richards |first=Will |date=2023-09-10 |title='Paul's Boutique' intersection officially renamed Beastie Boys Square |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/pauls-boutique-intersection-officially-renamed-beastie-boys-square-3495757 |access-date=2024-05-18 |website=NME |language=en-GB}}</ref> After a decade of petitioning the community board, on September 8th, 2023 the intersection was officially renamed with an event at which both Mike D and Ad-Rock spoke at.<ref name=":0" />

old_content: '''Jonathan Mark Smith Whittington''' (born 17 August 1973), known as '''Jont''', is an English singer, songwriter and musician.<ref name="Author Unknown 2008">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2005/11/19/jont_interview_feature.shtml |title=From Trent Bridge to the Social |publisher=BBC |date=19 November 2005 |access-date=18 May 2024}}</ref> First achieving prominence as a [[Left-arm orthodox spin|slow left-arm spinner]] for [[Middlesex County Cricket Club]],<ref name="Palmer, Judith 2008">{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Judith |title=The mad cow collective |url=https://infoweb.newsbank.com/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWGLNB&req_dat=1054640702C8DBC0&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F131FFEDDE36595A0 |access-date=13 March 2024 |work=The Independent |via=Newsbank |date=14 June 1996}}</ref> he then shifted focus to poetry then to music. Mainstream attention followed after his song "Sweetheart" was featured on the soundtrack to the 2005 US comedy film ''[[Wedding Crashers]]'' and two tracks from his 2008 album ''Supernatural'' were featured in season 5 of the US medical drama ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]''.

old_content: The term ''acqui-hire'' was coined in 2005. The phenomenon gained widespread attention in the 2010s due to media coverage of [[Silicon Valley]] tech firms, although acqui-hiring has been reported in a variety of industries.
new_content: The term ''acqui-hire'' was coined in 2005. The phenomenon gained widespread attention in the 2010s due to media coverage of [[Silicon Valley]] tech firms, although acqui-hiring has been reported in a variety of industries. With acqui-hiring, the company is aiming to acquire not only talented individuals but a cohesive group of people that are productive jointly. The capital expenditure of purchasing may be more tax advantaged compared to [[employee poaching]]. Compared to other mergers and acquisitions, acqui-hires are smaller, faster, and involve startups that have not earned any revenue. Acqui-hiring is most likely when talent is scarce.

old_content: | ShortSummary    = Behind Japan's prolonged period of peace, lies the intelligence organization "DA", which employs young orphaned girls known as "Lycoris" to covertly eliminate criminals and terrorists. Lycoris Takina Inoue is dismissed from the DA and partnered with Chisato Nishikigi after disobeying orders, risking the life of fellow Lycoris Erika. She reports to one of DA's front operations, Café LycoReco, run by its owner Mika and former DA agent Mizuki Nakahara. Meanwhile, the DA investigates a hacker named "Walnut" who breached their systems, as well as weapons which went missing from an arms deal. Chisato informs Takina that their job is to help others in need any way they can while showing her around. While protecting Saori Shinohara from a stalker, they realize she accidentally caught the ongoing arms deal in a picture she took. Takina uses Saori as a decoy to lure out the terrorists stalking her, but Chisato nonlethally subdues them before she can kill them. Meanwhile, a man from the Alan Institute who hired Walnut to spy on Chisato presumably kills him after bombing his apartment. The next day, Takina officially becomes LycoReco's newest waitress, and the man from the Alan Institute visits, who Mika recognizes.

old_content: * In 2016, Adichie was invited to speak about her thoughts on [[Donald Trump]]'s election to the [[President of the United States|US Presidency]] for the [[BBC]]'s program ''[[Newsnight]]''. When she arrived at the studio, she was informed that the format would be a debate between her and [[Emmett Tyrrell|R. Emmett Tyrrell, Jr.]], a Trump supporter and the [[editor-in-chief]] of ''[[The American Spectator]]'', a conservative magazine.(cite [https://hub.jhu.edu/2017/02/09/chimamanda-adichie-fas-hopkins/ Pearce] 2017 and [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/nov/28/chimamanda-ngozi-adichie-slams-bbc-ambush-with-trump-supporter-newsnight Cain] 2016) Tempted to walk out of the interview, Adichie decided to continue because she wanted to discuss her views on how economic disenfranchisement had led to Trump's victory.(cite Pearce 2017) The debate turned adversarial when Tyrrell said "I do not respond emotionally like this lady",(cite Cain 2016) and then "Trump hasn't been a racist".(cite to [https://www.theroot.com/watch-chimamanda-adichie-schools-white-man-you-don-t-1790857702 [[The Root (magazine)]] 2016). She countered his statements and a gave an example citing Trump's statement that Judge [[Gonzalo P. Curiel]] could not be impartial in the case ''[[Trump University#Low v. Trump University, LLC|Low v. Trump University]]'' because of his Mexican heritage.(cite to ''The Root'' 2016). After the debate, she wrote on her Facebook that she felt ambushed by the BBC and that they had "sneakily [pitted her] against a Trump supporter" to create adversarial entertainment. In response, the BBC issued an apology for not informing her of the nature of the interview, but claimed they had designed the program to offer balanced perspectives.(cite to Cain 2016) (Should this go in controversies, maybe a topic about politics, or just stay here? Other info Pearce says she is a permanent resident of the US with Nigerian nationality. Cain says she was an enthusiastic supporter of Hilary Clinton.)

old_content: '''Aloysius Harry Simmons''' (May 22, 1902 – May 26, 1956), born '''Alois Szymanski''',<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/s/simmoal01.shtml Al Simmons] at baseball-reference.com, accessed January 19, 2011.</ref> was an American professional [[baseball]] player. Nicknamed "'''Bucketfoot Al'''", he played for two decades in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) as an [[outfielder]] and had his best years with [[Connie Mack]]'s [[Philadelphia Athletics]] during the late 1920s and early 1930s, winning two [[World Series]] with Philadelphia. Simmons also played for the [[Chicago White Sox]], [[Detroit Tigers]], [[Washington Senators (1901–60)|Washington Senators]], [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]], [[Cincinnati Reds]] and [[Boston Red Sox]]. After his playing career ended, Simmons served as a coach for the Athletics and [[Cleveland Indians]]. A career .334 hitter, Simmons was inducted into the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in 1953.

old_content: While the ""Astros"" were dealing away their 1986 championship parts, they were grooming young players in the process, such as [[Ken Caminiti]] and [[Craig Biggio]]. Many people consider the best trade the ""Astros"" ever made to be their deal for [[Jeff Bagwell]] at the trading deadline in 1990. The [[Boston Red Sox]], in a tight race for the [[American League East]] title, needed relief pitching help. The ""Astros"" gave the Red Sox journeyman [[Larry Andersen]] in exchange for minor-leaguer Bagwell, who would win the 1990 [[Eastern League (1938–2020)|Eastern League]] MVP award for the AA [[New Britain Red Sox]]. With [[Mo Vaughn]] in their system, the Red Sox reasoned that Bagwell was expendable, and while Andersen did help the Red Sox to the divisional title, Bagwell went on to become the ""Astros""' all-time home run leader and, in most people's minds, the second best overall player in ""Astros"" history, behind the great Craig Biggio. The trade was so lopsided that it appears on virtually any list of the best/worst trades in MLB history, and "Larry Andersen" became a popular phrase in Boston to describe the futility of the Red Sox front office during the 86-year "[[Curse of the Bambino]]". However, after the 1991 season, the ""Astros"" made one of the worst trades in franchise history, sending speedy outfielder [[Kenny Lofton]] to the [[Cleveland Indians]] for catcher [[Eddie Taubensee]]. Lofton would prove to be one of the best center fielders of the 1990s, earning five AL stolen base titles, six All-Star appearances, and four Gold Gloves.

The trade was so lopsided that it appears on virtually any list of the best/worst trades in MLB history, and Larry Andersen became a popular phrase in Boston to describe the futility of the Red Sox front office during the 86-year "[[Curse of the Bambino]]". old_content: '''Acqui-hiring''' (a [[portmanteau]] of "acquisition" and "hiring") is the [[Mergers and acquisitions|acquisition]] of [[startup]]s or other small companies primarily to acquire [[human capital]].{{sfn|Chatterji|Patro | 2014|p=395}}{{sfn|Gala | Mueller|2024|p=1431}} In acqui-hiring, the company's product is of secondary interest and is often killed shortly after the acquisition.{{sfn|Gala | Mueller|2024|p=1431}}
new_content: '''Acqui-hiring''' (a [[portmanteau]] of "acquisition" and "hiring") is the [[Mergers and acquisitions|acquisition]] of [[startup]]s or other small companies primarily to acquire [[human capital]].{{sfn|Chatterji|Patro | 2014|p=395}}{{sfn|Gala | Mueller|2024|p=1431}} In acqui-hiring, the company's product is of at most secondary interest and is often killed shortly after the acquisition.

old_content: The exclave is on the [[Fujairah]]–[[Khor Fakkan]] road, which is mostly in the Emirate of Sharjah, and covers approximately {{cvt|75|km²}}. old_content: Akhtar Abdur Rahman was born on 11 June 1924 in [[Peshawar]], to a [[Kakazai]] [[Pashtuns|Pashtun]] family.<ref name=express>{{Cite web |last=Rahi |first=Arwin |date=2020-02-25 |title=Why Afghanistan should leave Pakistani Pashtuns alone |url=https://blogs.tribune.com.pk/story/94157/why-afghanistan-should-leave-pakistani-pashtuns-alone/ |archive-date=3 May 2020 |access-date=2020-06-26 |website=The Express Tribune |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200503132315/https://blogs.tribune.com.pk/story/94157/why-afghanistan-should-leave-pakistani-pashtuns-alone/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="The Nation, 2010">{{cite news|last=Staff report|title=General Akhtar Abdul Rehman (Shaheed)|url=http://www.nation.com.pk/pakistan-news-newspaper-daily-english-online/columns/17-Aug-2010/General-Akhtar-Abdul-Rehman-Shaheed|access-date=13 September 2012|newspaper=The Nation|date=17 August 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130428031114/http://www.nation.com.pk/pakistan-news-newspaper-daily-english-online/columns/17-Aug-2010/General-Akhtar-Abdul-Rehman-Shaheed|archive-date=28 April 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="PKKH, 2012">{{cite news|last=Shah, Mariam|title=An Unsung Hero of Modern History: Gen Akhtar Abdur Rehman|url=http://www.pakistankakhudahafiz.com/archive/2012/08/17/an-unsung-hero-of-modern-history-gen-akhtar-abur-rehman/|access-date=24 June 2016|newspaper=PKKH|date=12 August 2012|archive-date=26 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926191336/http://www.pakistankakhudahafiz.com/archive/2012/08/17/an-unsung-hero-of-modern-history-gen-akhtar-abur-rehman/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Akhtar's father, Abdur Rahman Khan, was a doctor at a government hospital over here. <ref name="tribune.com.pk"/> He lost his father at the tender age of four and was raised by his mother, after the family moved to [[East Punjab]] in British India. He studied at the [[Bishop Cotton School (Shimla)|Bishop Cotton School, Shimla]] in [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[India]], <ref>{{Cite web |last=Ghuman |first=Jagmeet Y. |date=2009-10-07 |title=Bishop Cotton School Celebrates Sesquicentennial Amidst Much Fanfare |url=https://hillpost.in/2009/10/bishop-cotton-school-celebrates-sesquicentennial-amidst-much-fanfare/16485/ |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=Hill Post |language=en-US}}</ref> before enrolling himself in the [[Government College University (Faisalabad)]] in 1941, subsequently earning a bachelor's degree in [[Science]] and [[Statistics]]<ref name="The Nation, 2010" /> in 1945, followed by a [[Master of Science]] in [[Economics]] in 1947.<ref name="The News International, 2012">{{cite news|last=Khan|first=Salman|title=General Akhtar Abdul Rahman Shaheed (1924–1988)|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-2-126934-General-Akhtar-Abdul-Rahman-Shaheed-%281924-1988%29|access-date=13 September 2012|newspaper=The News International|date=17 August 2012}}</ref>

old_content: It is believed that the Niquiranos were the first people to dwell in the land of Masaya (the Chorotegas had also inhabited these areas).<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Indigenous People of Mesoamerica and Central America|last=Carmack|first=Robert|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2017|isbn=9781498558976|pages=81–83}}</ref> There is evidence of their settlements in small towns like [[Nindirí, Masaya|Nindiri]], Niquinohomo and Monimbó from before the Spanish Conquest. One of the city's principle neighborhoods is Monimbó (which in Spanish means "close to the water") and is located very close to the lagoon. There is documented evidence that in the 6th century, Monimbó had a population of about 150 tributaries.

old_content: [[Chris Cester]] addressed the media speculation in an interview with with Pop in ''Uptown Magazine'',<ref name="uptownmag.com">[http://www.uptownmag.com/2009-10-15/page4696.aspx] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091020160333/http://www.uptownmag.com/2009-10-15/page4696.aspx|date=20 October 2009}}</ref> stating: "It's funny because I asked him point blank about that. He said I was crazy. He said that when he and [[David Bowie]] were writing '[[Lust for Life (album)|Lust for Life]]', they were ripping off Motown's beat. It's funny that he said that to me because we also thought we were ripping off Motown more than 'Lust for Life'. To be honest with you that kind of annoyed me a lot, because I always thought it was really lazy. People just go, well 'Lust for Life' is more well-known so that's what they go for, but if you listen to a song like 'You Can't Hurry Love' (The Supremes) I think you'll find it's closer to 'Are You Gonna Be My Girl' than 'Lust for Life' ever was. old_content: In his third start, on May 11, 2010, Ely was credited with his first win, allowing two runs, six hits and no walks and striking out six in six innings against the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]]. Ely was credited with his second win a week later against the [[Houston Astros]]. Ely threw 7 innings, allowing 5 hits and only 2 runs. He struck out 8 and walked no batters. Ely was the first Dodger to do so since [[Sandy Koufax]].  After winning his third straight decision against the [[Detroit Tigers]] on May 22, 2010, Dodgers Manager [[Joe Torre]] said, "He's certainly, as [[Yogi Berra|Yogi]] would say, making himself necessary."<ref>{{cite news|author=Baxter Holmes|title=John Ely keeps solidifying spot on Dodgers: Rookie pitcher comes up with another solid effort in win against Detroit Tigers|date=2010-05-22|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/may/22/sports/la-sp-dodgers-fyi-20100523}}</ref>

old_content: ''Kanrin Maru'', as a screw-driven steam warship, represented a new technological advance in warship design which had been introduced in the West only ten years earlier with {{HMS|Rattler|1843}}. The ship was built by [[Fop Smit]]'s in [[Kinderdijk]], the Netherlands later known as [[L. Smit en Zoon]]. The virtually identical screw-steamship with schooner-rig ''Bali'' of the Dutch navy was also built here in 1856. She allowed Japan to get its first experience with some of the newest advances in ship design.<ref>[[Hendrik Caspar Romberg]]'s account of the ''Sangoku-maru'' is a scant record of the brief attempt by the Tokugawa shogunate to create a sea-going vessel in the 1780s.  The ship sank; and the tentative project was abandoned when the political climate in Edo shifted. See [[Timon Screech]]. (2006). {{Google books|BLzQA7cpr7wC|''Secret Memoirs of the Shoguns: Isaac Titsingh and Japan, 1779-1822,'' pp. 48-49.|page=48}}</ref>
new_content: ''Kanrin Maru'', as a screw-driven steam warship, represented a new technological advance in warship design which had been introduced in the West only ten years earlier with {{HMS|Rattler|1843}}. old_content: '''Mark Barnes''' is an American attorney serving as a partner in the [[Ropes & Gray]] health care and life sciences practice based in Boston.  He was director of policy for the New York State Department of Health AIDS Institute, and associate commissioner for medical and legal policy for the [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|New York City Department of Health]] under the mayoralty of [[David Dinkins]].  He worked on the [[Health care reform|National Health Care Reform Task Force]] in the [[Clinton Administration]]. He also has served as executive vice president of [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]] and founded and directed the [[Harvard University]] HIV/AIDS treatment programs in Africa. His current legal and advocacy work includes a focus on the fields of research compliance, the ethics and regulation of clinical trials, medical privacy, and "big data" research.  He is past president of the [[New York State Bar Association]]'s [[Public health law|Health Law]] Section.

old_content: Bukha, which is 0 feet (0 meters) above sea level, has a subtropical desert climate (BWh). The district's average annual temperature is -1.44% lower than Oman's averages at 27.76oC (81.97oF). 12.47 millimeters (0.49 inches) of precipitation fall on Bukha yearly, and there are 21.67 wet days (5.94% of the time).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bukha, Musandam, OM Climate Zone, Monthly Averages, Historical Weather Data |url=https://tcktcktck.org/oman/musandam/bukha |access-date=2023-08-13 |website=tcktcktck.org}}</ref>A normal day in Bukha in April will have an average temperature of 76°F (24°C), with a high of 86°F (30°C).July is the hottest month, with daily highs of 98°F (37°C) and lows of 88°F (31°C). January is the coldest month of the year, with highs of 73°F (23°C) and lows of 67°F (19°C) on most days.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bukha, Oman weather in April: average temperature & climate |url=https://wanderlog.com/weather/86565/4/bukha-weather-in-april |access-date=2023-08-13 |website=Wanderlog}}</ref>

old_content: Between the 5th and 6th centuries the Langobards built a castle on the rock where the ''Castello Scaligero'' stands today. It was destroyed in 590 by the [[Franks]]. They subsequently rebuilt it and in 806 hosted King [[Pepin of Italy|Pepin]]. After attacks by [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]] the castle became part of the holdings of the [[Bishop of Verona]]. In 1277, the castle fell to [[Alberto I della Scala|Alberto della Scala]] and until 1387 remained in the possession of the [[della Scala]] family, whose name it still bears. Over the next centuries, castle and town were ruled in succession by the [[Visconti of Milan]] (until 1403) and the [[Republic of Venice]] (1405-1797). The control of Venice was only interrupted by a brief period (1506–16), when the area was under Imperial rule during the reign of [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Maximilian I]].<ref name="Tourist3"/>

old_content: The name of the city of Osh derives from the river [[Vakhsh (river)|Vakhsh]], anthropomorphised there as a water goddess of the same name, who was worshipped (in tandem with Atash, the sacred fire) in a Zoroastrian shrine or fire temple situated in the Eagle Cave of the ancient sacred mountain [[Sulayman Mountain|Sulaiman-Too]]. The river Vakhsh itself, known also as Surkhob  or Kyzyl-Suu ( Turkic: “red water”) is a tributary of the Amu Darya, the course of the Vakhsh lying to the South of the Fergana valley, rising as it does near the village of [[Sary-Tash]] and flowing southwest to join the Amu Darya not far from [[Nizhny Pyandzh]].<ref>A little history of the city of Osh https://osh-hospital.narod.ru/history_osh.htm; Live the East. info@centralasia-travel.com; Retrieved 17/4/2024.</ref>
new_content: The name of the city of Osh derives from the river [[Vakhsh (river)|Vakhsh]], anthropomorphised there as a water goddess of the same name, who was worshipped (in tandem with Atash, the sacred fire) in a Zoroastrian shrine or fire temple situated in the Eagle Cave of the ancient sacred mountain [[Sulayman Mountain|Sulaiman-Too]]. The river Vakhsh itself, known also as Surkhob  or Kyzyl-Suu ( Turkic: “red water”) is a tributary of the Amu Darya, the course of the Vakhsh lying to the South of the Fergana valley, rising as it does near the village of [[Sary-Tash]] and flowing southwest to join the Amu Darya not far from [[Panj]].<ref>A little history of the city of Osh https://osh-hospital.narod.ru/history_osh.htm; Live the East. info@centralasia-travel.com; Retrieved 17/4/2024.</ref>

old_content: The place was originally named Muithauard c.1200, Moneward 1203. Two different etymologies are given for the name. In the first it is asserted that the name is derived from the Gaelic ''magh'' + ''bard''; "Plain of the bards".<ref name="Gordon">{{Cite book|title=Chronicles of Strathearn|chapter=The Plain of the Bards|author=Gordon, Arthur|location=Crieff, Scotland|publisher=David Philips|year=1896|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/26342/26342-h/26342-h.htm#chap09}}</ref> (Locals pronounce it as Mon ee vaird). Under this view, the name of the nearby village of Monzie is unrelated except to render the pronunciation of the first syllable "Monz" as "Mon" in linguistic sympathy.  In the second etymology, Monzievaird comes from ''magh'' "plain" plus ''edha''' the [[genitive case]] of ''edh'' (''iodh'') "corn" plus the [[Old Saxon|Saxon]] ''vaird'' or "ward" meaning "enclosure", rendering the total as "place where corn is stored".<ref name="Lindsay">{{Cite book|editor1=Lindsay, William Alexander |editor2=Dowden, John |editor3=Thomson, John Maitland |year=1908|title=Charters of the Abbey of Inchaffray|chapter=Appendix III: Notes on the Place-names in the Inchaffray Charters|series=Publications of the Scottish History Society, volume 56|location=Edinburgh, Scotland|publisher=Scottish History Society|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=2QUdAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA324 324]}}</ref> Under this view the village name of Monzie has the same origin<ref name="Lindsay" /> as does the name of the nearby castle, Monzie Castle.<ref>{{GEOnet2|32FA88188A6C3774E0440003BA962ED3|Monzie Castle (Approved)}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> Regardless of origin it gave its name to the nearby [[Loch Monzievaird]].

old_content: The [[DC Universe (franchise)|DC Universe]] (DCU) is an American [[media franchise]] and [[Shared universe|shared]] [[fictional universe]] that is the setting of [[superhero film]]s and [[Superhero fiction#Live-action television series|television series]] produced by [[DC Studios]], based on characters that appear in [[DC Comics]] publications. DC Studios developed the DCU as a "[[Reboot (fiction)|soft reboot]]" of the prior DC Comics-based franchise the [[DC Extended Universe]] (DCEU) that retains certain cast members of the DCEU while replacing others. No actor would be playing multiple characters, with DC Studios co-CEOs [[James Gunn]] and [[Peter Safran]] expecting the same actors to play characters across mediums, including animation. The DCU's first slate of content is Chapter One: Gods and Monsters, which includes five feature films: ''[[Superman (2025 film)|Superman]]'' (2025), ''[[The Authority (film)|The Authority]]'', ''[[The Brave and the Bold (film)|The Brave and the Bold]]'', ''[[Supergirl: Woman of Tomorrow]]'', and ''[[Swamp Thing (upcoming film)|Swamp Thing]]'', and five series: the animated ''[[Creature Commandos (TV series)|Creature Commandos]]'' (2024), ''[[Waller (TV series)|Waller]]'' (2024), ''[[Lanterns (TV series)|Lanterns]]'', ''[[Paradise Lost (upcoming TV series)|Paradise Lost]]'', ''[[Booster Gold (TV series)|Booster Gold]]'', and the [[Peacemaker season 2|second season]] of ''[[Peacemaker (TV series)|Peacemaker]]''. An [[untitled Arkham series]] is also in development for the DCU. As the franchise will be composed of films and series adapted from a variety of DC Comics properties, there will be multiple lead actors.

old_content: Several of the triumphal arches were designed by a carpenter Stephen Harrison, and illustrated in a festival book commemorating the [[Royal entry]], engraved by William Kip.<ref>Janette Dillon, ''The Language of Space in Court Performance, 1400–1625'' (Cambridge, 2010), pp. 23–24.</ref> [[Thomas Dekker (writer)|Thomas Dekker]] wrote ''The Magnificent Entertainment'', and collaborated with [[Ben Jonson]] to produce on entertainments on the day.<ref>See external links: Anne Lancashire, 'Dekker's Accession Pageant for James I', ''Early Theatre'', 12:1 (2009), pp. 39–50: John Gough Nichols, ''London Pageants'' (London, 1831), pp. 59–63.</ref> According to Dekker, "the streets seemed to be paved with men; stalls instead of rich wares were set out with children; open casements filled up with women".<ref>Gary Taylor & John Lavagnino, ''Thomas Middleton: The Collected Works'' (Oxford, 2007), p. 232.</ref>

old_content: '''Antônio Wilson Vieira Honório''' (11 June 1943 – 11 March 2019), nicknamed '''Coutinho''', was a Brazilian coach and [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[Santos Futebol Clube]], where he was a teammate and one of the best partners of [[Pelé]], and became a member of the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]] that won the [[1962 FIFA World Cup]]. He is considered one of the greatest strikers in the history of Brazilian football with 368 goals in 457 matches<ref name="Morre Coutinho, ex-atacante de Santos e seleção brasileira">{{cite web|title=Morre Coutinho, ex-atacante de Santos e seleção brasileira|url=https://esporte.uol.com.br/futebol/ultimas-noticias/2019/03/11/morre-coutinho-ex-atacante-do-santos.htm|website=[[Universo Online|UOL]]|access-date=12 March 2019|language=pt}}</ref><ref name="Coutinho, ídolo do Santos e campeão mundial pelo Brasil, morre aos 75 anos"/> even though he prematurely ended his football career before the age of 30 due to knee problems. His main virtues as a striker were coldness and precision in finishing, the ability to dribble in tight spaces and a keen awareness of team play, which allowed him to make several one-two passes with Pelé in the midst of opponent defenses. In Brazil, during his time as a player, he received the nickname "genius of the small area" many years before other great Brazilian striker [[Romario]]. Pelé himself declares that "Coutinho, within the area, was better than me. His coldness was something supernatural".

old_content: '''Endothelial stem cells''' ('''ESCs''') are one of three types of [[stem cells]] found in [[bone marrow]]. They are [[multipotent]], which describes the ability to give rise to many cell types, whereas a [[pluripotent]] stem cell can give rise to all types. ESCs have the characteristic properties of a stem cell: [[stem cell self-renewal|self-renewal]] and differentiation. These parent stem cells, ESCs, give rise to [[progenitor]] cells, which are intermediate stem cells that lose potency. Progenitor stem cells are committed to differentiating along a particular cell developmental pathway. ESCs will eventually produce [[endothelial cells]] (ECs), which create the thin-walled [[endothelium]] that lines the inner surface of [[blood vessels]] and [[lymphatic vessels]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fang S, Wei J, Pentinmikko N, Leinonen H, Salven P | title = Generation of functional blood vessels from a single c-kit+ adult vascular endothelial stem cell | journal = PLOS Biology | volume = 10 | issue = 10 | pages = e1001407 | date = 2012-10-16 | pmid = 23091420 | pmc = 3473016 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.1001407 | veditors = Goodell MA | doi-access = free }}</ref> The blood vessels include things such as [[arteries]] and veins. Endothelial cells can be found throughout the whole vascular system and they also play a vital role in the movement of white blood cells<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last1=Alberts|first1=Bruce|last2=Johnson|first2=Alexander|last3=Lewis|first3=Julian|last4=Raff|first4=Martin|last5=Roberts|first5=Keith|last6=Walter|first6=Peter|date=2002|title=Blood Vessels and Endothelial Cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK26848/|journal=Molecular Biology of the Cell. 4th Edition|language=en}}</ref>

old_content: England was divided into ealdormanries led by [[ealdormen]] (later [[earl]]s) appointed by the king. An ealdormanry was divided into [[shire]]s. The ealdorman enforced royal orders, presided over the shire court, and led the local [[fyrd]] (army). A [[sheriff]] administered each shire as the ealdorman's deputy. Shires were divided into administrative units called [[Hundred (county division)|hundreds]].
